<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MissingTeen-Agers 1stLd-Writethru a0645 11-16 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missing Teen-Agers, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0645,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disappearance of Four Youths Remains a Mystery</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 1st graf and INSERTS one graf after 6th graf ``Stamm
said' to UPDATE with reward doubled to $20,000.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EAST LYME, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The disappearance of four young people
over the weekend still had police baffled four days later, and the
youths' parents offered a $20,000 reward Wednesday for information
in the case.
   ``We don't have indication of foul play. But the longer time goes
on, the more unusual the situation and the less likely it is the
kids are out on a lark,'' said state police spokeswoman Marcy Stamm.
``You'd think one of the kids would have called by now.''
   State police have issued a nationwide alert for the car the four
were last seen in and distributed a missing persons' flier
nationally.
   The missing friends, three 19-year-old women and a 20-year-old
man, were last seen Saturday night at an apartment near Southern
Connecticut State University in New Haven.
   The missing teen-agers are: Jill Sawyer, a student at the
University of Rhode Island; Christy Stevens, a student at Mohegan
Community College in Norwich; Michael Gallo, a student at Southern
Connecticut; and Laura Lagrotteria, who works at the Crystal Mall in
Waterford.
   Stamm said the four had about $50 among them and no change of
clothes. She said extensive interviews with friends and family gave
no indication the group had planned to run away.
   Their parents, who reported them missing Sunday night, announced
through state police a $10,000 reward and doubled it later Wednesday.
   Family and friends described the four 1987 graduates of East Lyme
High School as responsible adults, not likely to take off without
telling anyone.
   Stevens' father, James O. Stevens, said the three women had been
close friends since grade school. He said although they knew Gallo,
they had not seen him much until recently.
   ``If Christy was going to come in later than 2 a.m., we would
always get a call telling us she would be late,'' Stevens said.
   A state police airplane traced all possible routes the four could
have taken from East Lyme to New Haven but turned up no sign of
Stevens' car.
</TEXT>
