<1ST_LINE>r i PM-DalaiLama     11-16 0815</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dalai Lama,0836</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dalai Lama Seeks Compromise Over Independence to Preserve Tibet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dalai Lama, spiritual and temporal
leader of Tibetans, says time is running out for preserving his
people's culture and the only way to save it may be a compromise
with China over independence.
   The man revered as a god-king by his people said in an interview
with The Associated Press that ``I am not insisting we should be an
independent country.''
   Instead, he said, he was seeking ``a middle way'' that would
preserve the culture he fears will vanish if China continues to rule
Tibet for another 10 or 15 years.
   The remarks sounded conciliatory, but the Dalai Lama insisted in
the interview Tuesday they were not a modification of a proposal he
made five months ago in which China would keep troops on Tibetan
soil and handle Tibet's foreign policy.
   Sitting in a suite at New Delhi's luxury Ashoka Hotel during a
trip to visit Tibetan refugees, the Dalai Lama repeatedly expressed
worries that time was running out to save his homeland.
   It was these concerns that prompted his June 15 proposal in
Strasbourg, France, where the European Parliament was meeting. In
that proposal, his biggest concession since China invaded Tibet in
1949 and annexed it a year later, he suggested Tibet become ``a
self-governing democratic political entity ... in association with
China.''
   The proposal drew criticism from Tibetan exiles around the world
and prompted a spate of protest letters to the Dalai Lama's own
exile headquarters in Dharmsala, a Himalayan foothills town 300
miles north of New Delhi.
   China rejected the proposal, saying it failed to relinquish the
concept of Tibetan independence, but said it is willing to talk to
the Dalai Lama.
   ``In a way, sad, but realistically, in order to save Tibetan
culture, Tibetan people, and find some kind of satisfaction for
them, as a free spokesman for Tibetan people, I make a suggestion or
proposal on a middle way,'' the Dalai Lama said in the interview.
   ``In the northeast part of Tibet, my birthplace area, already in
that part of Tibet, Tibetans (are) becoming insignificant, a small
minority,'' said the bespectacled Buddhist holy man.
   He said that according to Chinese statistics, the Tibetan
population in the area where he was born is 800,000 and the Chinese
population about 3 million.
   The Dalai Lama, whose name means Ocean of Wisdom, was born 53
years ago and named Tenzin Gyatso, one of seven children of a farmer
in the poor village of Tagtser. Tagtser now lies in China, outside
what Beijing has designated the Tibetan Autonomous Region.
   The creation of the region, shrinking the area Tibetans consider
Tibet, is the main reason why the Dalai Lama says there are 6
million Tibetans and China says there are 2 million. An influx of
Chinese settlers into the area, including the Tibetan capital of
Lhasa, has further diluted the once-homogenous Tibetan population.
   It also has spawned riots, such as the ones in Lhasa in October
1987 and again in March when cars were set afire, a police station
burned, and at least 35 Tibetans and three Chinese policemen killed.
   The Dalai Lama, who fled to India in 1959 after an unsuccessful
uprising, said he thought non-violent tactics would be more
successful in attaining Tibetan control over internal Tibetan
affairs, such as education, health services, industry, mining and
construction of houses.
   At last, he said, the Chinese are finally recognizing Tibet as a
place with a cultural identity of its own.
   As evidence, he cited what he said was the establishment of a
center for Tibetan studies in Beijing and the willingness of Chinese
officials to meet a Tibetan delegation in Geneva in January. The
Dalai Lama said he did not plan to take part in any Geneva talks, at
least at the initial stage.
   Asked whether his proposals for Tibet could be construed as
autonomy within the Chinese nation, the maroon-and-gold robed Dalai
Lama said pensively: ``Autonomy. That's a nice word.''
   But his secretary for the past 15 years, Tenzin Geyche Tethong,
who holds Cabinet rank in the Tibetan government-in-exile,
interjected: ``We don't use the word autonomy.''
   After the interview, Tethong said: ``It's something that at this
point His Holiness does not want to be very specific about.''
   The Dalai Lama, whose status as god-king of the Tibetans began in
1940 when he was a 4-year-old child, travels with a retinue of
advisers, aides and bodyguards.
   His holy status was conferred when Buddhist monks decided he was
the 14th incarnation of the physical manifestation of the Buddhist
Lord of Compassion, Avalokitesvara. This decision was made when the
small boy was silently presented with a host of articles, ignored
most of them but picked out the only three that had belonged to the
13th Dalai Lama, who died in 1933.
</TEXT>
