<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 0957EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-TreasonTrial     11-16 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Treason Trial,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says Anti-Apartheid Coalition Was Directed By ANC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's largest
anti-apartheid group operated under the guidance of the outlawed
African National Congress, a judge said today as a three-year
treason trial neared its end.
   The 19 black activists on trial include senior leaders of the
United Democratic Front, a now-banned coalition formed in 1983 to
mobilize opposition to apartheid and white-minority domination. The
defendants have denied allegations that they encouraged
anti-government violence.
   Supreme Court Justice Kees van Dijkhorst will issue his verdict
within the next few days after he finishes reading aloud in court a
1,521-page summary of the trial. He began the process Tuesday, when
he revoked the bail of eight of the defendants.
   In the section of the summary read today, van Dijkhorst said he
agreed with prosecutors that the United Democratic Front was
supported and directed by the ANC, the country's main
anti-government guerrilla movement.
   The front has maintained it endorsed the African National
Congress' political goals, such as a one-person, one-vote system,
but did not approve of the use of violence.
   ``To side wholeheartedly with the ANC _ and then to say that the
UDF is neutral _ is to twist that word out of joint,'' van Dijkhorst
said.
   He said the group's leaders had participated in rallies where
crowds chanted in support of the ANC and sang ``revolutionary''
songs.
   A 1985 United Democratic Front statement calling for ``the
collapse of the system'' was ``an unequivocal declaration of war on
the state,'' the judge said.
   The three most prominent defendants at the trial are senior front
leaders who have been denied bail throughout the trial and have
spent 40 months in jail: Popo Molefe, 36, who was the group's
national secretary; Terror Lekota, 40, its publicity secretary, and
Moses Chikane, 40, secretary of the Transvaal Province branch.
   All 19 defendants have pleaded innocent to charges of treason,
terrorism, murder and subversion related to a central allegation
that the front and its affiliates sought to promote violence to make
South Africa ungovernable.
   The charges arise from violence and mob killings in black
townships south of Johannesburg in September 1984, the start of two
years of nationwide unrest in which more than 2,500 people were
killed.
   Treason and murder carry a maximum penalty of death.
   Van Dijkhorst has presided over the non-jury trial since its
start in June 1985 and has sole responsibility for the verdict and
sentencing.
   Founded in 1983, the United Democratic Front became the largest
and in many ways the most potent opposition group in South Africa's
history, encompassing more than 600 affiliated groups with about 2
million members. In February it was banned from any activities.
   The trial, conducted for many months in the town of Delmas before
being shifted to Pretoria, originally had 22 defendants. Three men
were acquitted in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
