<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Kerry-Quayle     11-16 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kerry-Quayle,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kerry Ruffles Feathers With Questionable Quayle Joke</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYNN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. John Kerry apologized today for a telling
a joke about Dan Quayle that offended some.
   At a businessmen's breakfast Tuesday, Kerry responded to a
question about the vice president-elect's qualifications by saying
``the Secret Service is under orders that if Bush is shot, to shoot
Quayle,'' The Boston Herald reported.
   The Massachusetts Democrat said in a statement today: ``I
shouldn't have repeated the story. It was inappropriate and I
apologize for doing so.'' Through spokesman Larry Carpman, Kerry
said he had been quoting a joke that was going around the capital.
   The breakfast, sponsored by an East Lynn bank, drew about 120
businessmen, bankers, lawyers and other professionals. The newspaper
said some audience members, which it did not quote by name,
complained about Kerry's remark.
   Carpman said Kerry recalled that he had followed his comment to
the group with a disclaimer: ``I don't mean that. I'm just relating
what some people are saying in Washington.''
   Jeff Nesbit, an aide to the Indiana senator, said, ``I personally
don't think the health of the president or vice president is
anything to joke about.''
