<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1031EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArmsControl 1stLd-Writethru a0544 11-16 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Control, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0544,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kampelman: Both Sides Studying Treaty Draft</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Kampelman throughout</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Soviet arms negotiators have made ``a
tremendous amount of progress'' in the latest four-month round of
talks on a long-range nuclear arms reduction treaty, the Reagan
administration's chief negotiator said today.
   The 10th round of talks adjourned in Geneva on Tuesday with many
items still unresolved in efforts to draft a treaty to cut
long-range nuclear forces in half, said U.S. negotiator Max
Kampelman.
   But, he added, ``there was a tremendous amount of progress'' in
the latest round of talks.
   On Tuesday, Soviet officials said they hoped for ``new progress''
in the Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty, or START, talks under the
George Bush administration.
   ``We have even a joint draft of this treaty and it's now more
than 300 pages long,'' Kampelman said on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show.
   ``We're exchanging these joint draft texts. They're very
important,'' said Kampelman, who just returned from the talks.
``We'll all study them during the course of this break and continue
the progress that we have made in resolving a great many of the
differences.''
   He declined to discuss whether he would continue to lead the
talks after President-elect George Bush takes office Jan. 20, but
said new approaches could be useful and ``there are no indispensable
people in any process.''
   Kampelman said negotiators on both sides hope to ``continue the
progress that we have made in resolving a great many of the
differences.''
   ``Even though a great many issues still remain to be resolved, I
am impressed with how many agreements we already have,'' Kampelman
said.
   Bush has been to Geneva and met with both sides in the talks,
which have been going on for nearly four years.
   ``We're engaged in something that's never been done before,''
Kampelman said, ``and we're doing it well, we're doing it slowly,
we're doing it carefully, because these are important issues of
national security.''
   Kampelman said he has no indication of what might occur at the
planned December meeting with Bush, President Reagan and Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
   Kampelman was asked what the U.S. response would be to any
surprise move by Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev during a meeting
with President Reagan and Bush in December. ``We'd welcome any kind
of move by the Soviets which is constructive,'' he said. ``There are
many areas they have to move on. I think they know that, and if Mr.
Gorbachev wants to do so, we would welcome it.''
   On Tuesday in Geneva, Kampelman said he assured the Soviets that
Bush would maintain continuity in the talks.
   The latest round of talks began July 12, involving both START and
space defense issues. The talks, which began in March 1985, produced
the U.S.-Soviet agreement to scrap all intermediate-range nuclear
missiles.
   U.S. negotiator Read S. Hanmer said Wednesday that differences
were narrowed on air-launched cruise missiles and on monitoring
mobile intercontinental ballistic missiles if they are included in
the treaty. But he said a longstanding disagreement remains over the
range an air-launched cruise missile must have to be included in the
treaty.
   Kampelman said no progress was made on sea-launched cruise
missiles, which Moscow wants to limit.
   He also said Reagan's Strategic Defense Initiative program for
space-based missile defenses, which the Soviets oppose, remains a
``serious objective'' and is not expected to be a bargaining chip
under Bush.
   The program, known as Star Wars, has been a stumbling block since
the talks began.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
