<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   11-16 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0513,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede JERUSALEM</HEAD>
<HEAD>Two Youths Reported Shot; Nearly 1 Million Arabs Under Curfew</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with violence reported. Changes byline.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAZA CITY, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army today confined
nearly 900,000 Palestinians to their homes, but Palestinian youths
defied the orders and hurled stones at soldiers. Two teen-agers were
reported shot.
   In the Gaza Strip, a curfew was in effect for a sixth straight
day. On Tuesday, some Arabs celebrated the Palestinian declaration
of independence in the streets with songs and fireworks. It is the
longest the seaside area has been shut by authorities since the 1967
Middle East war.
   Hundreds of soldiers patrolled in jeeps, trucks with plastic
shields to protect them from stones, and armored vehicles equipped
with machines to spray gravel at rioters.
   In the West Bank, soldiers carried out raids to prevent violence,
a military spokeswoman said. She said arrests were made, but she
would not say how many.
   In the West Bank town of Bethlehem, fireworks continued into the
morning and dozens of outlawed Palestinian flags were hung on walls
and utility poles. Graffiti read ``Congratulations to our people _
the state is born.''
   Two teen-agers were shot by soldiers in Gaza City, apparently
after violating curfew orders, officials at Ahli Arab Hospital said.
One was a 14-year-old shot in the right arm and the other a
15-year-old wounded in the leg, they said.
   A military spokeswoman said there were incidents of
stone-throwing in the city but no injuries. Israel radio said the
closure order was issued after soldiers caught two youths and
accused them of inciting other youngsters to throw stones.
   Smoke from burning tires rose above the city. At least five tires
were seen aflame in a two-hour, army-conducted tour for reporters.
Stones were thrown at one journalists' car in a convoy guided by two
army jeeps.
   Soldiers banged on the closed metal doors on one street where a
tire burned. They pulled out a middle-aged man and ordered him to
douse the tire with water and clear the debris from the roadway.
   As the soldiers shouted at the man, more than a dozen youths in a
nearby alley made V for victory signs for the benefit of
photographers.
   Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, armed forces chief of staff, said the
military will take whatever steps needed to keep the PLO declaration
of independence from fueling the 11-month Palestinian uprising
against Israeli rule in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. At
least 312 Arabs and 11 Israelis have been killed in the uprising.
There are 1.5 million Palestinians in the occupied areas.
   ``The Israel Defense Forces will keep as many troops in the area
as is needed. We will continue to keep the quiet by keeping people
under curfew as necessary,'' he said on Israel radio.
   The military said it filedcomplaints against three Israeli
journalists whom it accused of violating orders prohibiting
reporters from entering the West Bank on Tuesday, the day the
independence declaration was declared.
   The three were caught in Al-Ittihad hospital in Nablus, said the
military spokeswoman. One of them, Joel Greenberg of the Jerusalem
Post, said the reporters were not aware of the military order.
   In the Gaza Strip, 650,000 Palestinians were under curfew. The
army said curfews requiring people to stay in their homes also were
in effect in the West Bank towns of Tulkarem, Qalqilya, Nura Shams
and Shuweika, where 85,000 Arabs live. A reporter in Nablus said
soldiers put the city of 120,000 under curfew.
   The army declared Ramallah a closed military area, preventing
people from entering or leaving the West Bank city of 40,000.
</TEXT>
