<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1110EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HospitalKidnapping     11-16 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hospital Kidnapping,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baby Kidnap Suspect Was Desperate For A Boy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FREEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman accused of posing as a nurse and
kidnapping a newborn from a hospital was desperate to have a son and
had convinced many people that she was pregnant, police said.
   Acqunetta Smith, 32, of Hot Springs was arrested Monday in the
kidnapping of Christopher Michael Jones from Doctors Hospital on
Nov. 1. She pleaded innocent Tuesday.
   ``There is no doubt that she had planned this over a period of
time,'' Detective Vicki Flint said. ``She had made everyone believe
she was carrying a baby.''
   Ms. Smith, who is divorced, has at least three children of her
own, one a boy. But Capt. Bob H. Moore said she wanted a son with
her current boyfriend, Floyd Hannah.
   ``They were very much wanting to have a baby boy,'' Moore said.
``Everybody thought she was'' pregnant.
   The infant's mother, Annette Thomas-Jones, had handed her
3-day-old son to a woman posing as a nurse who came into her
hospital room saying the baby needed to be weighed.
   Officers acting on a tip found the baby Monday at the home of Ms.
Smith, who had worked as a nurse's aide. A $27,500 reward will go to
the caller, police said.
   Authorities said Christopher, who had been born six weeks
premature, was well taken care of during the two weeks he was
missing. During that time, they had expressed fear that he could die
because of his premature state.
   Christopher's parents took the infant home Tuesday to his two
sisters, ages 5 and 8.
   ``We're all well-rested,'' a smiling Mrs. Thomas-Jones said as
she left Doctors Hospital, cradling the boy. ``I slept like a baby
myself.'' Mrs. Thomas-Jones previously expressed forgiveness for the
kidnapper.
   Ms. Smith told officers that the boy, whom she called Floyd Jr.,
was born Nov. 4 at a hospital in Hot Springs, but could not provide
documentation, Mrs. Flint said.
   ``The girl almost had me convinced this was her baby,'' Mrs.
Flint said. ``She played it to the max. But when she let me hold the
baby, I just felt inside myself that it was the baby we were looking
for.''
   Mrs. Flint said Ms. Smith did not resist when the detective and
an FBI agent suggested they take the child to the medical center.
   ``She just kept repeating, `That's my baby,''' Mrs. Flint said.
   Ms. Smith was a nurse's aide at St. Joseph's Hospital until she
quit in September, saying she had problems with a pregnancy.
   She had a medical procedure known as a dilation and curettage in
July, but the reason wasn't known, police said. The procedure
removes matter from the uterus. For a pregnant woman, it amounts to
an abortion, but D and Cs also are done on women who are not
pregnant.
</TEXT>
