<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1110EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GandhiKillers     11-16 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gandhi Killers,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Vacates Stay on Execution of Gandhi Killers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today vacated a stay on
the execution of two Sikhs sentenced to death by hanging for the
1984 assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, the United News
of India reported.
   The action removed any legal bars to the execution of the two
Sikhs, who also have the right to petition President Ramaswamy
Venkataraman for mercy. One already has filed the petition.
   The news agency said a two-judge panel dismissed a request to
stay the execution pending resolution of a murder complaint filed by
one of the Sikhs in a magistrate's court. The panel earlier granted
a temporary stay while the petition was being heard.
   Satwant Singh, convicted for killing Mrs. Gandhi, has filed a
complaint against two policemen in the former prime minister's
security guard, claiming they shot at him and Beant Singh, another
Sikh involved in the assassination, after they were disarmed.
   Beant Singh received fatal injuries in the shootout and Satwant
Singh was arrested and charged after being treated for bullet wounds.
   The Singhs were not related. All Sikhs take the name ``Singh,''
which means ``lion'' in the Punjabi language, as a doctrine of the
faith.
   Beant Singh's maternal uncle, Kehar Singh, also was arrested and
convicted on charges of conspiracy. The death sentences against him
and Satwant Singh were delivered by a trial court and upheld by the
Delhi High Court and the Supreme Court.
   Satwant Singh's complaint against the policemen will be ruled on
Thursday.
   Mrs. Gandhi was shot and killed in her New Delhi residence on
Oct. 31, 1984, apparently in revenge for an army attack she ordered
four months previously on the Golden Temple in Amritsar, the holiest
Sikh shrine.
   The shrine, in the northern state of Punjab, was being used as a
base by militant Sikhs fighting for an independent homeland. At
least 1,200 people, most of them Sikhs, died in the army attack.
   Sikhs, known for their flowing beards and untrimmed hair, form
only 2 percent of India's 880 million people but are a majority in
Punjab.
   Radical Sikhs have been campaigning for a separate state since
1982, claiming the community was being discriminated against by
Hindus, who make up 80 percent of the population.
   This year, at least 2,275 people have been killed in Punjab by
the radicals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
