<DOCNO> AP881116-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1122EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w BC-Economy-Glance     11-16 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Economy-Glance,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Down, Inventories And Factory Use Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are economic reports issued
Wednesday by the government.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Trade Deficit</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's merchandise trade deficit shrank nearly $2 billion
to $10.5 billion in September as exports hit a record high. The 15
percent improvement came from an August deficit revised up from
$12.18 billion to $12.3 billion. Imports declined slightly in
September from the record high $39.8 billion posted the previous
month, the Commerce Department said.
   The dollar drifted lower on European and Canadian markets, but
trading was thin because West German markets were closed for a
national holiday. Stock and bond prices on New York markets also
edged lower in early trading.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Business Inventories</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories jumped 0.7 percent in September, the 21st
consecutive monthly gain, and sales remained virtually unchanged,
the Commerce Department said. Inventories on shelves and backlots
rose $5.5 billion to a seasonally adjusted $749.4 billion. Sales
fell a scant $35 million to $495.4 billion.
   The combination of rising inventories and flat sales is a sign of
economic weakness. If the trend continued, it could lead to fewer
orders from retailers, so they could sell off their backlog of
goods, and consequently to production cutbacks and layoffs at
manufacturing plants.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Factory Use</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The use of capacity at U.S. factories, mines and utilities rose
0.2 percentage points in October to 84.0 percent, the highest since
February 1980, the Federal Reserve Board said. The gain followed no
change in September, a 0.1 percentage point gain in August and a
sharp 0.7 percentage point rise in July.
   The overall rate is approaching the 85 percent threshold that
economists believe clearly signals a pickup in inflation.
   Capacity use has grown or held steady for eight consecutive
months, raising concern that factories will have trouble producing
enough goods to meet demand, leading to shortages and price
increases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
