<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1127EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AIDSTesting     11-16 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Testing,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Rejects AIDS Testing Regulations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Regulations limiting AIDS testing for insurance
were thrown out by Massachusetts' highest court today on grounds
that the state insurance commissioner lacked authority to issue the
rules.
   Authority to dictate such underwriting practices rests with the
Legislature, the Supreme Court said today in a unanimous ruling.
   Insurance Commissioner Roger Singer issued the regulations in
1987, making Massachusetts the second state, behind New York, to ban
by regulation health insurance testing for AIDS antibodies.
   Under the regulations, which never took effect, AIDS testing was
banned for all health insurance and group life and some disability
insurance.
   The Life Insurance Association of Massachusetts and several
insurance companies sued to block the regulations. In June, a
Superior Court judge ruled in favor of the insurance commissioner.
   The high court's ruling today focused only on the industry's
contention that Singer lacked authority to issue the regulations.
   The justices did not consider industry claims that the rules were
arbitrary and interfered with the rights of people not infected with
AIDS and the right of insurers not to enter into contracts.
   Singer claimed authority to issue the regulations under a 1924
law outlining his duties, but the court said it was doubtful the
Legislature intended that he be allowed to write regulations
dictating underwriting practices.
   ``We conclude that the commissioner had no authority, express or
implied, to adopt the regulations challenged in this case,'' Justice
Herbert P. Wilkins wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
