<HEAD>With PM-Reagan-Thatcher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Quayle Welcome at White House Any Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said today that Vice
President-elect Dan Quayle will be welcome at the White House any
time, even though he wasn't invited to tonight's state banquet for
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   Posing for photographers before a private meeting with Mrs.
Thatcher, Reagan was asked why Quayle had not been invited to the
gala dinner.
   ``You know, I don't get involved in the guest list there and I
don't know why, or whether this was some other engagement or not, so
I don't know the answer to that, but believe me, he will be welcome
any time,'' the president said.
   First Lady Nancy Reagan's press secretary, Elaine Crispen, said
earlier that the omission of Quayle was not intended as a slight to
the vice president-elect. She said Quayle, a Republican senator from
Indiana, had been invited to a state dinner in 1982 and his turn in
rotation among the 100 senators had not yet come up again.
   As vice president, Quayle will automatically be invited to all
state dinners, Mrs. Crispen said.
