<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1208EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Court-AIDSDecision     11-16 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Court-AIDS Decision,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Decision Upholds State Health Officials On AIDS Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YVETTE H. BLACKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York state health officials and gay
rights activists won a court battle to prevent AIDS from being
classified a communicable and sexually transmissible disease.
   Such a classification under the Public Health Law would have
required doctors to contact sexual partners of infected patients and
would have given local health officials power to quarantine AIDS
patients, officials said.
   Justice F. Warren Travers of New York state's trial-level Supreme
Court, in a ruling made public Tuesday, rejected an attempt by
doctors to force designation of the disease as sexually
transmissible.
   The lawsuit was brought by the Medical Society of the State of
New York and other doctors' groups against the state Health
Department and its policy-setting arm, the state Public Health
Council.
   By keeping AIDS off the list of sexually communicable diseases,
the Health Council has maintained it has been able to protect the
confidentiality and rights of AIDS patients.
   Listing of AIDS, which is transmitted primarily through sexual
contact and the sharing of infected needles by drug abusers, would
do more harm than good, they argued.
   Currently, people who test positive for the virus in a voluntary
test are counseled to encourage their sexual partners to be tested.
   The Gay Men's Health Crisis in New York City called the court
ruling ``a victory for both public health and common sense.''
Listing of AIDS as communicable ``would have completely eliminated
voluntary and anonymous testing,'' said Thomas J. Sweeney, the
group's deputy executive director for policy.
   Health Department spokesman Peter Slocum said he was delighted
with the decision. ``It rejects arguments based on ignorance and
fear which would have called for the indiscriminate mass testing
with no particular benefit,'' he said.
   Frances Tarlton, Health Department spokeswoman, said the
department never denied that AIDS was sexually transmissible. What
the ruling means, however, is that Health Commissioner David Axelrod
has the authority to decide ``what diseases should be listed (as
reportable) in the best way to protect the public.''
   B.J. Costello, a lawyer for the physicians' groups, said they
would appeal. He said there are ``vast numbers of people who have no
idea they have the virus, and physicians can do nothing when they
see the symptoms.''
   ``My clients are committed to a solution that will alter current
escalating figures of AIDS patients in the state,'' Costello said.
As of October, New York state had about 19,000 of the almost 75,500
diagnosed AIDS cases in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
