<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1224EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MercyKilling     11-16 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mercy Killing,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigator Shocked At Delman Bombshell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigator says he was shocked
to learn it wasn't the drugs administered by Dr. Peter Rosier that
ultimately killed Rosier's cancer-stricken wife, but the smothering
hands of her stepfather.
   But by then it was too late _ the stepfather had already been
granted immunity from prosecution in exchange for his testimony
against Rosier, James Fitzpatrick said Tuesday at Rosier's trial for
the murder of his wife, Patricia.
   Fitzpatrick, chief investigator for the state attorney's office,
said he began his investigation in 1986 after Rosier said in a TV
interview that he helped his wife kill herself that same year.
   The investigator knew that Mrs. Rosier's stepfather, Vincent
Delman, and his two sons might have seen the death and would be
crucial witnesses.
   But the Delmans' attorney said the three would testify against
Rosier only in exchange for total immunity. Prosecutors agreed,
Fitzpatrick testified.
   Then Farrell Delman, the elder of the two sons, dropped a
bombshell, saying his father had smothered Mrs. Rosier as she lay
unconscious, with the sons helping, Fitzpatrick said.
   Rosier earlier had injected his wife with morphine and given her
morphine suppositories after she failed to kill herself with
sedatives, Fitzpatrick testified.
   But when those drugs also failed to kill her, the Delmans
suffocated her, he said.
   Fitzpatrick said he was shocked and angered by the revelation,
particularly since he had offered the Delmans immunity, but added:
``We had two choices. Drop the case or grant them immunity. ... You
never enjoy giving immunity to felons. ... We could not prosecute
Dr. Rosier without them, even though we did not know about the final
act.''
   Moreover, Rosier ``is the one responsible,'' Fitzpatrick said.
``He is the orchestrator. He is the planner. ... He got the drugs.''
   Rosier is charged with murder, attempted murder and conspiracy.
He said in an unpublished book that he was fulfilling his wife's
wish to die with dignity.
   Earlier Tuesday, Vincent Delman testified he decided to smother
Mrs. Rosier with his bare hands in part because Rosier was afraid
his wife would end up a ``vegetable'' because the morphine had not
worked.
</TEXT>
