<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--OldMap     11-16 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Old Map,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medieval Map to be Auctioned to Save Cathedral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mappa Mundi, one of the most important
historical maps, will be sold to save Hereford Cathedral from
bankruptcy, a spokesman said Wednesday.
   The 13th century document, valued at more than $4.5 million, will
be sold at auction in June, said a spokesman for the cathedral, who
requested anonymity.
   The 6-by-4 map depicts historical events, biblical stories,
topography, flora and fauna.
   Medieval cartographers put Jerusalem at the center of the map,
while Hereford, about 140 miles northwest of London, is drawn on an
edge.
   The cathedral has owned the map for centuries, but says it must
be sold to pay a $270,000 debt and fund repairs.
   ``Faced with this situation, (the church) can see no alternative
but to offer for sale the single treasure, the Mappa Mundi,'' said
the spokesman.
</TEXT>
