<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1242EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   11-16 1158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,1208</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout
the nation.
   
   Nov. 15
   Tulsa (Okla.) World on the PLO and Israel:
   To no one's surprise, the Palestine Liberation Organization's
move to formally recognize Israel's right to exist was dismissed in
advance by Israel's right-wing leadership. It will not be so easily
ignored in the United States.
   ... The United States has always said it would not talk to the
PLO until it recognized Israel's right to exist. Now that such a
step appears foregone, what will be the United States response?
   President Reagan, wisely, reacted to the news with caution.
``Apparently there has been an indication they're willing to abide
by (United Nations Resolution) 242,'' the president said. ``I hope
that is true because it would be some progress.''
   Caution is needed. Yasser Arafat and other PLO leaders, speaking
individually, have made rather dramatic peace gestures in the past
only to recant later.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 15
   Portland (Maine) Press Herald on cost of supporting ex-presidents:
   When Ronald Reagan officially retires from the presidency in
January, it will be the first time in this century that four
ex-presidents will be living at the same time. That's more than a
historical footnote; it's a downright expensive proposition for
American taxpayers.
   In the 30 years since Congress formaly inaugurated a program for
the care and feeding of former presidents, the cost has increased a
hundredfold. The government will spend about $40 million on former
first families in 1989, $15 million alone on Reagan's first year of
retirement.
   Nobody begrudges Secret Service protection or the maintenance of
post-presidential office facilities for former chief executives. But
the biggest expense to taxpayers has nothing to do with
ex-presidential safety and comfort.
   Three dollars out of every five goes to maintain presidential
libraries, those combination archives and museums which have been
springing up after every change of administration since Herbert
Hoover.
   The libraries themselves, while built through private
contributions, are operated at taxpayer expense. What started out as
an annual $150,000 stipend now runs into the tens of millions.
   We need to take another look at the nation's presidential library
program with an eye to shifting more of the costs of operating them
to private foundations.
   Otherwise, let presidents simply turn their papers over to the
National Archives, where they probably belong in the first place.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 14
   Rochester (N.Y.) Democrat and Chronicle and Times-Union on George
Bush's election and the deficit:
   The foreign investors who bankroll America's spending binge to
the tune of $100 billion a year don't care about George Bush's
``read my lips'' pledge.
   They care about their investments _ and thus about the federal
budget deficit.
   In the judgment of many economists, the president-elect will have
only until early spring to make headway on reducing the deficit.
   If he fails, says C. Fred Bergsten, director of the Institute for
International Economics, look for ``a sharp fall in the dollar _ as
much as 20 percent to 25 percent. Inflation, double-digit interest
rates. Recession.''
   ... The new president will need great flexibility and bipartisan
support to manage the deficit, but Bush has tied his own hands and
alienated the congressional Democrats whose support he needs.
   ... If there's to be even a modest tax increase, Bush will have
to do more than agree to it. He will have to say, ``Read my lips: I
lied.''
   True, there is a certain poetic justice to Bush's predicament.
But soon he will be the president of all Americans; his predicament
will be ours.
   If he's willing to eat his words, Congress, and the public,
should let him.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 14
   The Evening Sun, Baltimore, on the resignation of William
Bradford Reynolds, the chief federal civil rights enforcer:
   William Bradford Reynolds officially leaves the Justice
Department on Dec. 9, and his legacy can be summed up in a single
word: bitterness.
   As President Reagan's chief civil rights enforcer, Reynolds so
alienated American blacks that they voted against Reagan in 1984 by
a margin of 9-to-1. That distrust continued to be reflected (Nov. 8)
... when blacks voted by nearly that same proportion against George
Bush, even though Bush once represented the kind of traditional
moderate Republicanism which, only 30 years ago, was drawing a
respectable share of the black vote.
   Reynolds no doubt took seriously his obligation to enforce the
law against such things as Ku Klux Klan terrorism, but this was
offset by his extremely constricted view of the law. He seemed to
feel that an absence of discrimination was the end of the federal
role in race relations. Out of this belief, he became a militant _
indeed, one could even say fanatic _ opponent of affirmative action
in any meaningful form. He did not seem to grasp the fact that
positive programs had to be pursued to overcome the effects of 300
years of slavery and segregation.
   No task of the Bush administration is more important than that of
beginning to repair the immense damage done by William Bradford
Reynolds in the past eight years.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 15
   The Tennessean, Nashville, Tenn., on the homeless:
   About 2,000 people reflected credit on themselves and their
nation the other day when they marched in Washington, D.C., to
express concern for America's homeless.
   Some 377 of the marchers went one step further, engaging in
non-violent civil disobedience by sitting down in the middle of a
street. They were arrested for disorderly conduct.
   Meanwhile, in the ``City of Brotherly Love'' _ Philadelphia _ 29
homeless people occupy a federal building near the Liberty Bell.
They, too, were carted off to jail.
   And in Nashville on the same day, almost 100 mourners turned out
for the funeral of Ms. Carol Kessler, a street person who had some
in recent years to symbolize homelessness here.
   It was fitting that the protest demonstrations occurred the day
before the presidential election.
   The plight of the homeless was largely ignored during the
campaign by both parties, and that is a shame; it should be high on
everyone's list of priorities.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 14
   The News-Leader, Springfield, Mo., on an anchorwoman's censoring
of news for religious reasons:
   Should a journalist be guided by religious faith? Maybe the
answer is yes if the end result is compassion and a commitment to
doing right by viewers and readers.
   (Sioux Falls, S.D., TV anchorwoman) Marilee Joyce prevented
broadcast of network stories on the New Age movement and the Hare
Krishna sect. Those two stories alone may not taint the credibility
of television news, or of a newspaper.
   But there ought to be more to news judgment than sanitizing
events of the day, especially those with which we might disagree.
   Marilee Joyce took her task a step too far, by trying to mold the
news of the day into a world the way she wanted it to be. That's not
education; it's indoctrination.
</TEXT>
