<HEAD>Afghan Radio Reports Six Journalists Injured in Rebel Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six foreign journalists visiting
Afghanistan at government invitation were injured in a rebel attack
on a main eastern road Wednesday, official Afghan radio reported.
   The reporters, from the Soviet Union, France, Japan and India,
were taken to Kabul for treatment of unspecified injuries after the
attack on the highway linking the eastern border town of Torkham
with Jalalabad, according to the broadcast monitored in Islamabad.
   The broadcast was the first report by Kabul of foreign
journalists being injured while on an official government tour.
   Radio Kabul did not describe the attack nor further identify the
journalists. The report could not be independently verified.
