<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     11-16 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Comes Out Against Plans to Close Shipyard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic Church on Wednesday
criticized government plans to close the Lenin Shipyard, the
birthplace of the Solidarity trade union.
   ``It is not a matter for the church to enter the sphere of purely
economic problems,'' said a statement issued by the Episcopate
Secretariat, which represents Roman Catholic Bishops nationwide.
``The government decision to close down the Gdansk Shipyard is a
political act not facilitating reconciliation.''
   The government announced the shipyard would be closed beginning
Dec. 1 because it was losing money. It now says closing the yard
will take 1{ years.
   The church statement also expressed concern that the decision
would block efforts to convene broad-based talks on Poland's future.
   ``It has also led to withdrawing the talks at the round table and
to blocking the emerging reconciliation of Poles,'' the statement
said.
   The authorities promised the talks during strikes in August, the
worst labor unrest in seven years.
   But government objections to the proposed participaton of
government critics and Solidarity advisers Adam Michnik and Jacek
Kuron have delayed the start of the talks.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa says he will not drop the two men
because that would create a precedent.
   The church statement also voiced disapproval of a strident media
campaign against social and trade union pluralism.
   ``The propaganda campaign against social pluralism, especially
against trade union pluraism which we have witnessed has not created
a favorable climate for those (round-table) talks,'' it said.
   The bishops called on authorities to fulfill a pledge to rehire
workers dismissed from their jobs for participation in the August
strikes, saying failure to do so had diminished the state's
credibility with society and with the church.
   Solidarity was crushed in 1981 and outlawed the following year
with the imposition of martial law.
   In another development, 51 activists continued a hunger strike
Wednesday to demand reinstatement of 49 miners and two steel workers
they say have yet to be rehired after the August strikes.
   The workers were holed up in Christ the King Cathedral in the
southern city of Katowice, where they took shelter Friday night
during a demonstration.
</TEXT>
