<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--TurkeyDrop     11-16 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Turkey Drop,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Live Turkeys Will Fall From The Sky</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A radio station has decided not to drop its
gift turkeys live from the sky Saturday in a stunt inspired by the
television show ``WKRP in Cincinnati.''
   In fact, they're not even going to drop the 97 birds, but lower
them from a hovering helicopter at a shopping mall in a canvas net,
Kay Feeney, a producer for WENS-FM, said Wednesday.
   Representatives of the local and national Humane Society, and a
Sacramento, Calif., group for the protection of turkeys called to
complain about the ``Lite Rock Turkey Drop.''
   An ad for the drop includes excerpts from the original ``WKRP''
episode in which a biplane drops live domesticated turkeys at a
shopping center.
   ``There's no harm intended to anyone,'' Feeney said. ``It's a way
to benefit some people who would not be able to afford a turkey.''
   The birds don't know how to fly and, as WKRP news director Les
Nessman says in the episode, they hit ``the pavement like sacks of
wet cement.''
</TEXT>
