<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--DefensePanel     11-16 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Defense Panel,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Names New Top Adviser On Women's Issues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci has
appointed a Rock Hill, S.C., college professor as the next
chairwoman of the Defense Advisory Committee on Women in the
Services.
   Connie Lee, a professor of history, government and human
relations at York Technical College in Rock Hill, will assume the
post on Jan. 1. The job carries a one-year term.
   A native of Charlotte, N.C., who has served on the committee
since 1986, Lee is succeeding Jacquelyn Davis of Cambridge, Mass.
   Davis has been widely praised for her performance, including
oversight of investigations last year that spotlighted sexual
harassment in the Navy and Marine Corps.
   The committee, known by the acronym DACOWITS, was created in 1951
by then-Defense Secretary George C. Marshall to offer advice on
policies and issues relating to women. The committee consists of 35
civilians.
   According to the Pentagon, Lee holds an undergraduate degree from
the University of North Carolina; a master's degree from Winthrop
College, and a doctorate from the University of South Carolina.
</TEXT>
