<DOCNO> AP881116-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1329EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bulgaria-Jews     11-16 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bulgaria-Jews,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir's Wife Remembers Bulgarian Effort to Save Jews in 1943</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of Israel's Prime Minister Yitzak
Shamir returned to her native country Wednesday to thank ``the noble
Bulgarian people'' for saving 50,000 Jews in 1943 from the Holocaust.
   Addressing a symposium organized by Bulgarian officials and the
nation's tiny Jewish community, Shulamit Shamir said Israel would
never forget what Bulgaria had done.
   ``Glory to the noble Bulgarian people and may it be blessed,''
she said.
   Her tribute came as Israel is seeking to restore ties to Soviet
bloc countries which, with the exception of Romania, severed
diplomatic ties with Israel over the Middle East war in 1967.
   The two-day symposium on Bulgaria's rescue of its Jews from
deportation to Nazi death camps is the first time the effort has
been marked with an international gathering of Jewish leaders in
Bulgaria.
   Leaders of the country's 3,000-member Jewish community were
present as the symposium opened amid fanfare showing it had support
from the communist leadership.
   Bulgaria's longtime leader Todor Zhivkov is among those given
credit for saving the country's estimated 50,000 Jews from
deportation, and she said she hoped she could thank him in person.
   In her speech, she also expressed hope ``the relations between
Israel and Bulgaria will intensify to the extent of matching the
strength of the historical bond between the Bulgarian and the Jewish
peoples.''
   ``We shall remember this forever,'' she told the conference in
Bulgarian, referring to the rescue.
   The Nazis had planned to deport thousands of Bulgarian Jews to
death camps in Poland on ``barges of death'' anchored at ports on
the Danube, Mrs. Shamir said.
   ``And then a historical miracle happened,'' she said. ``Everybody
witnessed how a whole people of intellectuals and workers, peasants
and townfolk, the church, the Holy Synod, men and women, rose to
save their Jewish compatriots against the wish of the fascist
authorities at this hellish time.''
   The Bulgarians are credited with foiling the plans of their king,
Boris III, and his Nazi-allied government, to deport Bulgarian Jews
following the deportation of 11,000 Jews in the spring of 1943 from
Macedonia and Thrace to the south.
   Members of the country's parliament turned against the government
to protest deportation orders, and Zhivkov is credited with helping
to organize a demonstration of 10,000 people against the
deportations.
   The tide then started to turn against the Nazis on the Eastern
front, where the Soviets dealt Adolf Hitler's armies a decisive
defeat at Kursk, and German representatives in Bulgaria told Berlin
they could no longer pressure the Bulgarian government into carrying
out the deportations.
   After World War II ended, the communists took power and most of
Bulgaria's 50,000 Jews emigrated to Israel.
   Jewish leaders from Britain, France, East Germany, Hungary and
Italy also attended, and B'nai B'rith sent representatives from the
United States.
   Mrs. Shamir is on her second visit to Bulgaria since she left at
the age of 17 in 1941 for Palestine, leaving all her family behind.
All her relatives survived the Holocaust.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881116-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1333EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LoveTriangle     11-16 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Love Triangle,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Minister Charged With Lover's Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUNCTION CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former minister serving a sentence
of life in prison for murdering his wife was charged today in the
1983 slaying of his then-lover's husband in a case dramatized in a
TV miniseries.
   Thomas P. Bird, 38, was arraigned on murder charges 12 days after
his former lover and church secretary, Lorna Anderson Eldridge,
pleaded guilty in the shooting death of her husband, Martin K.
Anderson, along a rural highway.
   The case formed the basis of the 1987 drama ``Murder Ordained''
on CBS.
   Bird was brought to the courthouse from the state prison at
Lansing. In addition to the life sentence, Bird is serving 2{ to
seven years for an earlier, unsuccessful plot to kill Anderson.
   Earlier this month, Mrs. Eldridge, 35, pleaded guilty to a
reduced charge of second-degree murder, testifying she gave Bird a
handgun and helped him kill her husband.
   She said that she and the former Lutheran pastor devised a plan
under which she pretended to lose her keys along a highway. Her
husband got out of their van to look for the keys, and Bird shot
him, she said.
   Mrs. Eldridge awaits sentencing on the murder charge. She is
serving 5 to 18 years for an earlier unsuccessful plot on her
husband's life.
   Bird was convicted in 1985 in the death of his wife, Sandy, who
was at first believed by authorities to have been the victim of a
traffic accident.
   Mrs. Eldridge remarried before being sentenced to prison. Bird
remarried in prison.
</TEXT>
