<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Oman-Polio     11-16 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Oman-Polio,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outbreak of Polio Reported in Oman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUSCAT, Oman (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An outbreak of polio among children living in
coastal villages has prompted a nationwide health alert, doctors
said Wednesday.
   More than 80 cases of the crippling disease have been reported on
the Batinah coast west of the capital of Muscat, and the number is
rising.
   Health workers were ordered to vaccinate all children under the
age of 5 in the area.
   ``Around 85 percent of infants under 1 have been vaccinated
against polio,'' said Dr. Jacob Matthai, the Muscat representative
for the United Nations International Children's Emergency Fund.
Extra vaccines will be flown in, he added.
   The cause of the outbreak was not known. Health authorities have
speculated that vaccines had lost their potency during transport in
summer heat, which reaches 120 degrees.
   Polio, short for poliomyelitis, is an infectious viral
inflammation of nerve cells in the spinal cord that can result in
temporary or permanent paralysis.
</TEXT>
