<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SpecialtyProduce     11-16 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Specialty Produce,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Americans Going Farther Afield for Their Veggies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supermarket produce counters are taking on a
special look these days, with bean sprouts, bok choy, guava and
other exotic items catching the eye of food shoppers, an Agriculture
Department economist said Wednesday.
   ``Specialty fruit and vegetable displays form a fundamental part
of the new up-scale image of many produce sections,'' said Catherine
Greene of the department's Economic Research Service.
   Rising demand for specialty produce is in line with a general
increase in fruit and vegetable consumption, she said. On the
average, Americans consumed 427 pounds of fruits and vegetables last
year, up 12 percent since 1972. That is a farm weight equivalent
before trimming, processing and after-harvest losses, she said.
   Greene said the per capita trend is expected to continue upward,
although there could be some year-to-year variations. For example,
she said, this year's drought probably will cause some decline from
the 1987 average.
   In any case, specialty fruits and vegetables are the rage among
many consumers, and there is no sign the demand will taper off soon.
Greene, writing in the agency's National Food Review, said there are
a number of reasons.
   ``Americans have become more health conscious, eating lots of
fruits and vegetables as part of a well-balanced diet,'' she said.
``Consequently, we want a huge selection of produce.''
   Further, Americans travel more frequently than they used to, and
many want ``foreign'' foods when they return home.
   ``Unusual fruits and vegetables are appearing on restaurant
menus,'' Greene said. ``Also influencing our diets are recent
immigrants from the Caribbean, Central America and Southeast Asia
who have brought their native foods with them.''
   A recent survey by the industry's Food Marketing Institute showed
that the number of items sold in supermarket produce departments
more than doubled to 150 between the mid-1970s and the early 1980s.
Today, more than 250 items is the norm, including new packs and
sizes of traditional fruits and vegetables, along with exotic and
specialty produce.
   Another survey conducted for a trade journal, The Packer, showed
the most frequently tried specialty fresh vegetables were alfalfa
and bean sprouts, followed by snow peas, pearl onions, parsnips,
leeks, baby vegetables, Chinese cabbage and shallots.
   Moreover, about a third of those surveyed also had seen or heard
of less widely known specialty vegetables such as Belgian endive,
bok choy, celeriac, daikon, kohlrabi, parsley root and Jerusalem
artichoke.
   The most frequently tried specialty fresh fruits, in order, were
pomegranates, persimmons, kumquats, quince and guavas.
   Additionally, at least a third of those surveyed had seen or
heard of breadfuit, passion fruit, plantains, prickly pear and red
bananas. But some fruits were nearly unkown: Asian pears,
carambolas, cherimoyas, sapotes, radiccho and rappini.
   Greene said the survey showed that consumers in the Western
United States are more likely to try specialty produce and fresh
herbs, another group of growth items. One factor is the West's large
Asian and Hispanic populations, with their interests in exotic
produce.
   Also, it was shown that consumers in the upper income brackets
eat more of the speciality fruits and vegetables.
   ``They may be better informed about the variety of produce
available and better able to afford the premium prices that
specialities sometimes command,'' Greene said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
