<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--ChicagoMayoral     11-16 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Chicago Mayoral,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court To Rule Monday On Chicago Mayoral Date</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Illinois Supreme Court will rule
Monday on when Chicago must hold its next mayoral election, the
court said Wednesday.
   A Cook County circuit judge ruled earlier this year that the city
must hold an election next spring to fill the two years remaining on
the term of the late Harold Washington.
   Supporters of Mayor Eugene Sawyer appealed that decision to the
Supreme Court, arguing his selection last year as acting mayor
entitles him to serve out Washington's term, which ends in 1991.
   The high court's decision will come less than a month before the
filing period opens for the spring election.
   Some major candidates have already announced for the race,
including aldermen Edward Burke, Danny Davis and Timothy Evans.
Sawyer is also expected to run, and Cook County State's Attorney
Richard Daley might also seek the job once held by his father.
</TEXT>
