<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Settlers     11-16 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Settlers,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Settlers Say They're Building While PLO Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EFRAT, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish settlers in this small
hilltop town south of Jerusalem dismiss the Palestinian declaration
of independence as ``just talk,'' but right-wing leaders are calling
for annexing parts of the occupied areas.
   Hardline Likud Trade Minister Ariel Sharon said the declaration
was ``a dangerous development'' and Israel should respond by
annexing parts of the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, where 1.5
million Palestinians live.
   In response to the declaration, the militant Tzomet Party headed
by former Chief of staff Rafael Eytan vowed to move its headquarters
from Tel Aviv to Arab east Jerusalem, captured in 1967 from Jordan
and later annexed by Israel.
   ``Those asking for war will get it,'' a party statement said.
   But a spokesman for the far-right Tehiya party, Avi Farhan, said:
``They are declaring declarations while we are creating facts. They
are making statements in Algeria, but we are building settlements.''
   About 70,000 Israelis live in more than 130 settlements in the
occupied territories. Settler leaders have called for building 50
more in the next three years. The United States views such
settlements as obstacles to peace.
   In Efrat, a settlement of 340 families located six miles south of
Jerusalem, most people seemed only vaguely aware of the Palestine
National Council's declaration in Algeria.
   ``On, that meeting ... Well, we won this country by war and the
Bible says we were here beforehand, so I don't really understand why
the Arabs think this is their land,'' said Eran Chemsky, a high
school student sitting on a park bench next to a young woman
knitting a skull cap.
   ``It's all talk, just talk,'' said a woman riding the bus from
Jerusalem to the settlement.
   Town administrator Bob Lang, an American-born immigrant, said
settlers have become accustomed to tight security in the town and
the risks of driving along the roads into Jerusalem, where they go
to shop and work. Hundreds of Israeli travelers have been injured in
stoning attacks in the 11-month-old uprising.
   They have even gotten used to the reluctance and outright refusal
of many friends and relatives to visit, for fear Palestinians will
hurl rocks or firebombs on their cars, he said.
   ``That's the biggest problem,'' he said.
   A restaurant owner who refused to give her name said she worries
because three of her daughters travel daily to schools outside the
settlement. But she said her family cannot move because ``we have
nowhere else to go. They're throwing rocks in central Israel also.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
