<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FactoryUse     11-16 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Factory Use,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Factory Use Surges to Highest Level Since 1980</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trade Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The operating rate at U.S. factories, mines and
utilities in October rose to the highest level in 8{ years, the
government said Wednesday in a report that stirred new concern about
inflation.
   The Federal Reserve Board said American industry used 84.0
percent of its capacity last month, up from 83.8 percent in
September. It was the largest increase since July and the highest
level since February 1980.
   Capacity use has grown or held steady for eight consecutive
months, creeping ever closer to the 85 percent threshold that
economists believe signals a pickup in inflation.
   As capacity increases, factories can have trouble producing
enough goods to meet demand, leading to shortages and higher prices.
   ``The hike ... is yet another sign of an increasingly fully
employed economy where substantial inflationary pressure is
building,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economist of The Boston Co.
   Although American businesses have spent heavily this year on new
equipment to expand production, Sinai said, ``increased capacity is
slow to come on line.''
   The rise in the operating rate last month followed a month of no
change in September, a 0.1 percentage point gain in August and a
sharp 0.7 percentage point rise in July.
   At manufacturing plants, the operating rate rose to 84.3 percent
last month, up from 84.1 percent in September and the highest since
July 1979. All of that increase was attributable to producers of
durable goods, ``big ticket'' items intended to last three or more
years.
   The durable goods rate jumped from 82.6 percent to 83.0 percent,
while the rate for non-durable goods held steady at 86.2 percent.
   The rate at motor vehicle and parts plants shot up for the third
month in a row, hitting 84.4 percent last month, up from 82.6
percent in September, the highest since 1985. However, the Federal
Reserve said the rate was still well below the 93.3 percent peak
reached in 1978.
   John Hagens, an economist with The Wefa Group, a Bala Cynwyd,
Pa., forecasting firm, said he saw ``some small sign of optimism''
in the capacity report because the growth came in industries with
more room to expand.
   ``The mix is in the right direction, away from non-durables and
toward the durables,'' he said. ``It's a high number but it's not as
high as it's been at the end of previous expansions.''
   The operating rate at utilities was 80.8 percent last month, up
from 80.6 percent in September. It hit a peak for the year in August
of 83.9 percent because of a surge in electricity use during the
summer heat wave.
   In the mining sector, which includes oil and gas drilling, the
operating rate slipped from 82.4 percent in September to 81.8
percent in October. U.S. oil drilling activity has waned in response
to a decline in world oil prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
