<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WashingtonPortrait     11-16 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Washington Portrait,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Washington Portrait Sold For Nearly $500,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Gilbert Stuart portrait of George Washington was
sold Wednesday for $497,000, more than five times its top estimate.
   The painting, purchased by the Berry-Hill Gallery of New York,
had belonged to James Madison, the fourth president, and originally
hung in Madison's Virginia home, said James Miller, an auctioneer at
Sotheby's.
   The painting shows the president looking old and tired and
dressed in a dark blue coat and white neck cloth. Its authenticity
was confirmed by Marvin Sadik, an art historian who is an expert on
Washington portraits, said Miller, who conducted the auction.
   Sotheby's estimated its value at only $54,000 to $90,500 because
it was one of more than 100 portraits of the president which Stuart
painted after Washington died in 1799, Miller said.
   The British seller, who was not identified, picked it up ``rather
cheaply'' at another New York auction house, he said.
   The firm said the owner brought the portrait to London for
auction because he thought it would have a ``more unusual impact
here,'' Miller said. It was included in a sale of ``British
Paintings'' which brought nearly $14.5 million.
   Stuart, who died in 1828, was an American but worked in Britain
and Ireland as well as America, where he found fame as a portrait
artist. He was the most famous painter of Washington, who did not
like posing but sat for Stuart four times in the last three years
before his death.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
