<NOTE>For Release at 6 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Gilda Radner, who had plenty of contact
with doctors while being treated for cancer, has gotten the last
laugh in a poem published in Thursday's New England Journal of
Medicine.
   Radner, who underwent surgery for ovarian cancer in 1986, had
this to say:
   ``Doctors are whippersnappers in ironed white coats
   Who spy up your rectums and look down your throats
   And press you and poke you with sterilized tools
   And stab at solutions that pacify fools.
   I used to revere them and do what they said
   Till I learned what they learned on was already dead.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHERRY HILL, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philadelphia sportscaster Howard Eskin
was assaulted by a 31-year-old man screaming ``I hate you, Howard!''
during a radio broadcast from a restaurant here, police said.
   Fortunately, Eskin's guest was Dave Rimington, the 6-foot-3,
288-pound center for the Philadelphia Eagles. Rimington grabbed the
man and held him around the neck until police came about five
minutes later, said Eskin, who was unhurt.
   Eskin, 35, said the Tuesday incident was the first time he had
ever been physically attacked during his 10 years doing live
sports-talk shows.
   Police charged Peter LaBletta, 31, with assault, malicious damage
to property and resisting arrest. He was released on $4,000 bail and
a hearing was scheduled for Jan. 11, police said.
