<DATELINE>PITTSBORO, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lady Bird Johnson, a longtime advocate of
nationwide beautification, still has a passion for things that grow.
   Mrs. Johnson, who received the North Carolina Botanical Garden's
Flora Caroliniana Award on Tuesday, described her ``lifelong love
affair with nature.''
   Mrs. Johnson, widow of President Lyndon Johnson, called plants
``our national heritage'' that at the same time give each area of
the country ``a regional identity.''
   A co-author of the new book ``Wildflowers Across America,'' Mrs.
Johnson founded the National Wildflower Research Center near Austin,
Texas, on her 70th birthday, in 1982. She described the center as a
13,000-member non-profit clearinghouse of information about plants
and how to grow them.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Basil Hume, leader of English and Welsh
Roman Catholics, was shocked when he heard that he had been
described as a newlywed in Debrett's directory of distinguished
people.
   But he forgave the trespass with a smile and received a free copy
of the offending book and an apology from the publishers, his office
said Wednesday.
   ``I know marriage by proxy is normal, but I wish I had been
consulted first,'' said the cardinal, whose priestly vows bar
marriage.
   Debrett's editor Tony Williamson said the latest edition of the
directory mistook the cardinal, who is archbishop of Westminster,
for a retired Anglican bishop who lives in Westminster and who
recently married.
   ``I was somewhat disconcerted and the lady must have been equally
astonished,'' Hume said.
