   When Nigerian writer and Nobel Prize
winner Wole Soyinka arrived here as a guest of the Indian
government, he was supposed to receive a warm welcome and be whisked
off to a luxury hotel.
   Instead, no one met him and staffers at the hotel where he was to
stay said they'd never heard of him. He finally found a room at a
less opulent hostelry.
   It wasn't supposed to happen that way, an Indian Foreign Ministry
spokesman said Wednesday.
   ``We had people camping, actually, at the airport around the
clock for three days,'' said the spokesman, who under briefing rules
cannot be identified.
   But since Soyinka arrived on a flight from Frankfurt, rather than
from Bombay, the reception committee missed the playwright, novelist
and poet who was invited to be the main speaker at Monday's
celebrations honoring the centennial of the birthday of the late
Prime Minister Jawaharlal Nehru.
   Soyinka won the 1986 Nobel Prize for literature.
