<HEAD>Judge Sentences Security Guard To 135 Months In Lawyer's Rape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A security guard charged with kidnapping
and raping a lawyer on her second wedding anniversary has been
sentenced to more than 11 years in prison by a judge who said he
would have preferred a harsher penalty.
   Ramsey County District Judge Roland Faricy said Tuesday that he
was constrained in sentencing Dwayne Alexander West by an agreement
with prosecutors under which West pleaded guilty to first-degree
criminal sexual conduct and kidnapping.
   West, 24, of St. Paul was accused of abducting the woman from a
Minneapolis office building last May, stuffing her in a car trunk
and raping her repeatedly in his home.
   Police said the woman was raped at least five times in the
13-hour ordeal.
   Faricy said West continually threatened the victim's life,
putting a noose around her neck and a pillow case over her head.
   ``He tried to kill her three times'' with the pillow case, Faricy
said.
   The woman escaped only because she convinced West that she
wouldn't tell police and talked him into delivering her to safety,
Faricy said.
   ``He dropped her off on her second wedding anniversary,'' he said.
   In October, West told an emotional court hearing, ``If I
committed a crime, I should pay for it.''
   Under the 135-month sentence, West will be eligible for parole in
7{ years, Faricy said.
