<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MIAsIdentified     11-16 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MIAs Identified,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Remains of Four Servicemen Identified</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of four U.S. servicemen missing
from the Vietnam war have been positively identified by an Army
laboratory in Hawaii, the Pentagon said Wednesday.
   The four sets of remains were among 52 repatriated to the United
States by Vietnam in April and July. Three of the four were Navy
aviators and the other was an Army officer. The identity of one of
the Navy men is being withheld ``at the request of the
next-of-kin,'' the Pentagon added.
   The remains will leave Hickam Air Force Base, Hawaii, with a full
military honors ceremony on Thursday and be flown to Travis AFB,
Calif..
   The Pentagon identified three of the missing servicemen as:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Army Maj. Kenneth J. Yonan, born July 18, 1947, lost during
combat in South Vietnam on April 24, 1972. He listed his home of
record at the time of his disappearance as Chicago.
   _Navy Lt. j.g. M.D. McMican, born on Dec. 29, 1940, lost over
North Vietnam on June 2, 1965. He listed his home of record as
Toppenish, Wash.
   _Navy Lt. j.g. Gerald M. Romano, born on March 20, 1942, lost
over North Vietnam on June 2, 1965. He listed his home of record as
New York City.
   The Pentagon said McMican, Romano and the man whose identity is
being withheld were flying on the same EA-1F airplane on a
search-and-rescue mission when they were shot down.
   The Pentagon said the remains of Yonan were among 27 repatriated
by the Vietnamese on April 6. Four of those 27 had been identified
previously.
   The remains of McMican, Romano and the unidentified serviceman
were among 25 repatriated on July 13. Five of the remains in that
group had been identified previously.
   The identification efforts are being pursued at the Army's
Central Identification Laboratory in Honolulu.
   With the latest identification, 2,383 Americans continue to be
listed as missing in Indochina as a result of the Vietnam war, of
whom 1,747 are listed as missing in either North or South Vietnam.
   All told, the remains of 172 Americans have been repatriated to
the United States from Vietnam and subsequently identified by the
Army lab since the end of the war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
