<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChristmasTrees     11-16 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Christmas Trees,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christmas Comes Early for Oregon Tree Growers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than $70 million worth of fragrant
Douglas and noble firs are being cut and bundled as Oregon growers
ready themselves for the Christmas season.
   With an expected harvest of 7.2 million trees this year, Oregon
remains the nation's single largest supplier of Christmas trees.
   Prices remain about the same as last year for premium trees, with
6-foot to 7-foot Douglas firs bringing growers around $11, said
Bryan Ostlund, spokesman for the Northwest Christmas Tree
Association in Salem.
   Slower-growing noble firs bring a higher price, he said, while
retail prices are at least double what growers receive.
   California is the chief market for Oregon trees, but they also
are shipped to East Coast and even tropical destinations.
   But growers with lower-quality trees are encountering buyer
resistance because of a plentiful supply of premium, well-shaped
trees, Ostlund said.
   Others in the business say an oversupply of trees is hurting
sales.
   Steve Woodard, Lane County extension forester, said an oversupply
has been predicted for a number of years and began showing up last
year.
   ``There's way, way more trees in the ground than will ever find a
market,'' he said.
   Many smaller Christmas tree plantings will probably be left
unharvested to grow into timber, Woodard said.
   ``People get out and plant two or five acres of trees and don't
take care of them,'' he said. ``The trees are not sheared and they
won't sell. But the big growers are dead serious about the business.
They produce quality, well-shaped trees and they have their own
market contacts.''
</TEXT>
