<HEAD>Study: Past Use of Birth Control Pill Doesn't Raise Heart Risk</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 6th graf, `Women who...' to CORRECT to Meir, sted Meil.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women who take birth control pills face double the
usual chance of heart disease, but their increased risk goes away as
soon as they stop taking the pill, a study concludes.
   Although the link between heart trouble and current pill use is
known, experts were unsure whether this increased risk lingered
after women stopped taking the pill.
   The latest study, based on the long-running Nurses'  Harvard Medical
School, concludes that former pHealth Study
atill takers have no
more than the usual risk of heart trouble.
   The study found that pill users are 2{ times more likely than
non-users the same age to have heart attacks and strokes. However,
their risk was still extremely low.
   The adverse effects of the pill could be potentially more
important if they continue after women stop using this form of birth
control. Former users are older and are already at higher risk of
heart trouble. Even a moderate increase in this hazard could be
significant.
   ``Women who have used oral contraceptives in the past do not have
to be concerned that this will raise their risk of cardiovascular
disease,'' said Dr. Meir J. Stampfer.
