<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drugs-Liability     11-16 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drugs-Liability,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manufactuers, Others Say Legal System Inhibits Drug Development</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug manufacturers and others concerned about
developing new medicines called for major reforms Wednesday in a
legal system that allows multimillion-dollar awards against drug
companies.
   Legal and medical experts told reporters the battle against AIDS
and other diseases will be hampered until manufacturers can be
better protected in lawsuits against drugs that have been approved
by federal authorities.
   ``The current climate has created strong disincentives to conduct
research and development in certain high-risk areas,'' including the
search for a cure to acquired immune deficiency syndrome, or AIDS,
said Bruce J. Brennan of the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers
Association.
   The American Medical Association in June passed a resolution
saying that biomedical research was deteriorating in certain fields
because of the unavailability of product liability insurance. The
organization's 420-member House of Delegates called for broad tort
reform.
   Huge jury awards in cases involving drugs approved by the Food
and Drug Administration already have caused some drugs to be removed
from the market and limited availability of others to a single
manufactuer, Brennan said.
   ``One must ask whether it makes any sense to have FDA's decisions
second-guessed by lay juries,'' he said.
   Brennan said FDA approval of a drug should be made a strong
defense in product liability action, unless the drug manufacturer
can be shown to have committed fraud on the FDA in obtaining
approval or negligence in manufacture or distribution of the drug.
   Groups representing lawyers have argued that limiting liability
would be denying victims of dangerous drugs their rights to redress
under the legal system.
   Ross H. Weaver, technology manager for the American Medical
Association, said reasonable guidelines are needed for pain and
suffering awards which have escalated in recent years to several
million dollars.
   ``We need to compensate, but we also need to ensure that new
products stay available for those who need them,'' he said.
   George Frazza, general counsel for drug manufacturer Johnson &
Johnson, said that whenever a drug comes out relating to the
reproductive system ``lawyers are swarming all over.''
   He said most juries will make awards based on scientific
evidence, but with some drugs facing hundreds of suits across the
country, all it takes to inhibit the manufacturer is one jury ruling
in favor of the plaintiff with a large award.
   Frazza suggested that a system be set up in which courts could
take testimony from a recognized scientific panel, rather than from
experts hired by the prosecution and defense who simply contradict
each other.
</TEXT>
