<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     11-16 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Politburo Member Urges Freer Press</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the Soviet Union's
Politburo urged publication of ``different opinions, whether you
like them or not,'' in an interview published Wednesday by the
Communist Party daily Rude Pravo.
   Also Wednesday, the Communist Party weekly Tribuna accused
independent groups that have become increasingly active in the
Soviet bloc of seeking legalization to ``legally subvert socialism.''
   In the Rude Pravo interview, Alexander N. Yakovlev, a close
adviser to President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, appeared to criticize the
state-run media in the East bloc for failing to report more
extensively on developments in other countries.
   ``I think that our journalists should publish more actively
information about the situation in other countries. It seems to me
that there exist many reserves,'' Yakovlev said.
   ``We write about life only formally, like in a protocol...but we
can nowhere read about what is interesting everywhere, in your
country, in our country or in the countries of our neighbors,'' he
told four Czechoslovak reporters, also representing the state news
agency CTK and state Radio and Television.
   He also said, ``If you profess democracy, open information, you
should also publish different opinions, whether you like them or
not.''
   ``The one thing we must not allow are factual inaccuracies,''
Yakovlev said.
   The Tribuna article said independent groups, such as Solidarity
in Poland or the recently established League of Free Democrats in
Hungary, as well as independent groups in Czechoslovakia, sought to
create ``the bourgeois type of a plural system.''
   It was written by the editor in chief, Karel Horak.
   According to CTK, which carried excerpts, Horak made clear that
independent groups in Czechoslovakia would not be allowed to gain
the kind of political footing a number of groups have achieved in
neighboring Hungary.
   The attack came less than a week after Yakovlev told journalists
in Hungary that each country's leadership should decide for itself
the question of introducing a multiparty system.
   The Hungarian government last week approved draft legislation
that could pave the way for a multiparty system.
   Czechoslovak authorities have taken a particularly tough stand
lately on dissent, cracking down on independent groups and using
police force to break up banned rallies.
   ``From a historical point of view, opposition under Socialism can
only be anti-Socialist,'' Horak wrote.
   However, Yakovlev, in a speech at the Communist Party School in
Prague on Tuesday, defended ``Socialist pluralism.''
   ``The conflict of opinions, emotions and interests is
inevitable.'' he said.
   He indicated that communist leaders and citizens must seek to
establish a compromise or consensus.
   ``We evaluate the art of political leadership by the ability to
make sure there are no people who disagree in the main and
fundamental, no people who are rejected, separated from the society
or separating the society,'' Yakovlev said.
</TEXT>
