<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Religious     11-16 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Religious,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israelis, American Jews United Against Orthodox `Blackmail'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of a new coalition said Wednesday they
represent more than 1 million Israeli and American Jews who oppose
ultra-Orthodox efforts to enforce strict observance of the sabbath
and change the rules of conversion.
   Founding members are the American Jewish Congress, the
Association of Americans and Canadians in Israel, three left-leaning
Israeli political parties and 18 other groups.
   ``A travesty is being played out on Judaism in Israel and around
the world,'' said Rabbi Philip Spectre, head of the coalition and
director of the Jerusalem-based Israel Movement for Progressive
Judaism.
   His 12,000-member group is Israel's equivalent of the American
Reform movement.
   In an interview, he said of the ultra-Orthodox: ``This is a breed
of Orthodox that is extremist. It threatens to push us into a
Neanderthal system.''
   Spectre told a news conference the coalition will lobby
parliament to oppose demands of the ultra-Orthodox.
   Religious parties won 18 of the 120 parliament seats in the Nov.
1 elections and probably will hold the balance of power in a
coalition government being formed by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
of the right-wing Likud bloc.
   In exchange for ultra-Orthodox support, Shamir promised to
support ``Who is a Jew'' legislation under which only Orthodox
rabbis could approve conversions to Judaism. The action would take
the form of an amendment to the Law of Return, which gives Israeli
citizenship to any Jew who seeks it.
   Current law defines a Jew as a person born of a Jewish mother or
converted to Judaism. The proposed change would add ``in accordance
with Halacha,'' Jewish religious law, and thus nullify conversions
performed by Reform and Conservative rabbis who do not strictly
observe such requirements.
   Spectre said such an amendment would alienate Conservative and
Reform Jews, who are the vast majority of the 5 million in America.
   ``We are dedicated to preventing the surrender to ultra-Orthodox
blackmail,'' he said. ``We don't believe the way to glorify Judaism
is through coercive legislation. Judaism's ideas can compete on the
open market of ideas. It doesn't need coercion to back it up.''
   He said his coalition favors reforming Israel's electoral system
to limit the power of the minority religious parties.
   Yehuda Bauer, head of the Israel Association for Humanistic
Secular Judaism, said Israel's largely secular population is
threatened by the resurgence of Orthodox political power. About 75
percent of Israel's 3.5 million Jews are non-religious.
   Bauer said Orthodox parties ``want to create a backward,
Khomeini-like society by legislating religious observance,''
referring to the Iranian revolutionary leader, Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881116-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1855EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CottonFire     11-16 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cotton Fire,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents Return Home, Cleanup Begins</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Ark Storms Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LAW3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FERGUSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTUS, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of a 20-block area evacuated
because of a devastating cotton fire returned home Wednesday to find
that the fire had destroyed at least 25 homes and four businesses.
   After a 30-minute tour Wednesday morning, Gov. Henry Bellmon
compared the situation to ``a scene out of a horror movie.''
   ``I can't imagine anyone thinking up a scenario like this, where
there would be a fire break out in a field of cotton modules when
the wind is blowing 60 miles per hour,'' Bellmon said.
   Eighteen people were treated for minor injuries; 400 residents of
a poor, south-side neighborhood were evacuated.
   ``Fire came and took everything,'' said Jose Cresencios Briones,
who lost his house and storage shed to the fire that began in a
storage field Tuesday and spread to this city of 23,000 in
southwestern Oklahoma.
   Briones said his property was partially insured but he didn't
know where he would work or how he would house his wife and five
children.
   Police Chief Jim Hughes said the destroyed cotton was probably
worth about $3 million. Besides the destroyed homes and businesses,
Hughes said about 100 homes were damaged by smoke. He said he had no
estimate of monetary damages.
   Several teams including Civil Defense, the Red Cross and city
workers reviewed damages Wednesday as preparation for submitting
applications for emergency aid, said city Administrator Joe Courtney.
   The cause of the fire was undetermined, Courtney said.
   Residents donated food, clothing and furniture to burned-out
residents, officials said. By early afternoon, $4,000 had been
collected; officials said the money would be spent primarily for
housing.
   Piles of clothes, canned food, toys and fresh fruit lined the
walls of the temporary relief center.
   The giant bales, or modules, were about 40 feet long, 8 feet high
and 8 feet wide, said Courtney. They were stacked in fields awaiting
processing at a cotton gin.
   The winds carried burning bits of newly harvested cotton through
the city Tuesday afternoon.
   The flames missed the trailer of Bill Tackett, but razed that of
his neighbor 15 feet away.
   ``Lucky. I'm telling you, I'm lucky,'' Tackett said. ``It could
have been worse. Because of the smoke, the firemen couldn't get
around to all of the houses.''
   ``We couldn't see a hand or foot in front of our face,'' said
firefighter Eddie Williamson. ``We had to feel from house to house.''
   On Wednesday, police and firefighters conducted a house-to-house
search of the charred area; utility workers repaired telephone lines.
   Meanwhile, firefighters watched the modules, which Civil Defense
director Dwight Dennis said Tuesday night would probably burn for
two days.
   ``It's not uncommon for a module to self-ignite under certain
situations,'' Courtney said. ``It might sit out there and smother
for two days and we might not even be aware of it.''
</TEXT>
