<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1857EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Jews     11-16 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Jews,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Leader Forced To Resign Over Kristallnacht Controversy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The No. 2 official in West
Germany's Jewish community resigned Wednesday under pressure from
fellow Jewish leaders angered by his defense of a controversial
speech on the Nazi era.
   Michael Fuerst's resignation came as West Germans continue to
debate last week's speech by Parliament President Philipp Jenninger,
who also resigned.
   Heinz Galinski, chairman of the National Jewish Council,
announced after a special meeting of the 18-member Jewish leadership
that Fuerst had decided to step down because of a ``long-standing
lack of agreement between me and himself.''
   Fuerst, a lawyer in the city of Hanover, left the council meeting
after issuing the resignation. A woman who answered the telephone at
his home more than 155 miles north of Frankfurt said he was not
there. No one answered the telephone at Fuerst's office on
Wednesday, a national holiday.
   ``I hope that with this explanation the controversy has been
resolved,'' Galinski said after reading the resignation
announcement. He said the announcement had been prepared with
Fuerst's approval.
   Fuerst had been under fire, especially from the West German
Jewish community leaders, since his defense of Jenninger's Nov. 10
speech at a memorial service on the 50th anniversary of
Kristallnacht, the night of terror against Jews across Germany that
signaled the coming Holocaust.
   Jenninger had reminded his audience during the speech that many
Germans initially embraced Hitler's campaigns and felt that the Jews
deserved being ``put back in their place.''
   About 50 members of the German Bundestag walked out in protest of
Jenninger's remarks, and the 56-year-old member of Chancellor Helmut
Kohl's Christian Democratic party resigned the next day.
   Jenninger said he had been misunderstood. He told nationwide
television that ``you can't call everything by its name in Germany.''
   Galinski said after the speech he thought silence was the only
appropriate response to Jenninger's comments.
   Fuerst, however, gave his own assessment hours after the
controversial address.
   ``I welcome the fact that the parliament president described in
full clarity what was happening in Germany between 1933 and 1938 ...
especially the fact that everything Hitler did was strongly
supported by the masses of all Germans,'' Fuerst told a nationally
televised panel discussion.
   Fuerst, 41, also spoke out at the time against the growing number
of calls for Jenninger's resignation. He said Monday he had received
many calls from those who approved of his defense of Jenninger.
   Galinski and other council members said Fuerst's statements
outraged most of the Jewish community.
   ``He had no chance. The overwhelming majority was against him, it
was not just us but the whole Jewish community,'' council member
Nathan Kalmanowicz of Munich said after Wednesday's meeting.
   Galinski told The Associated Press that the council members would
have taken a vote of no-confidence against Fuerst if he hadn't
stepped down voluntarily.
   The Jenninger dispute has intensified West Germany's debate over
the haunting legacy of the Third Reich.
   Many people, like Fuerst, have cautiously approved of Jenninger's
attempt to remind Germans that responsibility for the Holocaust is
shouldered by more than the Nazi leadership.
   ``The part about the people staying silent, giving approval, and
that it could happen among a majority of the Germans _ people say
that very seldom,'' said Parliament member Hildegard Hamm-Bruecher.
   Hamm-Breucher, a member of the government coalition partner Free
Democrats who started in politics in 1948, also said the speech
offered ``sharp corners and edges'' for further debate on the Nazi
era.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
