<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Missile     11-16 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Missile,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Reportedly Test Fires Nuclear-Capable Missile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel has secretly conducted a second test of a
missile with nuclear capability that has the range to strike all the
Arab capitals, a military journal reported Wednesday.
   Jane's Defense Weekly quoted unidentified U.S. intelligence
sources as saying the Jericho-II missile was fired into the
Mediterranean in September, around the time Israel launched an
experimental satellite into space.
   The two launches did not appear related, and the firing of the
Jericho-II ``did not yield any additional information regarding the
tactical missile's current and future capabilities,'' the magazine
said.
   It said the Jericho-II was first test-fired in May 1987 and
splashed down south of the Greek island of Crete.
   The 1987 launch carried the missile 530 miles, and it was
projected to have a maximum range of 940 miles, putting it in
striking range of all the Arab capitals, Jane's said.
   It said last year's launch prompted Soviet warnings that since
the missile could reach the southern Soviet Union, Moscow might take
``defensive and political steps,'' but these measures did not
materialize.
   After the Soviet protest, Israeli officials leaked word to the
media that the missiles could not reach Soviet territory, Jane's
said.
   Israel has never confirmed persistent foreign intelligence
assessments that it has nuclear weapons or can assemble them on
short notice, and has given scant information about the Jericho
program.
</TEXT>
