<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Executions     11-16 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Executions,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Claim Clerics Executed in Iran on Khomeini Orders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of Iran's main opposition group
said Wednesday that 12 clergymen have been executed in Tehran on
orders from Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Masoud Rajavi, leader of the Iraqi-based Mujahedeen Khalq, or
People's Holy Warriors, said the executions occurred last week and
indicated ``an intensification of the regime's internal conflicts
... as it heads for disintegration and inevitable collapse.''
   Rajavi's claims could not be independently confirmed.
   The statement, sent to The Associated Press in Nicosia from the
Mujahedeen's headquarters in Baghdad, followed a U.N. report Nov. 3
that ``large numbers of prisoners, members of opposition groups''
have been executed in Iran since July.
   Dissident Iranian factions say more than 1,100 people, including
Mujahedeen activists, have been executed since the movement's
military wing, the National Liberation Army of Iran, captured two
towns in a July offensive.
   The following month, Iran and Iraq agreed to a cease-fire in
their eight-year war.
   Khomeini's acceptance of the U.S.sponsored cease-fire is
understood to have been opposed by hardliners in the fundamentalist
Tehran hierarchy. Rajavi claimed it has internal divisions in Tehran
between various factions jockeying for power after Khomeini dies.
   The 88-year-old revolutionary patriarch has been reported to be
ailing.
   Despite statements by Iranian leaders that the hierarchy is
united, Rajavi said the executions showed that Khomeini ``has found
no other resort but killing and intimidation.''
   He said Khomeini and Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani _ the
most powerful figure after the ayatollah _ ``want to make it
abundantly clear to the other mullahs that the consequence of
non-conformity or dissent, even within the regime, is death.''
   The statement identified only three of the executed clerics. It
gave their names as Omid Najafababi, Hussein Arab and Sultani and
said they were executed ``on Khomeini's personal order.''
   Other Iranian dissident sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the executed clerics were associates of Ayatollah
Hussein Ali Montazeri, Khomeini's designated successor. They said
they had no details about why the clerics were reportedly executed.
   Montazeri and Rafsanjani have been at odds in the past, although
recent indications were that they had set aside their differences
while Iran sought to rebuild its military machine and carry out
post-war reconstruction.
   Montazeri, whose succession to Khomeini has been opposed by other
Iranian leaders, was tainted in 1986 by the arrest of Mehdi Hashemi,
brother of Montazeri's son-in-law and a former close associate.
   His arrest was ordered by Rafsanjani after Hashemi exposed
Rafsanjani's clandestine contacts with the United States in the
secret deal to trade arms for hostages held in Lebanon.
   Hashemi, a hard-line cleric who was believed linked to Iranian
terrorist operations abroad, was convicted of treason and murder and
executed last year.
   That was seen as a coup for Rafsanjani and a demonstration of his
ascendancy in Tehran.
</TEXT>
