<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SudanRebels     11-16 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan Rebels,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels, Khartoum Political Party Hope to Sign Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudanese rebels and political
leaders met Wednesday to finish drafting an agreement to end a
5{-year-old civil war in southern Sudan.
   The rebel Sudan People's Liberation Front and the Democratic
Unionist Party were attending the conference in Addis Ababa,
Ethiopia's capital.
   Col. John Garang, a rebel leader, and Mohammed Osman Mirghani,
the party general secretary, were first scheduled to sign a peace
agreement Monday. However, the signing was postponed to Tuesday and
then to Wednesday. There was no explanation.
   The Democratic Unionist Party is the second-largest political
party in Sudan and is a partner with Prime Minister Sadiq Mahdi's
Umma party in the Khartoum government.
   The five-point peace agreement calls for suspension of Islamic
law and the state of emergency in Sudan. It also calls for ending
defense pacts between Sudan and other countries and for convening a
constitutional conference attended by all political parties.
   In addition, Garang agreed to allow relief to reach starving war
refugees in Sudan.
   Mansour Khaled, a former foreign minister in the government of
ousted President Gaafar Nimeiri and now a rebel supporter, described
the Addis Ababa meeting as ``a final and formal conference.''
   Khaled said Mahdi would accept an agreement between the rebels
and the minority party because his majority Umma party is committed
to the so-called Koka Dam Declaration.
   Sudanese political parties, including rebel leaders, agreed to a
united and secular Sudan at a 1986 meeting in Koka, a resort town 60
miles south of Addis Ababa.
   Mahdi has given his blessings to the meeting and on Nov. 10 said
he had given Mirghani ideas to present to Garang. He did not
elaborate.
   Garang organized the Sudan People's Liberation Army in early 1983
and began his fight for southern autonomy and political, economic
and administrative reforms. Then-President Nimeiri's proclamation of
Islamic law exacerbated the war six months later.
   The rebels claim to control 95 percent of the southern
countryside and small towns.
   Relief workers say the accumulated effects of more than five
years of war have brought widespread famine to much of southern
Sudan this year. They estimate that starvation has killed more than
250,000 people.
   One-third of southern Sudan's civilian population of 6 million
has fled in search of a haven in northern Sudan and neighboring
Ethiopia.
</TEXT>
