<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LaunchPadDedication     11-16 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Launch Pad Dedication,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delta 2 Launch Pad Dedicated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force on Wednesday accepted
the first Delta 2 rocket and dedicated the pad from which the
powerful new space booster will be launched.
   ``Today marks another crucial step in achieving assured access to
space for our national security payloads,'' said Lt. Gen. Donald L.
Cromer, commander of ther Air Force Space Division.
   Cromer said the first Delta 2, scheduled for launch in December,
will carry a pair of navigation satellites which will have a
``revolutionary impact on worldwide navigation and on military
planning and force deployment.''
   The Delta 2 is a more powerful version of the Delta 1 rocket
which for 28 years has been a workhorse space booster for NASA and
the Defense Department, orbiting 170 satellites.
   The launch pad dedicated Wednesday is an old Delta 1 pad
renovated to handle the new, larger rocket.
   John Yardley, president of McDonnell Douglas Astronautics Co.,
said the Air Force has ordered 14 Delta 2s, with an option for six
more, while the company has orders for eight of the vehicles for the
launch of communications satellites and other commercial payloads.
</TEXT>
