<DOCNO> AP881116-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1937EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CBS-JFKAsssassination     11-16 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CBS-JFK Asssassination,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS' Documentary Recalls JFK Assassination in Rarely Seen Footage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thursday night on CBS it will suddenly become
mid-day on a Friday _ Nov. 22, 1963. The black-and-white soap opera
``As the World Turns'' will be on.
   The soap opera is interrupted by Walter Cronkite intoning, ``Here
is a bulletin from CBS News.''
   The rarely scene footage is in the CBS' documentary ``Four Days
in November: The Assassination of John F. Kennedy,'' marking the
25th anniversary of the death of the president.
   The documentary consists of little more than edited footage from
the 56 hours that CBS was on the air covering the assassination, the
shooting of Lee Harvey Oswald and the Kennedy funeral.
   The vintage film has an eloquence of its own that CBS anchor Dan
Rather and executive producer Perry Wolff wisely leave alone. The
documentary allows viewers their own memories, with a minimum of
present-day intrusion.
   ``We opened a time capsule, that's all we did,'' said Wolff who
joined Rather and the other producers of the program at a screening
for TV critics.
   ``For once at least, we didn't do too much,'' said Rather, who
only appears on camera to set up the next sequence.
   ``Our purpose is not to make commentary on the past, but to bring
it back.''
   Keeping present-day commentary to a minimum apparently also
allowed the network to avoid another Rather-Cronkite wrangle. Rather
gets the spotlight as anchor of the broadcast, but Cronkite is the
star of the archival footage.
   Cronkite declined to comment on his lack of participation in the
documentary, calling it a ``judgment'' call.
   The only footage in the documentary that was not part of CBS'
coverage at the time is the famous Zapruder 8mm film of the
assassination. CBS did not have rights to the film in 1963. Now,
however, the film is rented out by Abraham Zapruder's family.
   After the initial bulletin, CBS returned briefly to regular
programming _ a commercial for Nescafe _ then re-interrupted.
Cronkite appeared on camera in the newsroom. There were live
pictures from the Dallas Trade Mart, the site of a luncheon that was
to have been the next stop on Kennedy's agenda.
   Eddie Barker of KRLD, CBS' local affiliate, reported from the
Trade Mart, passing along unconfirmed reports that Kennedy was dead.
An unheralded cameraman zeroed in on a weeping black waiter; later
on workers sadly removing the presidential seal from the podium.
   Rather later confirmed the report of Kennedy's death, working the
story from the station by phone. Barker had gotten confirmation from
a doctor on the Parkland Hospital staff. Rather confirmed with a
priest and a doctor who were in the emergency room when the
president died. Cronkite reported Rather's confirmation, but the
official announcement did not come for another 17 minutes.
   ``It was a very long 17 minutes,'' Rather recalled.
   Cronkite is handed a piece of wire copy. ``From Dallas, Texas,
the flash, apparently official,'' he said solemnly. ``President
Kennedy died at 1 p.m. Central Standard Time. Two o'clock Eastern
Standard Time.'' He takes off his glasses and looks at the clock.
``Some 38 minutes ago.'' Cronkite's voice cracks, and he has to take
a moment to collect himself before continuing.
   In the documentary, Rather explains that viewers may see water
marks on some of the footage. Television had never covered such an
event, and because most news cameras used film instead of videotape,
technicians were developing film as fast as they could and putting
it on the air still wet.
   Also included is rarely seen footage of accussed assassin Oswald
answering reporters' questions as police escort him through the
police station. There's also the now-famous footage of Jack Ruby
stepping out of a crowd and shooting Oswald to death at point-blank
range.
   The last part of the documentary is the state funeral. It was
television news coverage at its best, as announcers let the tragic
spectacle unfold with very little comment.
   According to Wolff, viewers are lucky to see the CBS footage at
all. He said the film was deteriorating and probably would not have
lasted another five years.
   ``Even if the broadcast doesn't work, it's been preserved for one
more generation,'' Wolff said. ``This time capsule is a national
treasure.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881116-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1943EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NotDeductible     11-16 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Not Deductible,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRS Sets Disclosure Standards For Tax-Exempt Groups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service served formal
notice Wednesday that non-charitable, tax-exempt organizations are
required to fully disclose to potential donors that their
contributions are not tax-deductible.
   The agency also issued detailed guidelines to organizations that
offer to sell routine services that are available free or for a
nominal charge from the federal government. This requirement was
prompted by advertisements offering to sell workers a summary of
their earned Social Security benefits, even though that information
is available free from the Social Security Administration.
   The guidelines require such solicitations to state expressly if
the information can be obtained from the government for $2.50 or
less.
   The restriction applies only if the information to be provided
affects only the specific individual solicited. It exempts, for
example, solicitations to provide copies of federal agency
newsletters or material on pending legislation.
   The restriction and the requirement that non-charitable
organizations fully disclose that donations are not deductible as
charitable contributions were required by Congress in a 1987 law.
The latter provision affects such groups as political, farm and
labor organizations whose annual gross receipts normally exceed
$100,000.
   Any advertisement or other solicitation must include a statement
similar to: ``Contributions or gifts to (name of organization) are
not tax deductible.''
   If the solicitation is in a television ad, for example, the
statement must appear ``in close proximity to the request for
contributions,'' if oral, or, if written, must appear on the screen
in large easily readable type for at least five seconds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
