<1ST_LINE>u w AM-NotchBabies     11-16 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Notch Babies,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says No Changes Needed to Equalize Social Security Benefits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress should resist demands by so-called
notch babies to raise Social Security benefits for people born
between 1917 and 1921, concludes a report released Wednesday by the
National Academy of Social Insurance.
   The report by a panel of non-partisan experts said benefits to
some people born before 1917 are higher than Congress intended,
sometimes as much as $200 a month more than people with similar work
histories born a few days later.
   But the experts said it is not feasible, politically or
economically, to reduce their benefits or raise those of everyone
born later. ``Therefore, the panel recommends no change in present
law...'' the report concludes.
   The notch report was sought last March by Sens. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan and Bob Dole, chairman and senior GOP member of the Senate
Finance Committee's Social Security subcommittee.
   The notch, or discrepancy in benefits, arose when Congress
adopted a new formula meant to keep rising Social Security benefits
at a constant percentage of a person's average pre-retirement
earnings.
   However, people born before 1917 were allowed to use the old,
over-generous method of calculation. The result: a benefit rate that
peaked in 1981 at 56 percent of average earnings, about 15
percentage points higher than what Congress had intended.
   Robert Myers, chairman of the study panel and formerly executive
director of the National Commission on Social Security Reform, said
there are probably about 1 million notch babies feeling
``substantial impact'' from the situation.
   ``It isn't fair,'' Myers acknowledged. But he and others on the
study panel said those born after 1917 are receiving the benefits
Congress intended.
   The report said any inequity is due to some people getting too
much _ not others getting too little. ``It would be unwise to extend
this over-generous treatment to additional persons,'' the report
said. Furthermore, it said, there is no practical way to correct the
problem.
   Eliminating the notch ``would require reducing benefits for those
already receiving them,'' the report said. ``Conversely, increasing
the benefits of those born in the notch years would, in turn, create
new relative notches affecting those born in later years.''
   Myers said it would cost up to $300 billion to equalize
everyone's benefits. As far as reducing the windfall, he said it
would be very difficult and expensive to find the individuals who
received it _ not to mention that ``from a practical standpoint,
Congress would be quite loath'' to take away benefits from people
already receiving them.
   Myers said there are many misconceptions about the notch
situation and criticized some grass-roots notch groups for
disseminating erroneous information.
   The report says, for example, that some notch babies incorrectly
believe they are at a disadvantage compared to people born both
before and after them. Computation procedures are, ``if anything,
generally to the advantage of those born prior to 1922 when benefits
relative to prior earnings are considered,'' it said.
   The National Academy of Social Insurance describes itself as a
non-partisan, non-profit center for research and education on Social
Security and related programs. Its board of advisers includes
Moynihan and Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., AFL-CIO president Lane Kirkland
and Alexander Trowbridge, president of the National Association of
Manufacturers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
