<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0630,0714</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Challenge to Israeli Authority Persists with Songs and Stones</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs, 2 more wounded and Rabin quotes. PICKS
up
12th pvs `The latest'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAZA CITY, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teen-agers challenged
Israel's authority with songs, rocks and flaming tires Wednesday
despite army efforts to stop celebrations of the Palestinian
declaration of independence.
   Soldiers wounded eight Palestinians in Gaza City and the town of
Khan Yunis, said hospital officials in the Gaza Strip. Those shot
were protesters and violators of a military curfew that confined
Gaza's 650,000 residents to their homes for a sixth day.
   In the occupied West Bank, curfews and travel bans were imposed
on about 250,000 Palestinians. Gen. Dan Shomron, the army chief of
staff, said the army ``will keep as many troops in the area as is
needed. We will continue to keep the quiet by keeping people under
curfew as necessary.''
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said on state television: ``I
believe that the events of the last several days can become a
turning point leading to a significant decrease in violence. ... We
can undertake all the legally allowed steps.''
   Rabin said security actions have had a cumulative effect,
``making it more and more difficult for the residents to conduct
violent actions. ... I believe that in three to six months we shall
bring about a substantial quiet.''
   A 25-year-old man wounded by soldiers three days ago in the Gaza
Strip town of Rafah died Wednesday, raising to 313 the number of
Palestinians killed since the uprising against Israeli occupation
began Dec. 8, 1987. Eleven Israelis also have been killed.
   Palestinians have been celebrating the independence declaration
since it was issued Tuesday in Algiers by the Palestine National
Council, which acts as the legislature of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   Young men danced in the streets of Bethlehem in the West Bank and
sang the Palestinian anthem ``My Homeland, My Homeland.'' Masked
youths carrying a sign saying ``PLO, Israel No'' marched on even
after soldiers fired over their heads.
   Soldiers later were seen breaking into houses and ordering
residents to clear rocks from the streets. Using loudspeakers, they
ordered women to bring pails of water to put out fires.
   In Jerusalem, about 40 students from a Jewish girls' school in
the West Bank settlement of Ofra protested the independence
declaration, chanting and reading a statement against ``Palestinians
carrying on the ways of the Nazis, murderers of women and children.''
   Well-known Israeli writers Amos Kenaan and Dan Ben-Amotz
published an advertisement in the daily Hadashot congratulating
Palestinians on the declaration.
   ``We recognize your government and appeal to the Israeli
government to recognize the government of Palestine in exile and to
immediately launch negotiations with it,'' they said.
   The latest victim, identified as Tareq Abu Samhdaneh, died of a
bullet wound to the head, hospital officials said. Arab reporters
said he was shot the same day he was released from prison, where he
had been held without trial for four months.
   In Gaza Wednesday evening, firecrackers echoed through darkened
streets that had been kept quiet during the day by hundreds of
troops patrolling in trucks covered with plastic sheets as
protection against stone-throwers.
   During a morning tour by journalists under army escort, Gaza
youths dashed from an alley to throw stones at reporters' cars. One
car was hit, but no one was hurt.
   Reporters saw soldiers bang on doors of one deserted street where
a tire burned, hauling out a balding, middle-aged man in a white
robe to douse the flames and remove debris from the road.
   In the West Bank, the army declared Ramallah a closed military
area, preventing anyone from entering or leaving the city of 40,000.
Curfews were in effect in the towns of Tulkarem, Qalqilya, Nura
Shams and Shuweika, home to about 85,000 people. Nablus, the largest
West Bank city, also was reported to be under curfew.
   Troops carried out raids in several West Bank areas, a military
spokeswoman said. She said arrests were made but declined to give a
number. Israel radio said about 100 people were rounded up in the
city of Hebron and in several villages.
</TEXT>
