<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 2244EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hirohito     11-16 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor's Energy Waning, Palace Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito's energy is waning and doctors are
trying to keep the condition of the 77-pound monarch stable rather
than improving it, palace officials said Wednesday.
   The world's longest-reigning monarch has been bedridden since
Sept. 19, when he started bleeding internally.
   ``Compared to before, his energy has somewhat declined'' on
Wednesday, said Kenji Maeda, spokesman for the Imperial Household
Agency. But ``there has been no particular change,'' he added.
   On Wednesday afternoon, the emperor had a fever of 100.4 degrees,
up from 98.8 in the morning. His normal temperature is about 95.9.
   Maeda said doctors were more concerned with maintaining rather
than improving the emperor's condition.
   He said the emperor's showed no signs of new bleeding and doctors
did not plan to give him further blood transfusions. Hirohito has
received 42 pints of blood _ more than three times the amount
circulating in his body.
   On Wednesday, the emperor received visits from the families of
his two sons, Crown Prince Akihito and Prince Hitachi, but they
talked very little, Maeda said. Hirohito sleeps most of the time and
is awake only intermittently, palace officials said.
   Hirohito, who has not consumed any food since he became ill
except a few spoonfuls of porridge, receives about 600 calories of
nourishment every day intravenously. His weight has reportedly
dropped to about 77 pounds, down from 110 pounds before his illness.
</TEXT>
