<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Palestinians-Party     11-16 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Palestinians-Party,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Envoys, Palestinian Americans Celebrate `Independent State'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of Palestinian Americans and Arab
diplomats on Wednesday celebrated the declaration of a Palestinian
state with balloons, a birthday cake and wild cheering.
   Under a banner reading ``Happy Birthday Palestine,'' speakers
extolled this week's decision by the Palestine National Council to
declare an independent Palestinian state in the Israeli-occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The PNC, which is the legislative branch of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, also adopted a resolution which implicitly
accepts Israel's right to exist, renounces terrorism and calls for
Middle East peace talks under international auspices.
   Saudi Ambassador Prince Bandar Bin-Sultan said the PNC program
``is a major breakthrough toward peace. ... It's a great opportunity
for the United States.''
   Also present at the celebration were the ambassadors of Jordan,
Egypt, Qatar, Morocco, Yemen, as well as diplomats from Kuwait,
Djibouti, Somalia and India. So far, 23 countries have recognized
the declaration.
   The United States has rejected the declaration of a Palestinian
state, calling it a unilateral action that does not advance the
cause of peace.
   The State Department has also said the PNC program does not meet
the U.S. requirements for dialogue with the PLO because it fails to
explicitly recognize Israel.
   The declaration of a state does not have any practical effect in
the near term, but it has served to boost morale among Palestinians
in the occupied territories who have been staging an insurrection
against the 20-year Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   Wednesday's event, organized by the American Arab
Anti-Discrimination Committee, began with a moment of silence for
the 300 Palestinians killed in clashes with Israeli troops over the
past 11 months. ADC advocates civil rights for Americans of Arab
descent.
   Participants then sang the Palestinian anthem, which speaks about
a return to the homeland, followed by the popular Beatles' refrain
``Give Peace a Chance.''
   A birthday cake was then wheeled out to the sound of wild
cheering and yululating.
   Abdeen Jabara, President of the ADC, said the PNC decision
``should be the electric shock to break the cycle of violence and
pain'' for Palestinians. ``The American administration must seize
this window of opportunity,'' he added.
</TEXT>
