<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Sununu     11-16 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sununu,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sununu Does Not Dampen Speculation About Bush Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saying ``it isn't over until the tall, thin
guy sings,'' Gov. John Sununu on Wednesday would not confirm that
President-elect George Bush has picked him to be White House chief
of staff.
   But given several opportunities during a Statehouse news
conference, Sununu did not deny the report either.
   ``Until the vice president decides yes or no _ and he certainly
could decide no in the interim _ I don't really think it's
appropriate for me to comment,'' Sununu said when asked if he has
accepted the chief of staff job.
   ``It isn't over until the tall thin guy sings,'' he said of the
lanky vice president.
   But sources close to Bush who insisted on anonymity said Bush
definitely has chosen Sununu as chief of staff.
   Sununu is seen as a major political creditor of Bush's. He helped
the vice president rebound from defeat in the Iowa caucuses last
February with a critical win in New Hampshire's leadoff primary.
   Sununu, 49, subsequently decided not to seek a record fourth term
as governor and was one of Bush's national co-chairmen for the
general election campaign, traveling widely and appearing on
television programs to attack the Democratic nominee, Michael
Dukakis, governor of neighboring Massachusetts.
   Sununu dined privately with Bush in Florida on Monday evening and
accompanied the vice president back to Washington aboard Air Force
Two on Tuesday before returning to New Hampshire. On Wednesday
Sununu conducted routine state business.
   He also held a news conference at which he confirmed that he
discussed ``that job in particular'' _ the chief of staff post _
with Bush on Monday evening.
   ``We discussed what I might be involved in doing in general,''
Sununu said. ``It included a lot of positions in terms of general
interests, both his interests and my interests, and I'm going to
leave it at that.''
   ``You've heard me say I wouldn't go to Washington just to go to
Washington. I do think that chief of staff with a great president
can make a contribution,'' Sununu added.
   Sununu, an engineer who with his wife, Nancy, has eight children,
has said he was interested in getting a high-paying job in private
business.
   Asked about speculation that Bush might consider a ``troika'' to
head his White House staff consisting of Sununu and transition team
heads Craig Fuller and Robert Teeter, Sununu said, ``Both who is
going to do it and how it's going to be put together is (Bush's)
call.''
   Fuller, at a news conference in Washington, said he asked Bush on
Wednesday about reports that Sununu would be chief of staff.
   ``Let them know (that) when I am ready to make an announcement,
they'll hear it from me,'' Fuller quoted Bush as saying.
   Fuller said he did not know whether Bush had made the decision.
   Sununu would leave Bush with a right-hand aide with no Washington
experience but a reputation in six years as governor as a hands-on,
no-nonsense manager who turned a state deficit into a surplus.
   But some detractors also have called Sununu arrogant and abrasive.
</TEXT>
