<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SmokelessCigarette     11-16 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smokeless Cigarette,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board Asks Reynolds to Voluntarily Withdraw `Smokeless Cigarette'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Smokeout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arizona Board of Pharmacy asked the R.J.
Reynolds Tobacco Co. to voluntarily withdraw its test-marketed
smokeless cigarettes pending a determination of whether it is a
drug, but the company refused.
   The board did not determine whether the Premier cigarette is a
drug delivery system, as critics contend, or a non-burning
cigarette, as the company argues.
   Nor did it act on a request by the American Medical Association
to halt sales of Premier cigarettes in Arizona. A similar request
has been made of state officials in Missouri, where Premier also is
being test-marketed.
   R.J. Reynolds, in a statement from its headquarters in
Winston-Salem, N.C., declined to withdraw Premier from the market.
   ``Acceptance of Premier rests with the smokers, and we believe
they should be the final judges of the cigarette,'' the company said.
   The Arizona board also approved a motion to ask all interested
parties to submit pertinent information dealing with the tobacco
product for possible discussion at its scheduled Jan. 17 meeting.
But board members said a hearing on the issue would be unlikely then.
   The board voted 7-0 on member Michael W. Noel's motion to seek
voluntary withdrawal, after assistant attorney general Timothy J.
Agan declined to give the board legal advice in the public session,
``due to the possibility of litigation.''
   Noel's motion said the board has been unable ``to determine if
Premier is a drug or device over which it has authority to regulate
distribution and sale.''
   He said the board was soliciting information that will lead
ultimately to such a decision, but that ``the process will take
several months to complete.''
   The motion requested the voluntary withdrawal ``due to the
potential hazard to the health and safety of the citizens of
Arizona.''
   Jack LaSota, a former state attorney general representing
Reynolds, had urged the board to take no action on an AMA petition
filed with the board.
   The AMA asked the federal Food and Drug Administration in April
to take jurisdiction over the product as a drug, but the FDA has
been studying the issue and has yet to make a determination.
   Reynolds began test-marketing the product Oct. 1 in parts of
Arizona and Missouri. The AMA on Nov. 2 asked the Arizona board and
the Missouri Department of Health to bar sales.
   LaSota said a decision is expected from the FDA by the end of the
year, ``a scant six weeks away,'' and said the board should not act
before the FDA does.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
