<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ThriftActivity     11-16 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thrift Activity,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Rescues Improve S&L Capital Results for Second Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Savings and loan industry capital increased for
the second consecutive month in September as the government, by
closing and rescuing failed institutions, began transferring the
industry's losses to its own books, the government said Wednesday.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board said capital _ representing the
difference between loans and other assets and deposits and other
liabilities _ increased $2.4 billion in September following a $6.1
billion increase in August. In the first seven months of the year,
the industry lost $6.1 billion in capital.
   Capital declines are often a good indicator of losses, but the
bank board began increasing the pace of S&L rescues in mid-August.
Rescues, in effect, wipe out the red ink of the failed institutions,
transferring it to the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp.,
which insures deposits up to $100,000.
   The industry lost $7.5 billion in the first six months of this
year, and bank board economist James Barth has estimated third
quarter losses at about $2 billion.
   ``Not suprisingly, the use of financial assistance to protect
insured depositors exerts a positive effect on the overall financial
condition of the thrift industry,'' Barth said in a statement.
   The agency has dealt with more than 140 troubled institutions so
far this year.
   Meanwhile, deposits flowed out of the nation's 3,028 S&Ls for the
fifth consecutive month. The drain followed seven months of gains as
investors sought a safe haven for their money after the October 1987
stock market crash.
   Net withdrawals totaled $1.8 billion in September, down from $3.0
billion in August. For the first nine months of the year, S&Ls had
net new deposits of $6.7 billion, compared with net withdrawals of
$13.7 billion during the same period of 1987.
   Thrift institutions' mortgage lending business continued to
suffer with the decline in housing sales and construction. Mortgage
loans closed totaled $23.2 billion, down 5.6 percent from August and
down 12.6 percent from a year ago.
   For the first nine months of 1988, mortgage lending was off by
7.4 percent from the same period a year ago.
</TEXT>
