<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-PLO 1stLd-Writethru a0692 11-16 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0692,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Says No Dialogue Planned with PLO</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 7 grafs with Jerusalem mayor meeting with Reagan</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Wednesday the policy
declaration by the Palestine Liberation Organization's parliament in
exile falls short of U.S. conditions for opening a dialogue with the
PLO.
   Spokesman Charles Redman suggested that the declaration moved the
PLO somewhat closer to U.S. requirements, but he said no dialogue is
contemplated because of ambiguities and other shortcomings in the
statement.
   PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat had said Tuesday in Algiers that he
hoped the declaration would serve as the basis for a revived U.S.
effort to pursue a Middle East peace settlement.
   ``We feel that the ball is now in the American court,'' Arafat
said after the Palestinian National Council approved the declaration
which, among other provisions, accepts U.N. Security Council
resolutions as the basis for a Middle East settlement.
   The two resolutions imply recognition of Israel's right to exist,
but Redman said the PNC statement was insufficient because it was
ambiguous ``both in its meaning and placement in the text.''
   ``Recognition must be clear and unambiguous,'' Redman said.
   He said PLO repudiation of terrorist activities against civilian
targets was a restatement of the previous position. ``It is still
performance that counts,'' Redman said.
   The U.S. position on dealing with the PLO is that no dialogue can
take place until the PLO accepts U.N. Resolutions 242 and 338,
recognizes Israel's right to exist and renounces terrorism.
   The policy has been maintained since the Ford administration.
   The two resolutions call on Israel to withdraw from territories
occupied during the 1967 Arab-Israeli war and assert the right of
all countries in the region to live within secure borders.
   Arafat refused to say explicitly Tuesday whether acceptance of
Resolution 242 meant recognition of Israel.
   The Reagan administration's assessment of the declaration
reflects only a short-term U.S. position because it has only nine
weeks left in office.
   Alluding to the impending leadership change in Washington before
the PNC meeting convened in Algiers, Arafat called on
President-elect George Bush to pressure Israel into making
concessions.
   Bush was non-committal on the PNC declaration when asked about it
Tuesday at a news conference.
   ``If, indeed, there is specific recognition of Security Council
Resolution 242, that would be a very important step forward,'' Bush
said.
   He added that he wanted to be sure such recognition was contained
in the statement before commenting further.
   If the PLO does recognize the resolution without qualifications,
``it would be something that we have been encouraging for a long,
long time and so you would view that with optimism,'' Bush said.
   Despite an overall negative assessment, Redman said there were
some encouraging signs coming out of the PNC meeting.
   He said there were indications that some Palestinians ``are
trying to move the PLO in a constructive way. That's encouraging and
should continue.''
   Meanwhile Wednesday, Mayor Teddy Kollek of Jerusalem met with
President Reagan and said PLO leaders had not advanced prospects for
Middle East peace.
   ``They didn't denounce terrorism; they didn't accept the
existence of Israel; they couched it altogether with all the
resolutions at the U.N. which were denying Israel,'' Kollek told
reporters. ``There was nothing to it ... There is no step forward on
their part which would enable us to negotiate.''
   Israeli Embassy spokesman Yossi Gal said Kollek, who is in the
United States on a fund-raising drive for various projects, met with
Reagan in the Oval Office for 10 minutes.
   Gal said Reagan thanked Kollek for the free access being granted
the faithful of all religions to the holy sites of Jerusalem.
   Kollek said he invited Reagan to visit Jerusalem. The embassy
spokesman said the president thanked him, saying he hadn't yet made
future plans.
   Reagan encouraged Kollek to continue his endeavors at promoting
tolerance in the volatile city he has governed for 23 years, Gal
said.
   Kollek gave Reagan a 1550 map that shows Jerusalem at the center
of the world, what would become the United States a tiny blob on the
side and the Soviet Union not at all.
   ``Every mayor believes his city is the center of the world, but I
have it documented,'' Kollek said he told the president.
</TEXT>
