<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChickensCruelty     11-16 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chickens Cruelty,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmer Charged With Cruelty In Deaths Of 20,000 Chickens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KILLINGLY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A farmer has been accused of cruelty to
animals for allegedly allowing 20,000 chickens to die of
malnutrition and dehydration.
   Timothy Panteleakos, 32, of Canterbury was arrested on the
cruelty charge Tuesday by a Connecticut Humane Society officer. He
was released on a written promise to appear Nov. 28 in Superior
Court.
   Only fires and natural disasters have caused greater poultry
losses in the state, said William Harrington, chief of the
Connecticut Department of Agriculture's livestock division.
   State officials discovered the chickens on Oct. 31 after they
were notified that tens of thousands of chickens were dead or near
death at Panteleakos' farm, said Laurie Greene, the state
veterinarian.
   About 8,700 chickens were living when officials arrived at the
20-acre farm, Greene said. With the farm's feeding machine in
disrepair, officials fed the chickens by hand throughout the night,
using two tons of grain trucked in by the state.
   The health of the malnourished chickens improved after a week,
during which they were fed with a total of seven tons of
state-purchased grain.
   A New Jersey-based chicken rendering company agreed to pick up
the remaining live chickens at no cost.
   Greene said the Agriculture Department and the state Department
of Environmental Protection had cited the farm repeatedly during the
past year on health code and other violations.
   On Sept. 30, a state hearing officer recommended that the farm be
shut down, but Panteleakos appealed the decision to Agriculture
Commissioner Kenneth B. Andersen. The commissioner rejected the
appeal.
   Panteleakos, who operated the farm for about a year and who had
previous poultry farming experience, said the state shares the blame
for the loss.
   Panteleakos contended that the state ignored his requests for
assistance, and that ``health conditions were no worse or better
than other chicken farms.''
   ``This was a farmer in dire need,'' he said. ``I needed financial
help. ... I feel I'm the victim here.''
   Greene disputed Panteleakos' explanation. She said he never
sought help voluntarily, and that local, state and federal agencies
would have offered assistance.
   The 20,000 dead chickens, which officials said died during a
two-week period in late October, were buried in the Killingly dump.
The cost of the grain and disposal of the dead chickens was about
$3,000, Greene said, adding the state probably will seek restitution.
   Cruelty to animals is a misdemeanor punishable by a $75 fine or a
year in jail or both, said Don DuPont, a humane society police
officer.
</TEXT>
