<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Nestle-BabyFormula     11-16 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nestle-Baby Formula,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nestle Commission Gives Company Clean Slate on `Dumping'
Accusations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A watchdog commission founded by the Nestle
company said Wednesday it has found no evidence to support
allegations the international food products giant is violating an
agreement against ``dumping'' infant formula in Third World
countries.
   However, former Secretary of State Edmund Muskie, head of the
11-member commission, acknowledged that the panel had not examined
specific allegations because no specific complaints were filed by an
organization that called last month for a resumption of a boycott of
Nestle products.
   ``The system has broken down to the extent complaints are no
longer submitted to us,'' Muskie said at a news conference.
   A Minneapolis-based group called Action for Corporate
Accountability called for a resumption of the seven-year boycott,
ended in 1984, on grounds Nestle was failing to live up to the
spirit of a World Health Organization-sanctioned agreement on infant
formula marketing that prompted an end to the earlier boycott.
   Muskie acknowledged that his panel could only examine whether
Nestle was following the letter of the agreement since it had no
specific allegations of violations to investigate.
   ``All we have to rely on is a generalized accusation,'' said
Muskie.
   Action for Corporate Accountability charged Oct. 4 that Nestle is
dumping infant formula in Third World countries _ that is, supplying
large quantities of free formula to mothers of newborn infants in an
effort to get the mothers and babies ``hooked'' on bottle feeding
rather than breast feeding.
   Muskie said the commission does not agree with that assessment
and noted that the WHO agreement does not ban the supply of
reasonable amounts of free formula to meet the needs of poor mothers
who need the product and can't afford it.
   ``It is Nestle's standard practice to require that responsible
staff at each health institution complete a detailed request form
before supplies are delivered,'' Muskie said. ``In an effort to make
sure that the quantities required are appropriate, Nestle also
audits the amount of supplies it donates. In some instances, Nestle
has reduced the amount of formula that it provides.''
   Under questioning, Muskie acknowledged that Action for Corporate
Accountability and other Nestle critics apparently have lost
confidence in the panel's credibility since they no longer file
complaints with the committee as they did prior to the 1986 WHO
agreement.
   ``They have accepted our credibility, at least until now,'' he
said. Later, he added, ``We consider that we are in a position to
try to be helpful'' and said, ``We're hoping that out of this
difference of opinion ... we can shape a (new) relationship.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
