<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     11-16 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Sends Troops to Quell Violence, Strikes in South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Wednesday it sent
army reinforcements to break a wave of violence, demonstrations and
strikes by Sinhalese extremists that has paralyzed a southern region.
   Extremists hurled a bomb at a bus in Ja-ela, about 10 miles north
of Colombo, injuring nine people, said officials who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The strikes, which began two weeks ago, have closed schools,
shops and offices and brought public transportation to a stop in the
Southern Province, one of the eight provinces of Sri Lanka.
   Additional soldiers were sent to the province after its top
official, Chief Minister M.S. Amarasiri, appealed for help.
Amarasiri said the troops would try to force people to return to
work.
   On Tuesday, the army opened fire on thousands of people in towns
just north of Colombo who were protesting the massacre of 27
Sinhalese bus passengers by suspected Tamil rebels, police said.
Five protesters were killed.
   Military officials, who demanded anonymity, said Monday's bus
attack in a village north of Colombo was part of a battle by Sri
Lanka's minority Tamils to drive the majority Sinhalese from the
northeast, where the rebels have waged a five-year campaign for an
independent homeland.
   The Tamils, who represent 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million
people, claim they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who
form 75 percent of the population and control the military and the
government.
   The government's peace overtures to the Tamils have sparked a
backlash among extremist Sinhalese, who claim too many concessions
have been offered to the minority community.
   The Southern Province, which has a majority Sinhalese population,
is the center of the anti-government sentiment.
   On Tuesday, Sinhalese radicals shot and killed at least seven
fellow Sinhalese, the military officials said.
   Four of the victims died in Elpitiya, about 50 miles south of
Colombo, and the other three were bus drivers killed on the job, the
officials said.
   The People's Liberation Front, a radical Sinhalese group, called
strikes throughout the country two weeks ago in an attempt to force
President Junius R. Jayewardene to dissolve Parliament and resign.
   They have accused Jayewardene, who is Sinhalese, of selling out
the interests of this island nation's majority ethnic group to
pacify the Tamils.
   The extremists have rejected a July 1987 peace accord that
offered the Tamils limited autonomy if they surrendered their arms.
They have vowed to kill anyone who supports the accord and are
blamed for the deaths of more than 550 people, mostly Sinhalese
government officials and their supporters.
   The Tamils also rejected the accord and are fighting government
troops and Indian peacekeeping forces sent to Sri Lanka last year.
   To combat the spiraling violence in the south, Jayewardene issued
emergency decrees that allow the army to open fire on
anti-government demonstrators and to arrest anyone instigating
strikes. People convicted of starting strikes are subject to death
by hanging.
</TEXT>
