<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Strikes     11-16 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Strikes,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mail, Phone Service Restored As Workers End Walkouts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mail was being delivered and phone
calls were getting through Wednesday after workers ended strikes
that had paralyzed postal and long-distance telephone services.
   Federal court clerks and teachers also ended walkouts in what has
been a months-long effort by the state's approximately one million
employees to win pay boosts to keep up with triple-digit inflation
and recover lost purchasing power.
   The government, which has tried to tightly control increases in
state pay, warned Tuesday night that it will not depart from an
inflation-fighting program adopted in August despite pressure from
unions and business groups.
   Economy Minister Juan Sourrouille, speaking to the Argentine
Chamber of Commerce, said: ``There will be no modification in our
program of stabilization.'' He said inflation-fanning pay increases
will not be tolerated.
   Inflation slowed to 9 percent in October compared with 11.7
percent in September and 27.6 percent in August. Inflation has
soared more than 300 percent since January and more than 440 percent
for the 12-month period ending Sept. 30.
   The government has said business leaders agreed to limit price
increases to below 4 percent a month, and promised that monthly
public utility rate increases will not surpass that amount.
   Postal workers voted Tuesday night to end their 26-day work
stoppage after the Labor Ministry warned that it would declare the
strike illegal, allowing time lost to the strike to be deducted from
pay.
   Unions representing about 30,000 postal workers began their
strike more than three weeks ago to obtain what leaders said was $4
million in unpaid overtime and bonuses.
   Telephone workers ended their 36-hour walkout Tuesday afternoon
when state telephone company officials agreed to complete payment of
a second installment of wage arrears. The strike had affected
long-distance calls, customer service and repair work.
   In separate strike action, federal court workers in the capital
and the provinces of Buenos Aires, Rio Negro, Chubut, Neuquen, Santa
Cruz and the territory of Tierra del Fuego struck for 24 hours
Tuesday to press for an immediate wage adjustment.
   Union leaders said teachers in Buenos Aires and the country's
northeastern provinces took part in a walkout Tuesday in support of
pay demands and recognition of a union wage policy committee.
   At the Economy Ministry some 1,800 employees remained off the job
for a third day Wednesday in an indefinite walkout that started
Monday in search of pay increases.
</TEXT>
