<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-PoliceSlaying     11-16 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Police Slaying,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Members of Paramilitary Force Shot To Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGNARA DI ROMAGNA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five members of the elite
Carabinieri paramilitary force were shot and killed Wednesday in
their barracks in central Italy, officials said.
   Italian news agencies said investigators speculated one of the
Carabinieri went berserk, killed the other four with submachine-gun
fire, and then took his own life with his service revolver.
   The news agency AGI quoted prosecutor Aldo Ricciuti as ruling out
an attack by terrorists or common criminals.
   Interior Minister Antonio Gava told Parliament Wednesday night
that there was no evidence of ``an attack from outside.''
   ``Still, at the moment it is not possible to formulate hypotheses
on the exact sequence of events,'' he said.
   A passer-by heard shots at about noon and alerted police, who
found the bodies in one room of the barracks, said a spokesman at
the Rome headquarters of the Carabinieri.
   The official, speaking on the usual condition on anonymity, said
investigators had no immediate clue as to who carried out the
killings and why.
   The agencies said at least 11 submachine shells were found along
with two spent pistol shells.
   Bagnara di Romagna is a town of 2,000 people near Ravenna, about
215 miles northeast of Rome.
</TEXT>
