<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bishops 1stLd-Writethru a0670 11-16 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishops, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0670,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishops Reject Vatican Document _ Politely</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with fresh quotes, action on lay preachers, adds 7
grafs at end</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT FURLOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Conference of Catholic Bishops on
Wednesday rejected a draft Vatican document that questioned the
authority of conferences such as theirs.
   First, however, the bishops greatly softened the tone of their
reply, removing the confrontational language of an earlier version.
   Cardinal Joseph Bernardin of Chicago said of the Vatican draft,
``We think the document is so flawed that the Holy See should start
over.'' His fellow bishops agreed to send essentially that message
to Rome, by a 205-59 vote that was barely above the necessary
two-thirds of the conference's 305 active members.
   The Vatican has asked all national bishops conferences to respond
to its draft document on the role of such bodies in the church, and
no final version is expected for months or even years.
   American bishops on both sides of the issue decried any
suggestion that the issue amounted to a significant dispute between
the Vatican and themselves.
   Pope John Paul II has publicly praised the American bishops' most
controversial efforts _ their national pastoral letters taking issue
with Reagan administration policies on nuclear weapons and on
treatment of the poor.
   However, Vatican officials, noting the rising prominence of
national bishops conferences, have taken pains to point out publicly
that such organizations are not part of the Roman church's
traditional hierarchy.
   The Vatican draft attempts to make that same point, saying
bishops conferences have little real standing, that the church
lodges authority in the individual bishops under the pope, the
bishop of Rome.
   The U.S. bishops, in their reply, do not lay out a case arguing
that the Vatican is wrong. Rather, they argue that the Vatican
distorts some evidence and gives only one side of the matter in its
draft.
   Earlier this week, as the conference's annual meeting got under
way, Bishop James Malone of Youngstown, Ohio, a former conference
president, announced that the proposed notice of rejection _ already
widely publicized in news stories _ had been rewritten.
   Gone from the bishops' proposed description of the Vatican draft
were such phrases as ``rigid and confusing'' and ``overly defensive
and negative.''
   Then Wednesday, by voice vote, the bishops deleted these words:
``non placet _ the draft is not suitable.'' Several bishops had
argued that the phrase, especially the formal Latin, was too blunt,
bordering on being offensive to the Vatican.
   Still, the final version says elsewhere, ``We do not believe that
the working document is suitable as a basis for discussion.''
   Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston called for removal of that
sentence, too, but when he saw the other side had more votes he
withdrew his amendment, saying, ``Half a loaf is better than none.''
   Some bishops have criticized news accounts of the dispute.
   However, Archbishop John Roach of St. Paul-Minneapolis, another
former conference president who served on Malone's committee in
preparing the bishops' response, said the news media ``did us a real
favor'' in publicizing negative aspects of the original version of
the response.
   ``They perceived a sharpness in the tone of the document which I
don't think we intended'' and helped spur the bishops to change that
tone, he said at a news conference.
   On another topic, the bishops voted Wednesday to set guidelines
on who can preach during Catholic masses, and when.
   Several bishops said the guidelines could lead to more preaching
by lay men and women. But others noted the guidelines' clear
strictures against anyone other than an ordained minister giving the
main sermon interpreting the gospel during mass.
   Retired Bishop William McManus of Fort Wayne-South Bend, Ind.,
argued that reiterating that implicit ban on some preaching by women
_ who cannot be ordained as Catholic ministers _ would be an
unnecessary new ``source of irritation'' for women in the
denomination.
   He put forward what he described as the ridiculous possibility
that a local church would have Mother Teresa as its guest but could
allow her to speak only early in the service or at the very end,
leaving the main sermon to a male deacon parroting ``Bible lessons
he learned in the second grade.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
