<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storm Dumps Snow on Minnesota</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm dumped up to 10 inches of snow on the Canadian-Minnesota
border on Wednesday as an intense low-pressure system moved into
Canada. Gusty winds blew from the northern Plains through the upper
and middle Mississippi Valley and the Great Lakes.
   Temperatures plunged in Illinois on the heels of a storm system
that created as many as 49 tornadoes Tuesday in five states in the
South and Midwest. In Chicago, city workers scrambled Wednesday to
repair downed traffic lights, clear fallen trees and open sewers
clogged by heavy rains.
   An inch of rain fell in less than two hours Wednesday morning at
Fort Wayne, Ind.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered along the cold front
that extended across the Ohio and Tennessee valleys into the central
Gulf Coast.
   Snow and blowing snow brought hazardous weather to much of
Minnesota. Ten inches of snow fell at International Falls by
Wednesday morning, and amounts of 4 to 8 inches were reported from
central into northeast Minnesota.
   Winds guested to 56 mph at Traverse City, Mich., and Cleveland
and to 51 mph at Lansing, Mich., early Wednesday afternoon.
   Cold air spread throughout the Plains and Mississippi Valley.
Temperatures at midday were 30 to 40 degrees colder than at the same
time Tuesday from eastern Kansas into western and northern Missouri.
Temperatures were 20 degrees colder from northern Illinois into
Texas.
   Rain fell from western Oregon into northern and central
California.
   Snow advisories were posted across the Cascades of Washington
state and Oregon for Wednesday night, with snowfalls of 4 to 8
inches predicted by Thursday morning.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST
included nearly an inch at Jackson, Miss., and more than
three-quarters of an inch at Sault Ste. Marie, Mich.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 10
degrees in Havre, Mont., to 88 in Fort Myers and Tampa, Florida. The
low in the nation Wednesday morning was 7 degrees below zero at
Havre.
   Thursday's forecast called rain likely across New England and the
mid-Atlantic Coast, with rain diminishing over the upper Ohio
Valley. Showers and thunderstorms were expected to be scattered from
the Carolinas into Florida. Snow showers should occur across parts
of upper Michigan and northern lower Michigan. Rain also was
predicted to be scattered across the Pacific Northwest into northern
and central California valleys, with snow widespread from the
northern Rockies into the central Intermountain region west of the
central Rockies and the Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah.
   High temperatures were forecast to be in the 40s or 50s across
much of the nation, 30s from the northern Rockies through the
northern Plains and upper Mississippi Valley into the upper Great
Lakes, 60s from Southern California through the southern Rockies,
the southern Plains, the lower Mississippi Valley and southern
Appalachians and into the mid-Atlantic Coast, 70s in southern
Arizona and the Rio Grande Valley of Texas, and from the Florida
Panhandle to the Carolinas coast. Highs should be in the 80s in
central and southern Florida.
</TEXT>
