<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OrkinSentencing     11-16 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Orkin Sentencing,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orkin Gets $350,000 Fine, Probation In Fatal Fumigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge who criticized Orkin
Exterminating Co.'s ``scary'' disregard of safety standards fined
the corporation $350,000 Wednesday for a fumigation that killed a
Galax couple.
   ``It's almost a miracle that something like this didn't happen
before,'' U.S. District Judge James Turk said in sentencing Orkin
for failing to monitor the air in the home of Hubert and Freida
Watson after it was fumigated on Sept. 25, 1986. Watson, 73, died
three days after the fumigation with the chemical Vikane, and Mrs.
Watson, 65, died in three more days.
   ``I have no doubt at all but that they died from Vikane
poisoning,'' the judge said. ``It's nothing short of scary the way
the company was handling its business.''
   Turk imposed the maximum $500,000 fine, but told Orkin officials
they will only have to pay $350,000 if the company stays out of
trouble for a two-year probationary period. The judge also ordered
corporate officials to perform 2,000 hours of community service,
although none of the officials was named a defendant in the case.
   ``I think naturally we're disappointed,'' Orkin spokeswoman Judy
Donner said Wednesday evening from the company's Atlanta
headquarters. ``The company wants to express sympathy to the Watson
family for the loss.''
   Orkin President Bob Mercer was the final witness in the two-day
sentencing hearing for Orkin's one-count conviction. The company was
convicted of failing to follow directions on the label of the Vikane
container when it did not monitor the air in the Watson home as the
fumigation tent shrouding the home was removed and the Watsons were
allowed back inside.
   Evidence indicated Orkin also failed to remove a waterproof
mattress cover that could have trapped the poisonous gas.
   ``That was a tomb sealed up, waiting for the occupants to enter
and lay down and die,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Richard Pierce said.
   Orkin reached an out-of-court settlement with the family's estate
two months ago. Neither side has disclosed the terms.
   Several past and present Orkin employees testified that
throughout numerous fumigations in Virginia, safety standards,
including the air monitoring, were never followed. The former Orkin
employee who supervised the fumigation, Ronald Dean Mullins,
testified that he had never even read the ``fine print'' on a Vikane
label.
   ``I recognize there was a failure to carry out Orkin's policy and
procedure,'' Mercer testified Wednesday. He said that since he
became president in February, the company has worked to improve its
training.
   Ms. Donner would not comment when asked whether Orkin procedures
were being followed in other states.
   Asked whether Orkin management monitors compliance or
noncompliance with safety standards throughout the nation, Ms.
Donner said, ``I think I'd like to stick to comment on the case
itself.''
   Turk convicted Orkin in August after the government and the
company agreed to a set of facts concerning the exterminator's
failure to use the air monitor. The judge threw out four other
counts alleging unsafe application of the Vikane.
   Defense attorney Sam Wilson said monitoring the Watson home for
Vikane might not have made a difference, because in 1986, the pest
control industry used monitors that have since become outdated. But
the judge said that testimony indicated the old monitors erred on
the side of safety.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
