<DOCNO> AP881116-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1957EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Philippines     11-16 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Official Doesn't Rule Out Soldiers Behind Disappearances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top military officer said Wednesday
that soldiers or police could be behind some of the recent
disappearances of scores of human rights activists and unionists.
   But Brig. Gen. Alexander Aguirre, the Manila-area regional
commander, also said in a telephone interview that reports of
disappearances could be part of a smear campaign to discredit the
armed forces.
   ``It could be that they voluntarily disappeared, or people went
underground,'' Aguirre said. ``It appears also there is a pattern of
smear campaign, of making conclusions that disappearances were
caused by the military.''
   Aguirre did not rule out that military personnel were responsible
for some of the disappearances.
   ``The other possibility is that it could have been done by some
of our agents,'' Aguirre added. ``That's not sanctioned by the
military.''
   Meanwhile, suspected communist rebels fatally shot an officer of
President Corazon Aquino's guards Wednesday as he was driving along
a coastal highway south of the capital.
   Police said Lt. Jerson Nueva, 31, an officer of Mrs. Aquino's
elite Presidential Security Group, was found slumped at the wheel of
his car with a gunshot wound in the head.
   Police speculated that Nueva may have been slain by communist
guerrillas. The rebels have claimed responsibility for killing
soldiers and policemen here since 1987.
   Also Wednesday, military chief of staff Gen. Renato de Villa
summoned senior officers to discuss the recent wave of
disappearances of trade unionists, human rights workers and
leftists. Aguirre was among those attending the session.
   Armed forces spokesman Col. Oscar Florendo said he had no
knowledge of the meeting, but added the military is preparing a
report within the week on the cases of 73 missing unionists.
   The Task Force Detainees of the Philippines, a church-affiliated
organization, says 82 social activists, leftists and trade union
organizers have disappeared nationwide during the first six months
of 1988.
   The left-wing New Patriotic Alliance said 15 of its members had
disappeared in the Manila area so far this year.
   Military officials claim the Alliance is a front for the banned
Communist Party of the Philippines, which has been waging a
19-year-old insurgency to establish a Marxist state.
   Amnesty International reported this year that more than 100
leftist and social activists were slain in the Philippines in 1987,
apparently by military and paramilitary groups battling the
communist insurgency.
   Leftist and human rights groups have blamed the military for the
disappearances which they say is part of an effort to crush legal
left-wing organizations.
   On Tuesday, Mrs. Aquino said allegations that the military was
behind the disappearances were ``premature and unfounded.''
   Mrs. Aquino succeeded Ferdinand Marcos in a February 1986 popular
uprising and pledged to end the human rights abuses that were
rampant during her predecessor's 20-year administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
