<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drugs-Kerry     11-16 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drugs-Kerry,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kerry: Military Aid, Marshall Plan Needed To Help Latin America
Fight Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a Senate narcotics panel said
Wednesday that Latin American drug cartels pose a ``more immediate
and effective'' national security threat than the spread of
communism, and the United States should be willing to provide
military aid to drug-fighting nations.
   ``The drug cartels do represent a national security threat to the
United States and our friends and allies abroad. The sooner we
understand this fact of life, the sooner we can begin waging a
serious war on drugs,'' said Sen. John F. Kerry, D-Mass. ```Just Say
No' is just not enough. It just hasn't worked.''
   Kerry, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee on
narcotics, terrorism and international operations, said the new
administration must focus its national security initiatives on the
narcotics trade.
   ``In the post-World War II era, the national security focus of
the United States was framed by our predominate concern with ...
Marxist expansion,'' which led to ``a series of extraordinary steps
to respond to that threat'' such as the Marshall Plan, NATO, the
nuclear buildup and involvement in Korea and Vietnam, Kerry said.
   ``Now we must take equally drastic steps to combat the new threat
to our national security, the tide of drugs which are flooding our
hemisphere,'' he said.
   Outlining a ``Strategic Drug Initiative'' in remarks prepared for
an evening address at Georgetown University, Kerry said the Bush
administration should be willing to provide, with congressional
approval, military assistance to Latin American governments trying
to fight drug trafficking.
   ``If our allies need hardware to fight the war on drugs, we
should give it to them,'' Kerry said. ``If they want help in taking
out a cocaine processing lab, we should provide that assistance. If
they want help in the tracking of drug traffickers on aircraft and
ships, we should offer that help.''
   The senator also advocated a sweeping economic aid program,
similar to the Marshall Plan imposed after World War II to help
Western Europe, to bolster devastated Latin American economies and
help reduce their reliance on the drug trade.
   ``All of us are concerned about the spread of communism in Latin
America and elsewhere, but we cannot afford to put on blinders to
other threats which are equally grave. Drugs in this hemisphere are
an equal threat, and they are a more immediate and effective
threat,'' the senator said.
   Kerry, whose subcommittee has been investigating drug trafficking
in Latin America for two years, also called for a drug summit with
Western Hemisphere presidents, stiffer bank regulations to halt
money laundering and improved information exchanges among various
U.S. intelligence agencies.
</TEXT>
