<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Florida-Senate     11-16 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Florida-Senate,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MacKay Concedes Florida Senate Race To Mack 8 Days After Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OCALA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Kenneth ``Buddy'' MacKay conceded the
Florida U.S. Senate race to Republican Connie Mack on Wednesday,
eight days after their tight election.
   ``This election is over,'' MacKay told reporters at his home here.
   He said he would challenge none of the alleged irregularities
that had spurred him to ask for second looks at the voting in five
large counties.
   ``We have satisfied ourselves that all the votes that were cast
were counted, and that's all we wanted,'' said the 55-year-old,
three-term congressman, who lost by more than 31,000 votes. ``The
people have spoken. Congratulations to Connie Mack.''
   Mack, vacationing in Vermont, told The Associated Press:
``Obviously, I'm very excited. It's been a long election night that
has gone from 24 hours to seven days, and we're delighted to have it
over with.''
   Mack had claimed victory Nov. 10 after absentee ballots gave him
a decisive lead.
   He got 2,048,458 votes to MacKay's 2,016,867 _ a lead of 31,591
out of nearly 4.1 million votes cast in the race, in unofficial
returns.
   MacKay dismissed suggestions he had tarnished his reputation by
refusing to concede earlier.
   ``One thing worse than sour grapes is rotten grapes and that's
what we would have had'' if some voters felt their votes were lost,
MacKay said, referring to his campaign's claim that up to 170,000
votes for the Senate race may have been missed in totals.
   He said he was making sure that Florida voters were protected,
which should only help his reputation.
   His campaign cited steep drop-offs from presidential to Senate
vote totals in four large counties. MacKay showed charts here
reporting that in 63 of 67 counties, there were more Senate votes
than presidential votes.
   After his narrow loss, MacKay said sharp drop-offs in the Senate
vote totals compared with other races could have indicated computer
problems.
   MacKay was unwilling to prolong his challenge, however, by filing
lawsuits to seek court-ordered recounts.
   The Mack campaign said a variety of other factors, including
voter apathy or indecisiveness, could be blamed for the drop-offs in
the Senate race.
   Palm Beach County officials did a spot-check of some precincts
Wednesday and found no evidence of the computer irregularities
alleged by MacKay.
   MacKay, accompanied by his wife, Anne, said he hadn't had time to
decide about whether he will ever seek an elective office again.
   Meanwhile, U.S. Rep. Bill Chappell, D-Fla., remained in seclusion
Wednesday, refusing to comment on a request Tuesday by his
successor, political newcomer Craig James, to concede defeat. A
recount showed James won by 725 votes out of more than 250,000 cast
in the northeast Florida congressional district.
</TEXT>
