<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Palestinians-USReax     11-16 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Palestinians-US Reax,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Moves Evoke Pride In Arab-Americans; Jews Call Declaration A
Smokescreen</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab-Americans responded with pride and hope to this week's PLO
declaration of a Palestinian state, while a leading Jewish group on
Wednesday called the pronouncements in Algeria ``a phony gesture.''
   In Algiers on Tuesday, Yasser Arafat, chairman of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, declared an independent Palestinian state
with Jerusalem as its capital. He also said the organization was
renouncing terrorism and had endorsed key United Nations resolutions
on the Middle East, including one that partitioned British-mandated
Palestine into Jewish and Arab states.
   ``I am very excited, very happy and optimistic,'' said Sana
Ahmad, a Palestinian-American who attends classes at William
Paterson College in Wayne, N.J.
   ``I think more people now recognize this is not just an Israeli
problem but also a Palestinian problem,'' she said. ``People here
are questioning more, they're realizing that there are two sides to
the story.''
   In downtown St. Louis on Tuesday, about 200 people marched in
support of the declaration. Some carried Palestinian flags and wore
black-and-white checkered kafiyehs, Arab headdresses; others held
banners stating, ``Palestinian Statehood Now'' and
``Self-determination for Palestine.''
   ``We are here as Palestinian and Arab-Americans gathered to bless
and support the declaration of an independent Palestinian state. We
are for peace and prosperity for the whole region,'' said Dr. Z.A.
Dalu, chairman of the Arab-American Community Center of St. Louis.
   ``It is now up to the Israeli government to abide by U.N.
Resolution 242, which calls for independence and prosperity for
every state.''
   But in New York, the head of the Conference of Presidents of
Major American Jewish Organizations said the Palestine National
Council's actions announced by Arafat amounted to smokescreens.
   ``I say it is a phony gesture. ... What we have here is a
declaration for propaganda,'' said Morris B. Abram, chairman of the
conference that represents 46 American Jewish organizations.
   The PLO announcement gives the ``impression of moderation on
behalf of a violent purpose.''
   He noted that Arafat declined to specify whether the PLO's
acceptance of the United Nations resolutions meant an explicit
acceptance of the Jewish state.
   The Palestine National Council, the parliament in exile, rejected
terrorism, but accepted guerrilla actions in Israel and the
territories it has occupied since the 1967 war, he added.
   ``This is a forecast of more terrorism to come _ and not only in
the so-called occupied territories,'' said Abram.
</TEXT>
