<1ST_LINE>r p AM-WyoCanvass     11-16 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wyo Canvass,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Vote Count Shows Wallop Won in Wyoming; Recount May Be
Asked</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials verified on Wednesday U.S.
Sen. Malcolm Wallop's defeat of Democratic challenger John Vinich by
1,322 votes and they awaited Vinich's decision on asking for a
recount.
   After the state canvassing board confirmed the results of the
Senate race as well as Wyoming's U.S. House contest, the
presidential race and other races, a national Democratic leader told
Secretary of State Kathy Karpan that Vinich had not told him whether
he would ask for a recount.
   State law calls for an automatic recount if the victory margin is
less than 1 percent of the votes received by the apparent winner.
   The canvassing board's figures reveal Wallop collected 91,143
votes to Vinich's 89,821, putting the race outside the 911-vote
difference that would trigger a recount.
   Wyoming's election code allows candidates to request another
count of an election, but they must pay for the exercise.
   A recount would cost Vinich, a 38-year-old state senator, up to
$11,500. He has until Friday afternoon to file for a recount and
make a $100 deposit.
   Bob Chlopak, executive director of the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee, told Karpan that Democratic officials had no
doubt that Wyoming officials were careful in their election work,
but Vinich may want a recount anyway because of the narrow margin.
   Karpan, a Democrat, said she told Vinich in a conversation a few
days ago that if he has a ``shadow of a doubt'' about the election
results, he should ask for a recount.
</TEXT>
