<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital Kidnapping, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0750,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Accused Abductor of Newborn Pleads Innocent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 1st graf, 7th graf, `Mrs. Rutherford,' and penultimate
graf to change kidnapping to abduction. Subs 4th graf with four
grafs to UPDATE with authorities changing charge from kidnapping to
permanent detention, also a felony. Picks up 5th graf pvs `Ms. Smith
will....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MELISSA CONTI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The woman accused of abducting a newborn
baby pleaded innocent Wednesday by reason of mental disease or
defect and will be examined by psychiatrists on her ability to stand
trial.
   Acqunetta Rushon Smith, 32, was arrested at her Hot Springs home
on Monday after police received a tip from an anonymous caller.
   Capt. Bob H. Moore of the Little Rock Police said Tuesday that
Ms. Smith wanted to have a child by her boyfriend and that the two
``were very much wanting to have a baby boy.''
   Ms. Smith is charged with ``permanent detention or restraint'' in
the abduction of 3-day-old Christopher Michael Jones from Doctors
Hospital on Nov. 1. , said Chief Deputy Prosecutor Lloyd King.
   She had been charged with kidnapping, to which she pleaded
innocent Tuesday. The charge was changed Wednesday, King said,
because Arkansas law defines kidnapping as an abduction for the
purpose of holding someone for a ransom, as a hostage, or to hurt
the victim.
   Authorities said the premature infant was well taken care of
during the two weeks he was missing.
   The permanant detention charge, which involves holding or
concealing a person ``without ever releasing him, without ever
returning him to the person or instituation from whose lawful
custody he was taken,'' is a felony. Like kidnapping, it is
punishable by five to 20 years in prison and a fine of up to $15,000.
   Ms. Smith will be examined by psychiatrists who will report to
Pulaski County Circuit Court on her ability to stand trial,
according to Bill Simpson, public defender. She pleaded innocent
Tuesday in Little Rock Municipal Court and was denied bond.
   Lisa Rutherford, a registered nurse, said in an interview that
Ms. Smith was a loving person and took care of her terminally ill
sister who died early this year.
   Mrs. Rutherford said she saw news of Ms. Smith's arrest on
television and couldn't believe she was charged with the abduction
because ``she seemed so level-headed.''
   Ms. Smith's sister, whose identify was not revealed because of
patient confidentiality, died early this year. Mrs. Rutherford would
not reveal the woman's illness.
   ``She (Ms. Smith) could have deserted her sister,'' Mrs.
Rutherford said. ``A lot of patients that come in here that have a
very bad illness, their families just totally turn on them.
   ``She could have done that easily but she didn't,'' said Mrs.
Rutherford, an assistant head nurse at the University of Arkansas
for Medical Sciences.
   Ms. Smith allegedly posed as a nurse and took Christopher from
the room of Annette Thomas-Jones. Mrs. Thomas-Jones and her husband,
Willie Jones, made several appeals to the abductor through the
media. A reward totaling $27,500 was offered for the child's safe
return. Police are to announce the disposition of the reward on
Thursday.
   Ms. Smith is divorced, has four children of her own and cares for
her sister's child.
</TEXT>
