<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Stand-Off,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Take Man Into Custody After Stand-Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE LLOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man suspected of stealing an unmarked state
police car filled with weapons held police at bay for 1{ hours
Wednesday while threatening to hang himself, authorities said.
   Police were trying to serve a warrant for Andrew Kane's arrest in
the Nov. 8 theft when the suspect spotted the officers and ran down
a street about 2:30 p.m., Detective Edward Tenuto said.
   Kane ended up on the roof of a row house with one end of a rope
tied around his neck and the other around a pipe, Tenuto said.
   Officer William Ervin, one of three officers who helped talk the
29-year-old Kane into surrendering, said the suspect was worried
about charges in the theft case.
   Kane surrendered at 4 p.m. and was charged with auto theft,
receiving stolen property and weapons violations, police said.
   The unmarked state police car was stolen in Philadelphia while a
trooper visited relatives. In the trunk was a grenade launcher, tear
gas grenades, a submachine gun, a .357-caliber revolver, two
shotguns, ammunition and rappelling hooks and other equipment used
to scale buildings.
   The stolen car was used by Sgt. Charles Rogers, a member of the
state police's Strategic Emergency Team. Authorities said team
members normally carry the weapons and equipment in their cars
because they are on call 24 hours a day.
   City police found the car about two hours after it was reported
missing. The car's trunk had been forced open and the weapons were
missing.
   All but two shotguns and a handgun have been recovered, police
said.
   On Saturday, police arrested Kelsey Little, 18, of Philadelphia
in the case. Little was charged with buying the submachine gun,
receiving stolen property and possessing 20 vials of crack, police
said.
</TEXT>
