<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Elections     11-16 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Elections,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Party Recognizes Salinas Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main opposition party Wednesday ended its
fight to overturn the results of the July 6 election and said Carlos
Salinas de Gortari can legitimize his presidency by ensuring
democracy.
   The conservative National Action Party said however it still
maintained that Salinas, of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party, won the presidency in a fraudulent election.
   Abel Vicencio Tovar, National Action Party secretary general,
told a news conference that Salinas should begin his term on Dec. 1
with ``a transition to a real democracy.''
   Vicencio Tovar said the president-elect could ``legitimize
himself before the Mexican people with the just exercise of his own
power'' and by ``respecting the popular mandate of democratization,
pluralism, social justice and national sovereignty.''
   It was the first time that a major Mexican opposition party
publicly accepted Salinas' victory. National Action's presidential
candidate, Manuel J. Clouthier, previously had called upon President
Miguel de la Madrid to annul the election results and appoint an
interim president until a new ballot could be held.
   According to the Federal Election Commission, Salinas won with
slightly more than 50 percent, the slimmest margin of victory in the
ruling party's 59-year history. Presidential candidates fielded by
the governing party traditionally have won with at least 70 percent
of the vote.
   The PRI, as the ruling party is known has not lost a presidential
election since its founding in 1929.
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of the leftist National Democratic Front
coalition came in second with 31 percent and Clouthier finished
third with 17 percent, according to the governing party-dominated
commission.
   Vicencio Tovar released a National Action Party statement
demanding that Salinas' administration initiate ``a peaceful and
civilized evolution toward social and political coexistence, based
on respect of the human, social and political rights of all Mexicans.
   ``In this way, we will advance toward a more just, free,
participative society in which pluralism is an integral part of the
state structure,'' the statement said.
   Saying National Action had adopted a position as ``a responsible
democratic opposition,'' the statement also outlined policy demands
for the new president, including fixing foreign debt service
payments to a percentage of export revenues, capping the growth of
the $104 billion foreign debt, support for small businesses, better
living conditions for farm workers, and conservation of national
resources.
   The party also called for a revision of Mexico's election code to
ensure fraud-free elections.
</TEXT>
