<HEAD>Peggy Lee to Disney: Is That All There Is?</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Disney officials' with no comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Peggy Lee _ whose hits have asked the
questions ``Why Don't You Do Right?'' and ``Is That All There Is?''
_ demanded answers Wednesday as she announced the filing of a
lawsuit against Walt Disney Productions.
   Miss Lee, who co-wrote the lyrics and performed songs and voices
for Disney's cartoon classic, ``Lady and the Tramp,'' said she
hasn't received any money from the movie's considerable
videocassette sales.
   She told reporters at a Manhattan news conference that she only
received a little over $4,000 for her original work on the 1955
movie.
   In a $25 million lawsuit filed Tuesday in Los Angeles County
Superior Court, she charged that Disney has ignored a 1952 contract
provision that barred the company from making ``phonograph
recordings and-or transcriptions for sale to the public'' without
her consent.
   Her attorney, Alvin Deutsch, said that provision applied to
videotapes. But he acknowledged that Disney maintains that
``transcriptions'' referred only to sheet music.
   Tania Steele, director of publicity for Disney video, said, ``We
can't comment on litigation.''
   Miss Lee said she noticed the contract provision only after she
helped Disney promote the videotape version of ``Lady and the
Tramp,'' which she said has sold more than 3{ million copies.
   In the movie, she said, she played the voices of Peg the dog, two
Siamese cats and the human mother referred to only as Darling.
   Miss Lee, 68, She said she received a $500 honorarium for her
promotional work. ``My hairdresser makes more than that,'' she said.
   When she approached Disney about getting a cut of the movie's
profits, she said, ``I was ignored in a polite way, like, `Go away,
kid, don't bother me.' ... Considering the circumstances, it was
rude.''
</TEXT>
