<2ND_LINE>AM-OAS-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0760,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Calls for New U.S. Policy on Central America</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs `Meanwhile, Honduran ...' with five grafs
to
list countries the Honduran foreing minister is meeting and UPDATE
with Guatemala calling for Central American summit</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua on Wednesday called
the Reagan administration's Central America policy a failure and
urged President-elect George Bush to formulate a new one based on
dialogue and mutual respect.
   The Nicaraguan position was expressed in a speech to the
Organization of American States General Assembly by Carlos
Tunnerman, Nicaragua's ambassador to the OAS.
   Tunnerman served as ambassador to the United States until he was
expelled by Washington in July in retaliation for the leftist
Sandinista government's expulsion of U.S. Ambassador Richard Melton
and seven other American diplomats.
   ``The failure of U.S. policy in the (Central American) region
should make the new U.S. authorities reflect and should inspire them
to construct a new era of relations with the region,'' Tunnerman
told OAS delegates.
   ``Threats and the use of force should be proscribed forever.
Intervention should cease. Concepts of zones of influence or
strategic reserves should be abandoned ... reason should prevail
over force and dialogue over pressure,'' he said.
   Since 1981, the Reagan administration has supported Nicaraguan
rebels known as Contras in their bid to overthrow the Sandinistas.
U.S. military aid to the Contras expired in February, and most of
the rebels fled to Honduras.
   The Sandinistas and Contras signed a cease-fire agreement in
March, but talks on a permanent truce broke down in September.
   Meanwhile, Honduran Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras told
the OAS assembly that he and his counterparts from Nicaragua, El
Salvador, Guatemala and Costa Rica would meet in Mexico on Nov. 30
in an effort to breathe new life into the stalled Central American
peace process.
   In Guatemala, President Vinicio Cerezo Arevalo on Wednesday said
he would press for a summit meeting of Central American presidents
before Bush is inaugurated on Jan. 20.
   Cerezo said the summit agenda would include the re-establishment
of a verification commission to monitor compliance with a regional
peace plan signed in August 1987. Other topics could include forming
a Central American parliament and environmental issues affecting the
area.
   The Central American presidents had considered meeting later this
month to further define the peace plan.
   The pact, by Costa Rican President Oscar Arias, seeks to end wars
in Nicaragua, El Salvador and Guatemala and was signed by those four
countries and Honduras.
</TEXT>
