<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Testing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0656,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massachusetts High Court Rejects AIDS Testing Regulations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3 grafs for 8th graf, `Singer issued ...' to UPDATE with
Gov. Dukakis' reaction to decision. Picks up 9th graf pvs, `Only
California ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Massachusetts Supreme Court on Wednesday
unanimously threw out regulations that would have banned AIDS
testing for health insurance and other forms of coverage.
   Its decision, the court said, was based solely on the question of
the insurance commissioner's authority and ``has nothing to do with
the substantive merits of the (AIDS-testing) regulations or with the
need for their adoption.''
   ``We conclude that the (insurance) commissioner had no authority,
express or implied, to adopt the regulations challenged in this
case,'' Justice Herbert P. Wilkins wrote for a unanimous court.
   The court said it was up to the Legislature to decide whether to
give the insurance commissioner such authority.
   ``I am very pleased with the decision,'' said William Carroll,
executive director of the Life Insurance Association of
Massachusetts, which along with several insurance companies appealed
the regulations. ``We felt that the authority issue was the most
critical issue of the case.''
   Denise McWilliams of the Gay and Lesbian Advocates and Defenders
group, which intervened in support of Insurance Commissioner Roger
Singer, said the result will be that ``it is going to make it
impossible ... for people to get insurance, particularly those
individuals who are just (tested) positive.''
   Beyond that, she said, ``I think the long-term effects can be
truly staggering, because, obviously, if folks can't get private
insurance, they are going to be thrown onto the public rolls. I
frankly don't think that's fair to anybody's interest.''
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis called the decision ``a setback for our
efforts to deal responsibly with the issues of AIDS testing and the
use of AIDS-related information for life and health insurance.''
   ``I continue to believe in the need for regulations that are
reasonable to the industry and fair to those they insure,'' he added.
   Singer issued the regulations on Sept. 11, 1987, making
Massachusetts only the second state, after New York, to ban by
regulation health insurance testing for antibodies to the human
immunodeficiency virus associated with acquired immune deficiency
syndrome.
   Only California and the District of Columbia have passed laws
banning AIDS testing for health insurance.
   Under the Massachusetts regulations, AIDS testing would be banned
for all health insurance, any group life and most disability
insurance. Testing would be allowed under controlled conditions for
individual life and non-cancellable disability insurance.
   The regulations said that insurance companies who wished to test
must offer no-test policies of up to $100,000 with an AIDS
exclusion. Companies could also offer any policy with a no-test AIDS
exclusion which could later be removed if the individual
policyholder furnished proof of a negative test for the AIDS
antibody.
   The regulations never went into effect because of the insurance
industry's appeal.
</TEXT>
