<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 2313EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FarewellGlitz 2ndLd-Writethru a0774 11-16 0904</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farewell Glitz, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0774,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagans Hold Final State Dinner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Thatcher Bjt, a0804</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 3rd graf pvs bgng, `Mrs. Reagan,' to
UPDATE with toasts at dinner</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With their 55th _ and final _ state dinner on
Wednesday, President and Mrs. Reagan closed the book on one of their
favorite White House events, one for which they rekindled a
tradition of glitz and glamour dating to John Adams' New Years Day
bash in 1801.
   Though most presidents have made the White House a stage for some
of the nation's most elaborate and exclusive entertainment, the
Reagans brought back a Hollywood party style to an executive mansion
shorn of hard liquor and dancing during the Carter years.
   Mrs. Reagan, asked as her guests arrived why British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher was the honoree for their final state
dinner, responded, ``Because she was our first (guest) and we love
her.''
   During their dinner toasts, Mrs. Thatcher saluted the first lady,
saying her ``charm, dignity and quiet but sure courage have won the
hearts of millions.''
   She also praised the president as ``more than a staunch ally and
counselor. You have also been a wonderful friend to me and our
country.''
   Reagan said the prime minister ``is a leader with the vision and
the courage to stay the course until the battles are won. ... As I
prepare to depart this office in January, I take considerable
satisfaction in the knowledge that Margaret Thatcher will still
reside at No. 10 Downing Street.''
   The first lady was attired in a red satin ball gown while Mrs.
Thatcher wore a pink two-piece dress with gold edging and buttons.
Mrs. Reagan also wore a brilliant, multistone necklace that appeared
to be made of diamonds and sapphires, but her spokeswoman, Elaine
Crispen, described it as ``definitely costume.''
   Wednesday night's black-tie tribute to Mrs. Thatcher was an apt
finale to a glittering series in which Reagan, now 77, never seemed
to tire, regaling his guests with anecdotes, both at the dinner
table or while working the after-dinner demitasse crowd in the Blue
Room.
   And after an evening's entertainment _ ranging from the Dance
Theater of Harlem to Wednesday's pianist, Michael Feinstein _ the
first couple virtually never failed to take a near-midnight turn
about the marbled dance floor while their guests lingered over
champagne.
   Mrs. Thatcher was the first foreign leader to be honored by the
couple at such an event, which took place on Feb. 26, 1981, a month
after Reagan took office.
   ``We've come quite a long way and done quite a lot together,''
Mrs. Thatcher reminisced during an Oval Office tete-a-tete with the
president. The president and Mrs. Thatcher also held formal talks
several hours before the evening's festivities. Mrs. Thatcher's
husband, Dennis, was also an honored guest.
   The two leaders _ soulmates of staunch conservatism _ spent a
good part of the day trading laudatory statements about the success
of their eight-year alliance.
   But despite the prime minister's usually patrician demeanor, the
farewell day was a time to have a bit of fun, as well.
   At a State Department luncheon of monkfish and venison, Secretary
of State George Shultz presented Mrs. Thatcher with a black patent
leather handbag, saying he'd grown used to seeing her pull perfect
compromises from her bag ``like a rabbit out of a hat.''
   While President-elect George Bush was invited in his No. 2
capacity, Vice President-elect Dan Quayle was not on the evening
guest list.
   White House aides scrambled to explain that Quayle had been
invited to a dinner in 1982 as part of the normal congressional
contingent and that he'd be going to many, many more such events
after the change in administrations.
   Members of Congress invited to Wednesday's dinner included Reps.
Trent Lott, R-Miss., Dick Cheney, R-Wyo., and Tom Foley, D-Wash., as
well as Sens. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., Ted Stevens, R-Ala., and Robert
Byrd, D-W.Va.
   While the Reagans have shown a preference during their years in
office for guests from Hollywood, the arts and the world of fashion,
they have also included sports stars and representatives from
academia and captains of industry.
   Wednesday's guest list also included American Ballet Theatre
artistic director Mikhail Baryshnikov, Discovery space shuttle
commander Frederick Hauck, Los Angeles Dodgers pitcher Orel
Hershiser, actor Tom Selleck, New York City Opera general director
Beverley Sills, the Rev. Billy Graham and author Tom Wolfe.
   Traditionally, some 120 guests are invited to the executive
mansion, where they are treated like royalty from the moment they
are greeted by military aides and the elegant strains of a harpist
at the East Wing entrance.
   They are treated to before-dinner drinks, a formal reception line
with the guests of honor, and a five- or six-course meal. Given the
Reagan's pride in their home state, California wines normally are on
the menu.
   For the fete honoring Mrs. Thatcher, the State Dining Room was
turned into a garden of peach roses, with hundreds of the flowers
gathered in topiary trees on each table and arrayed in bouquets
around the room.
   The guests, dining on the famed $200,000 red Reagan china, were
served baby lobster in a caviar yogurt sauce; roasted saddle of veal
perigourdine; asparagus with hazel nut butter; autumn mixed salad
and a selection of cheeses, as well as chestnut marquise with
pistachio sauce, orange tuiles and ginger twigs.
</TEXT>
