<HEAD>Jewish Civil Rights Group Expresses Concern About Sununu</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after pvs 10th graf bgng ``As chief ...'' to
add Bush comments; ADDS 3 grafs at end to include Reagan comments</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jewish civil rights group expressed concern
Wednesday about John Sununu, whom sources say has been tapped to be
White House chief of staff, because of his failure to support a
measure that condemned an anti-Zionist U.N. resolution.
   The Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith issued a statement
saying Sununu, the retiring governor of New Hampshire, was the only
governor who refused to endorse a proclamation attacking a 1975 U.N.
resolution that equated zionism with racism.
   At a news conference in Concord, N.H., Sununu, who is
Arab-American, said he did not endorse the proclamation sponsored by
Zionist groups because it would have been inappropriate.
   ``I have said very clearly that it was inappropriate for a
governor to try to issue something that would have as its focus an
attempt to influence foreign policy,'' he said.
   But he said that he made sure that the condemnation of the U.N.
resolution found its way into the Republican Party platform at the
national convention last summer. Sununu was President-elect George
Bush's liaison to the GOP platform committee.
   ``So I don't have a problem supporting that in the proper
context,'' he said.
   Sources have said Bush has picked Sununu to be the chief of
staff. Bush has not made a formal announcement, and Sununu has not
confirmed or denied the reports.
   The ADL, in a statement from its New York office, said that
Sununu was the only governor out of 50 not to endorse the
proclamation, ``a position which put him at odds with President
Reagan, Vice President Bush and both Houses of Congress.''
   Despite its criticism of Sununu, the ADL said the governor has
issued proclamations commemorating Israel's 40th anniversary and
efforts on behalf of Soviet Jewry.
   ``As chief of staff, Gov. Sununu will bear a major responsibility
for facilitating the implementation of the new president's program
and policies as reflected in the Republican Party platform. We hope
and trust he will meet the responsibility,'' the ADL statement said.
   Bush, asked about some criticism of Sununu from Jewish leaders,
defended the New Hampshire governor as being sensitive to Isreali
concerns.
   ``Sununu is practically the author of the best party platform on
the Middle East that any party has ever had,'' the president-elect
said.
   Bush, however, would only shake his head and laugh when asked
when he would announce his choice for chief of staff.
   Sununu said he had ``no problem in stating rather clearly'' that
he believes a key to peace in the Middle East is the ``assurance of
the integrity and protection of the state of Israel.''
   President Reagan, asked for his view on the reported asignment of
Sununu to the chief of staff post, praised his record as governor.
   ``I have great admiration for him _ I've seen him as governor and
what he's done ... he's a great governor and if that's what turns
out (that he becomes chief of staff) he'll do a remarkable job,''
Reagan said.
   The president added that Bush has not asked any advice about
possible appointments, but that he would gladly offer it if asked.
</TEXT>
