<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru     11-16 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Kill 11</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas blew up a farm truck
carrying highland peasants and sent it tumbling down a mountain
ravine. Eleven people were killed, four of them children, police
said Wednesday.
   Seven other passengers on the paneled, flat-bed truck were
wounded, police said. They blamed the attack on the Shining Path
guerrilla movement.
   Rebels detonated dynamite buried beneath a gravel road as the
truck passed, seeking to kill four policemen who they thought were
aboard, police said.
   ``We made a mistake. They're not police. Let's get out of here,''
a survivor said, quoting one of several armed guerrillas who swarmed
over the wreckage moments after the attack late Monday.
   Police said the four officers had gotten off the truck a few
minutes before the blast on a major road near Quinua, a town 20
miles northeast of Ayacucho.
   The truck was carrying several Indian peasant families from
Ayacucho to nearby villages and farms. Farm trucks are frequently
used in place of buses to carry passengers throughout Peru's lofty
Andes Mountains, where paved roads are rare.
   The region surrounding Ayacucho, 230 miles southeast of Lima, is
the heart of the Shining Path's eight-year insurgency to impose
Marxist rule.
   The area is also the bloodiest. The government says the majority
of the 12,000 people slain during the insurgency have been Ayacucho
peasants caught in the crossfire between rebels and government
forces.
   In related violence, police said two policemen and one guerrilla
were killed Wednesday in two separate Shining Path attacks along
Peru's northern coast.
   Guerrillas in a passing car shot and killed a policeman as he
climbed aboard a city bus in Trujillo, a coastal capital 350 miles
north of Lima, police there said.
   In Carabamba, a village 30 miles east of Trujillo, a column of
100 rebels launched a dawn attack against a police post manned by 20
officers. Police said one policeman and one attacker were slain in
an hour-long firefight before the rebels were driven off.
</TEXT>
