<1ST_LINE>a a PM-ReligionintheNews Adv18   11-16 0844</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Religion in the News, Adv 18,0870</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Fri PMs Nov. 18, or thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AIDS Victims Illume A Truth About Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the complexity of life, AIDS victims tell a
truth about it. Challenging modern illusions of immortality, they
illuminate a universal reality _ that death comes to all.
   Their suffering also can be ``a means of grace for them and
others,'' says the Rev. David Felter of Kansas City, Mo., who helped
initiate a special selection of Scripture for AIDS patients.
   ``If the sufferer can accept God's acceptance of himself, he is
free, liberated, to offer his own suffering under God as a
sacrament,'' Felter said in a telephone interview.
   ``If he accepts that reality, not with the acquiescence of
defeat, but with a triumphalness of spirit, we see something ugly
but nevertheless inevitable changed from a final enemy to a doorway
to a new and better existence.''
   Indications of that enlightening assurance that can come through
difficulty run through a small booklet of Scripture passages issued
by the American Bible Society to help in coping with AIDS.
   Called ``Nothing can separate us from the Love of God,'' the
booklet includes 22 passages from the Old and New Testament, such as
the 23rd Psalm, which reads in part:
   ``Even if I go through the deepest darkness, I will not be
afraid, Lord, for you are with me.''
   It is regarded the first time, nationally, that a special
collection of Bible passages has been issued to bolster the spirits
of those stricken with AIDS, presently incurable and always fatal.
   ``Who then can separate us from the love of Christ?'' says Romans
8. ``Can trouble do it, or hardship or persecution or hunger or
poverty or danger or death?... No, in all these things we have
complete victory through him who loved us.''
   The passages are in the simplified translation of the ``Good News
Bible'' in today's English, emphasizing God's backing in the worst
times of helplessness, abandonment and fear.
   ``You threw me down into the depths, to the very bottom of the
sea, where the waters were all around me,'' reads Jonah 2. ``But
you, O Lord my God, brought me back from the depths alive.''
   The idea for the booklet grew out of a consultation of
denominational representatives at which Felter, long-time pastor and
now training coordinator for the Church of the Nazarene, cited the
need for such material.
   Telling of a couple whose son was stricken with AIDS, he said,
``This kind of thing hurts so much, and we've been ill equipped to
provide any kind of real strengthening in these cases.''
   The project for the booklet resulted. Chaplains and others who
work with AIDS patients reviewed the manuscript and expressed
approval of passages chosen.
   ``Jesus... answered, ... `I have not come to call respectable
people, but outcasts','' reads Matthew 9.
   The booklet is being made available to hospitals, hospices,
church groups and individuals who minister to people with AIDS.
   ``We despised him and rejected him; he endured suffering and pain
... we ignored him as if he were nothing,'' go verses in Isaiah 53
and 52. Yet many ``will see and understand something they had never
known.''
   Felter said that in ``our death-denying society,'' AIDS ``remind
us of our finitude, of our temporariness, that we are indeed like
vapor that appears and then is gone.
   ``These events teach us that there is no circumstances, no
situation regardless of how hopeless, that cannot in the grace of
God be transformed into a window for the spirit whereby we see
reality more clearly.
   ``Suffering and awareness of others' suffering sharpens our
perceptions of life.''
   He said AIDS victims can find grace for themselves and others in
their plight through realizing their acceptance by God.
   ``In a sense, they can take what is loathsome, ordinary and
deadly and transform it into a window that allows us to see beyond
the ordinariness threatening us all,'' he said.
   He said it models ``in a small way'' what Jesus did in the
resurrection after his crucifixion, ``transcending hopelessness, the
sentence that is against them,'' and opening a ``changed perspective
of life forever.''
   Interspersed among the Bible passages offered for AIDS sufferers
are brief commentaries stressing God's constant devotion to the
rejected and weak and forgiving compassion for human failure, such
as:
   From Psalm 103 _ ``As for us, our life is like grass. We grow and
flourish like a wild flower; then the wind blows on it, and it is
gone... But for those who honor the Lord, his love lasts forever.''
   From 2 Corinthians 4 _ ``Even though our physicial being is
gradually decaying, yet our spiritual being is renewed day by day.''
   From 1 Corinthians 15 _ ``Listen to this secret truth: ... when
the last trumpet sounds, we shall all be changed in an instant, as
quickly as the blinking of an eye... For what is mortal must be
changed into what is immortal.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Nov. 18</NOTE>
