<NOTE>For release Fri PMs, Nov. 18, and thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANSFIELD, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the hymns sung in present-day
churches derive from a religious revival in 17th century America,
the ``Great Awakening,'' says a Protestant campus chaplain at
Mansfield University.
   Based on research, the Rev. Joanne Weiss says that before that
period, church music primarily was chanted psalms. ``The change from
psalms to hymns took place because weorshipers needed a new language
of praise,'' she says.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OSAGE BEACH, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Missouri Baptist Convention says it
``respects, honors and intends to preserve'' emphasis on the
priesthood of the believer _ a concept discounted to some extent by
the national Southern Baptist Convention.
   The doctrine holds that each member has equal standing in
interpreting Scripture and in other religious rights, but the
national convention had insisted the pastor had ruling authority.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KIAMESHA LAKE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Declaring that both parties in the
recent national campaign ``assassinated ethics, morality and honesty
in the quest for the presidency,'' a Jewish women's leader calls for
an uprising of women to change such politics.
   ``If the men can't do it, women must,'' Evelyn Auerbach of Glen
Rock, N.J., president of the Women's League for Conservative
Judaism, told its annual convention.
   She said it's time for women's organizations from all walks of
life to ``assume the leadership in both the Republican and
Democratic parties to assure us that future elections discuss issues
and facts in a clean forthright manner''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's film review board has banned
showing of the movie ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' on grounds
that it is offensive to Christianity. Israeli law forbids offending
any religion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, in a message for observance
of National Bible Week, Nov. 20-27, says the Bible ``is the most
precious treasure yet entrusted to man.''
   ``Over the centuries, though empires have risen and fallen,
though civilizations have ebbed and flowed, the Bible has remained a
constant source of hope and inspiration,'' he says.
   Reagan and his wife, Nancy, are honorary national chairpersons of
the week, an interfaith project emphasizing importance of the Bible
and promoting greater reading of it, including daily passages
recommended for the week.
   Reagan says the Bible ``shaped the ideas and formed the
consciences of many early Americans'' and nurtured ``a profound
belief in human dignity, in individual freedom and in the
inalienable rights of man...
   ``Unless we ... insure that the wonderful treasures of the Bible
are handed down to each new generation, we cannot, I believe, long
remain a `nation under God.'''

</TEXT>
