<2ND_LINE>PM-On the Money, Adv 17,0646</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday Oct. 17</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Eleventh-Hour Tax Checkup</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before the end of 1988 gets much closer,
financial advisers say, it's a good idea to check on whether you
have been paying the right amount of federal income tax.
   That advice holds not only for people with large incomes and
complicated investments, but for everyday wage-earners who haven't
checked lately on the progress of their income and withholding taxes.
   The idea is simply to determine whether you have paid too much or
too little so far toward the eventual bottom line on the tax return
that will be due April 15.
   If the answer is too little, you may be in danger of incurring
interest charges and penalties from the Internal Revenue Service.
   If the answer is too much, you may want to consider asking your
employer to reduce your withholding tax for the last few paychecks
of the year.
   Less withholding now will reduce the size of the refund you stand
to collect next spring. That may not appeal much to people who use
overwithholding as a type of ``forced savings'' plan.
   But if you are going to be due the money a few months from now,
why not collect it sooner and put it to work for you, rather than
leaving it ``on deposit'' with Uncle Sam at no interest?
   Perhaps the extra take-home money in December might help you to
pay for holiday gifts and activities without having to borrow at
high credit-card interest rates.
   The exercise of calculating the status of your tax payments does
not have to be especially complicated. But experts on the subject
say it needs to be done with care to avoid a misstep.
   Many people can start with their most recent pay stub, which
should give them a pretty good idea of what their total wages and
salaries will be for the year.
   If your other income and deductions, such as investment interest
received and mortgage interest paid, has not changed drastically
since last year, you can use the numbers on your 1987 return as a
basis for estimating what your 1988 taxable income will be
(remembering that some deductions, such as for consumer interest
expense, will be less generous for 1988).
   Then you can compute your projected 1988 tax liability using the
tax tables for the year, which may be available from your employer,
a financial institution where you do business or your local library.
   If it looks as though your withholding is going to fall short by
a significant amount, further action may be warranted.
   To avoid penalties and interest, the rules require that your
withholding (and any quarterly estimated or other advance payments)
satisfy one of two standards.
   It must equal either 100 percent of what you owed for 1987, or 90
percent of the total that will be due for 1988.
   Suppose you had a windfall this year, substantially increasing
your taxable income, and you find that you are not likely to satisfy
either of those tests.
   ``If you're able to adjust withholding, you can solve the
problem,'' says William Brennan, an adviser on investment and tax
planning with the accounting firm of Ernst & Whinney.
   ``Just arrange with your employer to withhold the amount needed
to `catch up.' Withholding is deemed to have been paid in evenly
throughout the year, no matter when it's actually withheld.
   ``In this way, you may be able to avoid interest and penalties
entirely.''
   Another way to close the gap: Step up you deductible activities,
such as charitable contributions, to reduce the amount of income
that will be subject to tax.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs Nov 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881116-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1357EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv17   11-16 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 17,0571</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday Nov. 17</NOTE>
<HEAD>Taxing `Income' That Isn't Income</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobody in recent years has been able to
demonstrate that taxes are fair. The claim is made _ every time the
tax laws are changed, in fact _ but the proof isn't provided.
   Is it right, for example, to impose big tax burdens on young
singles who have few items to deduct? Should corporate dividends be
taxed twice, as they are? Do homeowners really deserve the tax
shelter they have?
   Almost anyone can compile a list of ``inequities'' in the tax
laws. They write to Congress, and Congress then rearranges the tax
laws. It has done so every year of this decade, closing loopholes,
opening others.
   And next year, if President-elect George Bush follows through on
campaign indications, Congress may be asked to deal with an aspect
of the tax law that many people consider to be not just inequitable
but just plain foolish.
   It is the tax on income that never was made, on buying power that
never existed, on funds that the person taxed never had the use of.
It is the capital gains tax which, as it exists, taxes a person for
inflation.
   For example, assume an investment of $5,000 in stocks has been
held seven years. If the appreciation averaged 10 percent over that
time you will have approximately doubled your money. Your capital
gains would be $5,000, your tax about $1,400.
   While you might appear to have earned 10 percent in current
dollars, you really would have earned only 6 percent a year. Why?
Because the value of the dollar changed. Inflation probably eroded 4
percent a year.
   At 6 percent a year your money will not double in seven years. It
will grow only to around $7,000. Nevertheless, you will pay capital
gains taxes as if it had grown to $10,000. You will pay $1,400 in
taxes.
   Deducting the taxes from the inflation-adjusted total amount
earned will leave you with just $5,600 _ an average gain of $100 a
year or less for having invested your savings in the American
economy.
   As the law exists, capital gains _ which are long-term gains and
thus vulnerable to inflation _ are taxed at the same 28 percent rate
as ordinary income, which suffers relatively little from inflation.
   It is for reasons such as this that Bush mentioned the
possibility of pushing back the capital gains tax rate, which was
raised in the 1986 tax reform measure. But there is more to it than
the inequity.
   The repercussions of the current level of capital gains shows up
every day in the securities markets, where individual investors
refrain from buying stocks and opt instead for the lower risk of
interest-bearing bonds.
   Paying taxes on money never earned isn't restricted to the
securities markets. In fact, the most common abuse of common sense
occurs in the taxing of capital gains ``earned'' on the inflated
value of personal residences.
   In this latter instance, however, homeowners are accorded various
tax benefits that offset some of the damage. In most other
investments, however, there is no relief.
   In such investments, the investor simply pays taxes on ``income''
that was never made.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs, Nov 17</NOTE>
