<1ST_LINE>a i AM-StarvinginSudan ADV24   11-16 0830</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Starving in Sudan, ADV 24,0850</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs AMs, Nov. 24, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Hunger Widespread Among Sudanese in Southern War Zone</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Spelling Thamos is correct in 1st graf.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUBA, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anna Ido Thamos waves a limp clover-like weed
in one hand and with the other displays sorghum mash, residue from a
local beer factory.
   Often boiled weeds and sorghum mash are all she has to feed
herself and her seven children. Some days, they do not eat at all.
   ``It is miserable,'' the 36-year-old nurse said as the tropical
dusk fell over several hundred people waiting to receive grain at a
food distribution center in this provincial capital beseiged by
rebels fighting Sudan's government.
   The grain is part of 1,500 metric tons of food being airlifted
into Juba in an emergency United Nations Operation from Entebbe,
Uganda, and a Norwegian Church Aid airlift of 150 metric tons from
Nairobi, Kenya. It is the first food to Juba since September when
the remnants of a truck convoy carrying relief food from Uganda
limped into town following a rebel attack that killed 15 people,
mostly Kenyan drivers and assistants.
   The airlifts may be the last chance of survival for the people
here in southern Sudan, caught up in the conflict between the rebel
Sudan People's Liberation Army led by John Garang and the
government, 750 miles north in Khartoum, say local government,
church and relief officials.
   ``Garang is a southerner and the people here are southerners so
the central government is not interested. They want everyone to die
of hunger,'' charged Francis Luate, deputy director of information
for Equatoria province.
   However, rebel activity has made the lush food-producing
countryside uninhabitable, forcing people into Juba where the
displaced and the townspeople alike now must rely on international
aid.
   ``The rebels claim to be fighting to liberate the people, yet
they are committing atrocities, raping and killing,'' Luate claimed.
   The rebels took up arms against the Moslem-dominated government
in 1983 seeking greater autonomy and economic reforms for the
predominantly Christian and animist south and the lifting of the
country's Islamic laws in the area.
   Roman Catholic Archbishop Paulino Lukudo Loro accuses the
government of deliberately withholding food aid in an effort to
depopulate the south and rob the rebels of their base of support.
   ``This is a clear plan of extermination of the south,'' said
Loro. ``It is really genocide going on.''
   Loro points to the government's ability to continue airlifting
arms and ammunition to its soldiers in Juba.
   ``Why is it not using military planes to bring food here?''
   The situation is worse in Torit, 50 miles east of Juba, where the
army recently made five airdrops of food and supplies to troops but
nothing to the people, according to a radio message from the town's
relief committee.
   The committee urgently requested an airdrop for the 4,000 people
living in the besieged town.
   ``The civilians are left to eating only leaves and waiting to be
buried,'' it said in message to the Norwegian Church Aid office in
Juba.
   Both rebels and government soldiers have placed landmines on the
footpaths and roads around the besieged towns, cutting off the
region's lush, green fields where crops remain unharvested.
   Small stocks of vegetables are available in Juba's markets, but
they are insufficient for the town's population which has swelled
from 150,000 to more than 200,000 with people from the embattled
southern countryside who fled to camps on Juba's outskirts.
   Predominantly Arab merchants continue to get supplies on
government-chartered flights from Khartoum but sell food at prices
well beyond the means of most. Before the airlift began, for
example, a 12-pound bag of maize (corn) was selling for the Sudanese
pound equivalent of $340.
   However, the grain being airlifted is not enough, said Sam Kenyi,
head of the Combined Agencies Relief Team, a consortium of relief
agencies and churches in Juba. The emergency operation allows the
estimated 50,000 refugees in the camps around Juba each 200 grams
(seven ounces) of maize a day. A third of the relief grain has been
allotted to cooperatives in town where wage-earners like Ms. Thamos
can buy up to eight pounds at most once a week.
   Death rates have been rising since September with as many as 400
hunger-weakened people, mostly children, dying each month in the
town's two hospitals, said Dr. Oliver Duku, project leader of
African Medical and Research Foundation and U.S. Agency for
International Development.
   Nobody is sure of the countrywide death toll since the fighting
began. But foreign relief officials in Khartoum and Equatoria's
Episcopal Archbishop Benjamin Yugusuk estimate at least 250,000
people have died of starvation or inadequate medical care since late
last year.
   About 2 million people, a third of the south's population, have
been turned into refugees by the fighting, about 1.3 million of whom
were forced from their homes this year, they say.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs AMs, Nov. 24</NOTE>
