<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Stocks Soar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices soared to a record high on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange today for the fourth session in a row, while the U.S.
dollar held its ground against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the market's
main price index, rose 166.71 points, or 0.57 percent, to close at a
record 28,996.12. The average reached a new high on Friday, and has
climbed in every session since then.
   Foreign exchange traders said the currency market was in a
wait-and-see mood in advance of today's release of U.S. monthly
trade figures for September in Washington.
   ``The dollar will surely take a direction if the trade (deficit)
figures are not around the predicted $10 billion,'' said an exchange
dealer at a major commercial bank, who spoke anonymously.
   The United States posted a trade deficit of $12.2 billion in
August.
   The dollar opened at 123.58 yen and was traded in a narrow range
of 123.45-123.65 yen before closing at 123.54 yen, up 0.29 yen from
Tuesday's close of 123.25 yen.
</TEXT>
