<HEAD>Dollar Slips in Europe After Trade Deficit Announcement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: adds reaction to trade figures in first 9 grafs, picks up 6th
graf, Gold fell...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar drifted lower in Europe today after
U.S. trade figures for September showed a drop in the merchandise
trade deficit that was not big enough to reverse the currency's
steady decline.
   ``These figures are a little bit better than was expected,'' said
Richard Jeffrey, a senior economist for brokers Hoare Govett.
   ``However, I think the longer-term picture is still the same:
that demand is still too strong in the U.S. and that that is sucking
in exports to too great an extent.''
   Jeffrey told British Broadcasting Corp., ``Temporarily I think
these figures will lift some of the downward pressure from the
dollar and might stop interest rates going up in the very short
term.''
   In the longer term, however, he said the U.S. administration
would ``have to sanction higher interest rates to constrain consumer
demand.''
   Volume was thin because West German markets were closed for a
national holiday, traders said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.29 yen to a closing 123.54. After the trade
report, the dollar was quoted in London at 122.90 yen.
   Other dollar in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's prices,
included: 1.7400 West German marks, down from 1.7465; 1.4595 Swiss
francs, down from 1.4630; 5.9465 French francs, down from 5.9660;
1.9580 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9685; 1,292.00 Italian lire, down
from 1,300.50; and 1.2298 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2344.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.8115, compared with
$1.8060 late Tuesday.
   Gold fell in calm trading in Europe. Bullion dealers said selling
from Eastern Europe and some orders from the United States brought
prices down from their Tuesday levels.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $422.15 a troy ounce
compared with $423.75 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$422.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $422.65, down from $423 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 38 cents to close at a bid
$423.69.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.39 a troy ounce,
down from Tuesday's $6.41.
</TEXT>
