<HEAD>Forstmann Little Abandons Idea of Bidding for Food-Tobacco Giant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acquisition specialist Forstmann Little & Co.
said today it has scrapped a plan to enter the bidding for RJR
Nabisco Inc., the food-tobacco giant targeted in the largest-ever
corporate takeover attempt.
   Forstmann Little said in a brief statement that an investment
group headed by the firm had decided ``consistent with its
investment criteria, it will not submit a proposal.''
   Its withdrawal from possible involvement in the battle for
Atlanta-based RJR Nabisco leaves two enormous contenders, a group
consisting of RJR Nabisco management, backed by the Wall Street
firms Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. and Salomon Brothers Inc., vs. the
investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.
   Both have offered more than $20 billion for RJR Nabisco, a maker
of products ranging from Oreo cookies to Winston cigarettes. Most of
that money would be borrowed and repaid via RJR Nabisco's earnings
and the sale of some of its assets, an increasingly controversial
transaction known as a leveraged buyout.
   Forstmann Little's withdrawal came three weeks after it held
talks with the RJR Nabisco management group and considered joining
their bid for the company. It then assembled a rival group
consisting of Procter & Gamble Co., Ralston Purina Co., Castle &
Cooke Inc. and Goldman Sachs & Co.
   The RJR Nabisco management group stunned the financial world late
last month by disclosing its intention to acquire the company in a
leveraged buyout. The size, complexity and enormous debt load of
such a transaction have raised concerns about the use of borrowed
money to finance corporate takeovers.
</TEXT>
