<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Pillsbury     11-16 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Pillsbury,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Grand Met Threatened to Lower Pillsbury Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC has threatened to lower
its $5.23 billion takeover bid if Pillsbury Co.'s planned spinoff of
its Burger King Corp. unit occurs, according to a published report
Wednesday.
   Attorneys for the British conglomerate told a Delaware court that
Grand Met would be ``required to make fundamental changes to its
($60-a-share) offer'' should the spinoff occur first, the Wall
Street Journal reported.
   Among the changes would be a lower price to reflect a potential
tax liability of several hundred million dollars, the Journal
reported.
   In addition, since Burger King would become a Florida
corporation, Grand Met would have to mount additional legal attacks
on Florida's anti-takeover laws should it still want to acquire the
fast-food chain, the Journal quoted Grand Met attorneys as saying.
   Pillsbury's stock closed at $58 Tuesday, down 62.5 cents, in
composite New York Stock Exchange trading.
   ``The spinoff will make it substantially less likely that Grand
Met will ever successfully acquire the entire Pillsbury company,''
Grand Met's attorneys said in a letter to the Delaware Chancery
Court.
   The court is reconsidering the validity of Pillsbury's ``poison
pill'' defense, an attempt by the Minneapolis-based food and
restaurant company to thwart a takeover. The pill is designed to
discourage Grand Met from buying tendered shares, since to do so
would increase the price.
   Pillsbury spokesmen did not immediately return a phone call
Wednesday.
   On Tuesday, Grand Met extended to Nov. 18 its $60-per-share offer
for Pillsbury, saying that 79.1 percent of Pillsbury stock now has
been tendered to the British firm. It was the third extension of the
offer, which was launched Oct. 4.
   Grand Met said nearly 67.6 million shares of Pillsbury common
stock had been tendered and not withdrawn by the Monday night
deadline. When it extended its second deadline of Nov. 8, Grand Met
reported that about 74.3 percent of Pillsbury's outstanding shares
had been tendered.
   Pillsbury, which has rejected the bid as ``inadequate,'' had no
comment Tuesday on the extension of the offer.
   Pillsbury Chairman Philip Smith has told Pillsbury shareholders
they would be better off holding on to their stock because Pillsbury
has proposed spinning off Burger King into a separate public company
in a restructuring that would include a special dividend. Pillsbury
shareholders would receive the dividend and Burger King stock under
the plan. Additional moves also are being considered to enhance
shareholder value, Smith has said.
   Grand Met's attorneys, in the letter to the Delaware court,
characterized the Burger King spinoff proposal as a ``poison tax''
designed to kill any deal. While the spinoff, which is scheduled to
occur Dec. 2, is structured to be tax-free for current Pillsbury
holders, it would create a huge tax liability for any third party
who bought Pillsbury after Dec. 2.
   Attorneys for Pillsbury shareholders urged the court to set a
hearing on motions to extend that date, the Journal reported. The
holders say they needed more time, partly because they don't have
detailed information yet on the spinoff's tax consequences.
   Grand Met's letter describes the spinoff plan as ``another time
bomb, planted by Pillsbury's management, to deter the acquisition of
the company by Grand Met or any other party.''
</TEXT>
