<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 3rdLd-Writethru   11-16 0848</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0874</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Report Hurts Bonds, Dollar; Stocks Dip</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with Fed reportedly buying
dollars; currency falling despite intervention; bonds, stocks
heading lower; new report on rising business inventories; picks up
10th graf, On Wall ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. merchandise trade deficit narrowed to $10.5 billion in
September, the government said today in a report that led to
declines in the value of stocks, bonds and the dollar.
   The deficit figure, although smaller, was toward the high end of
market expectations and raised the possibility that the dollar would
need to fall further to make American goods cheaper in world markets.
   ``The numbers showed improvement; there's no question about it.
But the absolute number's still pretty high,'' said John McCarthy,
chief dealer of Amsterdam Rotterdam Bank in New York.
   Exports set a record, while imports dropped slightly from their
record levels of August, the Commerce Department said.
   Currency traders said they believed the Federal Reserve had
bought dollars with Japanese yen to support the U.S. currency, but
it had little effect and the dollar soon resumed its decline.
   The dollar fell about half a percent against the Japanese yen and
1 percent against the West German mark by late morning in New York,
dipping to 122.6 Japanese yen and 1.728 West German marks from 123.2
yen and 1.743 marks late Tuesday. The dollar is now slightly above
its lowest point against the yen since modern exchange rates were
established in the late 1940s.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 19.03 points
to 2,058.14 as of 11 a.m. on Wall Street. Declining stocks
outnumbered advancing ones by a 7-to-2 margin on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   In the credit market, the price of the Treasury's benchmark
30-year bond fell. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction,
rose to 9.06 percent from 9.01 percent late Tuesday. As recently as
Nov. 1, the long bond yielded just 8.76 percent.
   The 2.2 percent, or $700 million, September export increase to a
record $28.2 billion was led almost entirely by higher sales of
American autos, data processing and office equipment and chemicals,
the department said.
   For the first nine months of the year, the trade deficit is
running at an annual rate of $137.2 billion, compared with a record
$170.3 billion last year and $155.1 billion in 1986.
   In another report today, the Commerce Department said business
inventories jumped 0.7 percent in September, the 21st consecutive
monthly increase, while sales remained virtually unchanged.
   The combination of rising inventories and flat sales is a sign of
economic weakness. However, business sales have been generally
strong this year and economists said the gain in inventories during
most months was in line with sales.
   On Wall Street Tuesday, stocks rose marginally in the lightest
trading in seven weeks. Investors had been reluctant to participate
ahead of the trade report.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 12.09 points to
2,077.17.
   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange fell to 115.17 million
shares, down from 142.90 million in the previous session and the
lowest since a 113.72 million-share day Sept. 28.
   Worries about accelerating inflation sparked by the retail sales
report released Tuesday initially drove bond prices sharply lower,
although they later recovered on the strength of falling prices for
crude oil and other key commodities.
   Anticipation of the September trade figures also kept foreign
exchange trading edgy. The dollar fell to 123.23 Japanese yen in
late New York trading from 123.75 yen Monday.
   In other economic developments Tuesday:
   _The Federal Reserve Board reported that U.S. industrial
production rose 0.4 percent in October, the biggest increase in
three months, despite a decline in activity in the nation's oil
fields.
   _U.S. automakers reported that their car and light truck sales
rose 14.9 percent in early November compared with results a year
earlier that were depressed by the absence of buyer incentives.
   _A majority of the nation's small-business owners believe the
federal budget deficit is the No. 1 issue facing President-elect
George Bush, and they favor spending cuts to reduce the shortfall,
according to a poll by the accounting firm Arthur Andersen & Co.
   The Commerce Department said retail sales rose to a seasonally
adjusted $135.6 billion in October, boosted by gains at department
stores and auto dealerships. It also revised its figures for the two
previous months, showing a brisker sales pace than previously
thought.
   ``These numbers give a much different picture than just a month
ago. Some people were betting the expansion would die of old age.
These numbers refute that strongly,'' said David Jones, an economist
with Aubrey G. Lanston & Co., a government securities dealer in New
York.
   But, he said the unexpected strength has rekindled concern about
inflation, which had waned as growth cooled in August and September.
   In the latest report, the government said retail sales fell 0.3
percent in September, up from an earlier estimate of a 0.4 percent
decline, and rose 0.3 percent in August, rather than falling 0.1
percent as previously thought.
</TEXT>
