<2ND_LINE>PM-Social Security-Appeals, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0031,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proposal Made to Restrict Social Security Appeals Process</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs comment after 2nd graf pvs, The Social ... ;
adds 5 grafs comment at end. Also moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elderly and disabled people who have been
denied Social Security benefits would face tougher requirements for
appealing the decisions under new rules proposed by the government.
   The Social Security Administration calls the proposal preliminary
and says final action is unlikely before next spring.
   Such a rule would meet strong opposition from Congress, said Rep.
Edward R. Roybal, D-Calif., chairman of the House Aging Committee.
The private National Committee to Preserve Social Security and
Medicare said the proposal would be ``stacking the deck'' against
recipients.
   The American Association of Retired Persons said the rule change,
if adopted, appears to violate the spirit of the Social Security
program.
   The proposal by the agency's Office of Hearings and Appeals has
not yet been reviewed by Social Security Commissioner Dorcas Hardy,
said agency spokesman Phil Gambino.
   Under the proposed rule change, people who are challenging the
denial of benefits would be required to submit all of their evidence
in advance of a hearing before an administrative law judge, he said
Tuesday.
   Currently, new evidence may be submitted during the hearing, but
Gambino said the proposal would allow that only if new information
had come to light too late to be produced ahead of time.
   Also, Gambino said a pre-hearing meeting would be required in an
effort to outline the areas of disagreement.
   Gambino said the proposal was ``just a brainstorming idea'' and
is expected to go through several governmental levels before a final
decision is made.
   The current appeals process can last four to six months, Gambino
said. About half of all cases are reversed on appeal.
   Ken Hoagland, spokesman for the National Committee to Preserve
Social Security and Medicare, said Social Security was ``trying to
stack the deck against disability appeal claimants.''
   ``They are tyring to change the rules. If you can't win under the
rules of evidence that exist now, change the rules. It's stacking
the deck, that's what it is.''
   Martin Corry, AARP's Social Security staff specialist, said he
had not yet seen the draft of the notice of proposed rule-making.
   But, he said, AARP hopes that such a change would get the close
attention of Secretary of Health and Human Services Otis Bowen
because ``as a physician he would bring to that consideration
perhaps a better understanding of the potential harm that could be
done to disabled persons.''
   ``Older and disabled persons have earned their Social Security
and Medicare benefits and once again the administration is trying to
deny vulnerable citizens what they are entitled to,'' said Royball.
He said he finds it interesting that the proposed change is becoming
known the week after the election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
