<2ND_LINE>BC-Skyscraper Sold,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Houston's Heritage Plaza Sold For $110 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heritage Plaza, the downtown area's newest and
emptiest skyscraper, was sold for $110 million to a Houston-based
partnership whose major investor is the Michigan Employees
Retirement System.
   The 53-story tower was sold Tuesday by 261 Associates Ltd. to the
Coventry Fund III. Coventry Investment Group, a Houston investment
adviser, will manage the building as general partner.
   The Michigan pension fund and Laudio III, a Spanish investment
company using pension money from a Spanish pipe and steel company,
are limited partners.
   Heritage Plaza was completed in 1986 but has yet to attract a
large tenant. Only 8 percent of the 1.2-million-square-foot plaza is
occupied, Coventry officials said.
   The 1 million square feet of space available to lease is the
largest contiguous block of new, high-quality office space downtown.
The new owners said a $5 million renovation is planned for the
property, along with an aggressive leasing program.
   Texaco Inc. and several other companies have been shopping for
large blocks of office space downtown, said R.F. Howard, president
of DMH Properties, a newly formed unit of Coventry.
   Coventry, however, had declined to enter into any lease
negotiations until the purchase was closed, Howard said.
</TEXT>
