<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in a continuation of the price
slide that began late last week.
   Crop futures prices have closed lower in three of the last four
sessions and today's lower opening was ``just follow-through from
the liquidation taking place,'' said Ted Mao, grain specialist with
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   The Agriculture Department's announcement late Tuesday of the
sale of 1.2 million metric tons of corn to the Soviet Union had been
expected and had little effect on prices this morning, analysts said.
   And while the decline in U.S. grain prices appeared to be
generating some new buying interest in Europe, it will take a much
larger boost in demand to propel prices higher, Mao said.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 2\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.13{ a bushel; corn was
unchanged to { cent lower with December at $2.65{ a bushel; oats
were { cent lower across the board with December at $2.09{ a bushel;
and soybeans were 1{ cents lower to { cent higher with November at
$7.42 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were lower in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .02 cent to .23 cent lower with December at
73.12 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .25 cent lower
with November at 81.95 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent to .20
cent lower with December at 40.95 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .52 cent to .92 cent lower with February at 44.25 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled sharply higher on Tuesday. Pork futures
also advanced.
</TEXT>
