<HEAD>Japan's Sony Corp. Posts 174.8 Percent Gain In Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sony Corp. on Wednesday said its profit nearly
tripled in the latest quarter as sales climbed 46.3 percent.
   The Japanese consumer electronics company said its results were
helped by cost-cutting and rises in domestic and overseas sales in
all product groups, including its record operations, which were
augmented by the acquisition of CBS Records Inc.
   In the second quarter of its fiscal year, Sony said net earnings
rose to 13.1 billion yen, or $97 million at current exchange rates,
from 4.762 billion yen a year earlier. Revenue rose to 529 billion
yen, or $4.39 billion, from a revised 361.358 billion yen a year
earlier.
   In the first half of its fiscal year, the company said it had net
earnings of 29.2 billion yen, or $216 million, more than triple the
profit of 8 billion yen a year earlier. Revenue rose 41.9 percent to
992 billion yen, or $7.35 billion, from 699 billion yen a year
earlier.
   By market, sales inside Japan rose 42.2 percent, sales to the
United States rose 39.4 percent, sales to Europe rose 54.1 percent
and sales to other regions rose 58.8 percent. Sony does about a
third of its business in Japan and just under a third in the United
States.
   Dollar equivalents are calculated on the basis of 135 yen to the
dollar, the rate prevailing at the end of the reporting period.
</TEXT>
