<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BoeingOrder 1stLd-Writethru   11-16 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Boeing Order, 1st Ld-Writethru,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Australian Concern Orders 22 Boeing Jetliners</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with additional details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ansett Worldwide Aviation Services, an Australian
leasing group, has ordered 22 Boeing jetliners worth approximately
$1.12 billion, Boeing Commercial Airplanes confirmed Wednesday.
   So far this year, an industry-record 595 Boeing commercial jets
have been ordered, valued at $28 billion.
   The latest order is for six 767-300 extended range widebody jets
and 16 mid-sized 757s, plus options on an additional seven 767
aircraft, said Boeing spokesman Tom Cole.
   Cole said the airplane manufacturer was not releasing an exact
price for the order, at Ansett's request. However, a 757 is worth
approximately $44 million and a 767-300 sells for around $70 million.
   The 757s will be powered by Rolls-Royce RB211-535E4 engines, in a
deal worth approximately $318 million to the British engine firm.
Engines for the 767-300s will be announced later, Boeing said.
   Ansett Worldwide is the leasing arm of TNT Ltd. and The News
Corp. Ltd., which also owns Ansett Airlines and East West Airlines
in Australia.
   Deliveries of the 767s will start in October 1990 and continue
through 1993. Ansett has reserved the right to substitute smaller
767-200 or shorter-range 767-300 aircraft if it choses.
   Ansett also will start receiving its new 757s in October 1990,
and will continue to do so through 1995. Some of the 757s may be
delivered in a freighter configuration, the carrier said.
   The twin-engined 757 holds about 186 passengers and can fly up to
about 4,000 miles. The 767-300ER, also a two-engine plane, can carry
261 people 6,200 miles.
   The order brings to 353 the number of 767s ordered to date and
the number of 757s ordered to 387.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
