<1ST_LINE>r f BC-GTEHeadquarters     11-16 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-GTE Headquarters,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GTE Selects Dallas Suburb for Telephone Headquarters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK GODICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IRVING, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GTE Corp. said Wednesday it has selected
this suburb of Dallas for the consolidated general office
headquarters of its biggest division, telephone operations.
   Kent Foster, group vice president of GTE telephone operations,
said the communications company would transfer 3,000 employees from
all over the country to temporary office space here beginning in
January 1989. The move also was expected to create 1,000 new GTE
jobs here, company officials said.
   GTE will build a one million square-foot ``campus-like facility''
on a 112-acre site in the Las Colinas business development area. The
facility will house more than 4,000 employees and will be ready for
occupancy in mid-1991.
   Other sites under consideration were Tampa, Fla., Thousand Oaks,
Calif. and Westfield, Ind.
   The selection by the Stamford, Conn.-based communications giant
was the latest of several corporate moves to the Dallas-Fort Worth
area.
   AMR Corp., parent of American Airlines, moved to nearby Fort
Worth about five years ago and J.C. Penney Co. Inc. is in the
process of moving its headquarters to the Dallas suburb of Plano.
Both formerly were based in New York City.
   Six days ago, the federal government picked a site just south of
Dallas to build the ``super collider'' project. The $4.4 billion
high-energy physics project also is expected to generate thousands
of jobs.
   GTE began restructuring its telephone operations in March.
Telephone operations account for $12 billion of GTE's $15 billion in
annual revenue.
   So far, the business has been restructured into three groups _
the mobile communications unit, which will be located in Houston
with 1,000 employees; the information services unit, which will be
moved to Tampa, Fla, with its more than 5,800 employees, and the
local telephone service unit.
   The telephone operating group, which is composed of the three
units, has a total of 91,600 domestic employees.
   The company has 1,100 employees at its corporate headquarters in
Stamford, 300 of whom are in the telephone operating group. The
company is keeping its corporate headquarters in Stamford.
   James L. Broadhead, who was president of GTE Telephone Operations
until recently, said in a recent interview that 3,000 to 4,000
people of an estimated 15,000 to 20,000 employed by the local
service unit around the country will work in the telephone
headquarters operation.
</TEXT>
