<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grains Close Lower; Soybeans Advance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures closed mostly lower while soybean
futures finished slightly higher Wednesday on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Analysts said the quiet session appeared to mark the end of the
recent selling wave.
   ``It looks like a lot of the liquidation has run its course; it
looks like the market is finally finding some support at these lower
levels,'' said Ted Mao, grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. in New York.
   Grain and soybean prices had declined in three of the previous
four trading sessions as the market reflected dismay at the
relatively slow pace of grain sales for export.
   The Soviet Union's purchase this week of at least 1.5 million
metric tons of U.S. corn helped steady the corn market, analysts
said, and the general drop in prices appeared to be generating some
new buying interest in Europe.
   At the close, wheat was 3\ cents lower to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.10{ a bushel; corn was 2
cents lower to \ cent higher with December at $2.64} a bushel; oats
were 1{ cents to 4{ cents lower with December at $2.05{ a bushel;
and soybeans were \ cent to 2{ cents higher with November at $7.46 a
bushel.
