<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1521EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Trade-Dollar Bjt   11-16 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade-Dollar, Bjt,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sentiments _ For Now _ Are Against U.S. Currency</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar's rapid slide toward 40-year lows
illustrates the truth of a favorite maxim of traders: ``The trend is
your friend.''
   The sharp drop of the dollar on Wednesday was attributed to the
government's trade deficit report, but a bigger factor was probably
the general bearish mood in the markets.
   As long as the trend in the dollar appeared to be downward, few
traders were willing to buy dollars even if they happened to believe
the trade report was fundamentally good for the U.S. currency.
   If the market's mood had been more positive, it is possible the
dollar might have rallied in response to the same Commerce
Department report of a $10.5 billion merchandise trade deficit for
the month of September.
   ``Traders don't care what's going to happen next week. They care
about today or tomorrow,'' said Shafiqul Islam, a senior fellow for
finance at the Council on Foreign Relations in Washington.
   This is not to say that currency exchange rates have nothing to
do with fundamental factors, such as trade patterns, inflation and
economic growth. But since economists and government leaders cannot
agree on what the rates really should be, there is plenty of room
for speculation.
   The dollar on Wednesday neared its lowest point against the
Japanese yen since the establishment of modern exchange rates in the
late 1940s. It fell to 122.4 yen and 1.723 West German marks, a
decline of more than 8 percent against the yen and 7 percent against
the mark since early October.
   Ironically, in early October the dollar was rising so powerfully
that central banks were striving to slow its ascent by selling
dollars in the open market. In a complete reversal, the Federal
Reserve on Wednesday was buying dollars to support the currency.
   It doesn't matter to traders whether the dollar rises or falls,
as long as it does not move sideways. Often traders, sitting at
their computer screens, will sell dollars into a dull market just to
see if they can start a chain reaction.
   ``Exchange markets are horrified by the idea of the stability of
exchange rates,'' said Islam.
   Big banks in Japan, Europe and the United States dominate the
world foreign-exchange markets, trading currencies both for clients
and for their own accounts. When currency rates are stable, their
business dries up.
   Foreign-exchange trading is ``becoming an increasing line item in
banks' profits,'' said Brent Erensel, an analyst for Donaldson
Lufkin & Jenrette Securities Corp. ``It's fairly profitable.''
   The steep decline of the U.S. currency has many traders
explaining why the dollar should be falling, focusing mainly on the
massive U.S. trade deficit.
   The explanations may well be correct. But only last month, when
the dollar was surging upward, some of these same traders were
offering explanations to justify the rise.
   The truth is that traders care more about buying low and selling
high than they care about debates among economists over whether the
dollar is fundamentally overvalued or undervalued.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Peter Coy covers trade and technology for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
