<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1614EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-India-CocaCola     11-16 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-India-Coca Cola,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coca-Cola Applies to Set Up Production Unit in India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coca-Cola Co. applied to the Indian
government Wednesday for permission to set up a production unit in a
free trade zone near the capital, the company announced.
   The unit would manufacture ingredients for Coca-Cola concentrate
to be sold in markets outside India, according to a company
statement. But the company planned limited domestic sales of the
products, in accordance with rules governing export production in
free trade zones, the statement said.
   ``The project, if approved, would make India an important new
supply base for the company's expanding international operations,''
the statement said.
   The unit would cost the company 33 million rupees, or about $2.2
million, the statement said.
   Free trade zones are government-designated areas where companies
can set up manufacturing units with substantial tax and excise
reductions if most of the produce is exported.
   Coca-Cola withdrew from India in 1977 rather than follow
government directives to dilute its ownership and reveal its secret
formula.
   At that time, it had been operating for 27 years and had licensed
at least 20 companies to bottle its soft drinks.
   The Coca-Cola bid comes almost two months after Pepsico Inc. was
allowed to sell its soft drinks in Indian markets. In September, the
government approved a venture between Pepsico and two Indian
companies to produce processed foods and soft-drink concentrate.
   The Pepsico soft drinks are not expected on the market for at
least two years. The company made its proposal to the government in
June 1986, but it was not approved until two years later.
   Coca-Cola, based in Atlanta, and Pepsico, based in Purchase,
N.Y., are the bigest soft drink makers in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
