<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade-Autos, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0154,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Rep Rejects Michigan Unfair Auto Trade Petition</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 new grafs after 9th graf pvs, The trdae ... to
UPDATE with Blanchard, parts manufacturers reax. Picks up 10th graf
pvs bgng, Michigan's petition ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michigan's request for federal protection from
Canadian automotive trade practices was rejected Wednesday by the
U.S. trade representative, who said state officials had no right to
file such a petition.
   Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter, in his decision, also said
the state's request had been superceded by a free-trade agreement
negotiated between the United States and Canada.
   Michigan Gov. James Blanchard asked Yeutter last month to declare
that Canada's duty-remissions program constituted an unfair and
illegal trade practice that discriminates against U.S. automotive
manufacturers.
   Under the program, Canada gives duty rebates on autos to foreign
manufacturers in return for the use of Canadian parts in their cars.
   The free-trade agreement, which is awaiting Canadian
parliamentary approval, would allow the Canadian rebate programs to
remain in place through 1996, a time-span U.S. critics say would
enable Canadian parts suppliers to build long-term ties with
foreign-owned manufacturers.
   ``Both the Free Trade Agreement and the U.S. legislation to
implement the agreeement specifically address the issue complained
of in the petition,'' Yeutter said. ``So (an) investigation now is
simply not appropriate.''
   He also said the law gives government officials no right to file
petitions under the legal provision cited by Michigan.
   ``The law is designed instead for petitions by private parties
that have a direct economic stake in the issues,'' Yeutter said.
   The trade representative has never accepted a petition under that
seciton of the law ``filed solely by a government official,'' he
said.
   Blanchard said he rejected Yeutter's contention that Michigan had
no right to file a petition.
   ``Nothing in the law or in the trade representative's own
implementing regulations precludes a state from filing a complaint
against unfair and illegal trade practices,'' Blanchard said. ``They
speak only to parties with `significant economic interest',
something which the state of Michigan has in this matter.''
   The director of the American Automotive Parts Association, a
trade group representing U.S. parts manufacturers, said his
organization was considering filing a petition of its own on behalf
of its members.
   Michigan's petition argued that the program discriminated against
U.S. parts purchases and amounted to an illegal subsidy of exports
of Canadian parts to the United States and other nations through
their inclusion in third-country automobiles.
   Canada gave $2.2 million in automotive duty remissions in its
1986-1987 fiscal year, and the practice would cost U.S. parts
manufacturers an estimated $132 million in business in 1990, the
state said.
   Large Japanese automakers, such as Honda, Nissan and Toyota,
benefited from the program in 1986 and 1987, the state said.
   The agreement has been approved by the Congress but was under
heavy attack in Canada's Parliament by opposition parties that
feared economic and cultural absorption of their nation by its large
southern neighbor.
   The issue figures heavily in the campaign leading up to Canada's
national elections on Monday.
</TEXT>
