<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Seaway-Coal     11-16 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seaway-Coal,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Coal Exports Through Seaway To Hit Six-Year High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. coal exports from Great Lakes ports
traveling though the St. Lawrence Seaway more than tripled from
April through October compared with a year ago, seaway officials
said Wednesday.
   They said U.S. coal exports reached 569,000 metric tons from
April through October, compared with 165,000 metric tons for the
same period a year ago.
   The officials expressed optimism that the increase in coal
exports though the inland waterway will continue, resulting in a
six-year high at the end of the 1988 shipping season.
   The announcement came about a week after the seaway reported a
record amount of U.S. export steel would move through the channel by
yearend.
   U.S. coal exports through the seaway for all of 1987 totaled
234,000 metric tons. In 1985 and 1986, the highest years for coal
shipments through the seaway since 1982, coal exports just exceeded
600,000 tons each year. The 1982 total was 1.1 million metric tons.
   Spurring the demand for American-mined coal were: the lower value
of the dollar; competitive worldwide ocean freight rates; a tight
supply due to a series of industrial disputes last summer in
Australia; sanctions against using South African coal; and
production problems and rising production costs in Poland, the
seaway said in a news release.
   James L. Emery, administrator of the Saint Lawrence Seaway
Development Corp., which operates the U.S. portion of the
American-Canadian channel, credited 1986 seaway trade mission stops
in Norway and Denmark. The majority of U.S. export coal through the
system so far this year has been transported to Denmark for power
production, he said.
   ``Our visits to those countries provided Great Lakes coal
representatives the chance to build relationships with those looking
to buy coal,'' Emery said in a statement. ``No sooner did we get
back to the U.S. when our people in coal went back over to close new
deals.''
   Canada Steamshp Lines Inc., which participated in the 1986 trade
mission, has transported the majority of the coal through the seaway
this season, according to the release. As of Oct 31, it had moved
nearly 500,000 metric tons of U.S. coal from Lake Erie ports.
   Nationally, 1988 U.S. coal exports as of Aug. 31 totaled 52.2
million metric tons, up 15 percent from the same period last year,
according to the National Coal Association.
   The seaway begins at the mouth of the St. Lawrence River and runs
through the Great Lakes, ending 2,342 miles later at Duluth, Minn.
</TEXT>
