<1ST_LINE>u f AM-SteelImports 1stLd-Writethru f0151 11-16 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steel Imports, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0151,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Imports Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, Both groups ... to CORRECT that September
total is down from August but up from a year ago.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel imports rose 8.2 percent to 16.1 million
tons in the first three quarters of the year compared with the same
period of 1987, two steel industry trade groups reported Wednesday.
   The American Iron and Steel Institute of Washington, D.C., which
represents U.S. steelmakers, said the 1988 imports thus far
represented 20.6 percent of the U.S. market, down from 21.2 percent
in the first three quarters of 1987.
   The American Institute for Imported Steel Inc. of New York, which
represents 70 leading steel importers, said imports for the first
nine months included 2.3 million tons of semifinished steel bound
for U.S. mills. Excluding the semifinished steel, the AIIS
calculated raw steel imports at 17.7 percent of the U.S. market.
   Both groups reported September steel imports, including
semifinished steel, at 1.6 million tons, representing about 19.7
percent of the U.S. market. The September figure is down from 1.8
million tons in August but up from 1.56 million tons in September
1987.
   The Reagan administration's Voluntary Restraints Agreements
import program seeks imports no higher than about 20.2 percent of
the apparent U.S. market. President-elect George Bush has promised
to extend the program beyond its current expiration on Sept. 30,
1989.
</TEXT>
