<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-16 0810</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0839</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cocoa Futures Surge On Rumors of Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocoa futures prices surged Wednesday on New York's Coffee, Sugar
& Cocoa Exchange on rumors that the Ivory Coast and France had
reached an agreement to withhold a large amount of new-crop Ivorian
cocoa beans from the world market.
   On other exchanges, silver futures sagged but gold was little
changed; copper futures retreated; stock-index futures plunged;
grains were lower; soybeans were higher; and livestock, meat and
energy futures were mixed.
   Rumors of an impending cocoa pact between France and the Ivory
Coast have kept the cocoa market on edge for weeks. But on
Wednesday, the agreement was said to have been finalized and an
announcement was expected at any time.
   Cocoa settled $35 to $59 higher with the contract for delivery in
December at $1,392 per metric ton. The rally erased all of the
previous day's sharp losses.
   The Ivory Coast's policy of withholding its prized cocoa from the
market in an attempt to force prices higher hit a snag this fall
when the West African nation ran short of storage space for its
newly harvested crop, analysts said.
   The former French colony appealed to the French government and
has reportedly been negotiating for France's cooperation on a new
withholding plan.
   ``I would say they are very close to an agreement and may indeed
have reached one today,'' said Sandra Kaul, cocoa market analyst
with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago.
   She said she did not know the details, but it was rumored that a
large Paris-based trading house would buy a large quantity of
Ivorian cocoa, which it would withhold from the world market by
government command.
   Analyst Kim Badenhop of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New
York said the amount to be withheld from the market was rumored to
be 400,000 metric tons _ slightly less than two-thirds of the Ivory
Coast's new crop.
   ``That's taking a lot of cocoa off the market and the market's
been responding to that,'' he said.
   The speculation went that the Ivorians would try to sell the
remainder of their cocoa at prices above the world market price.
   But analysts said few market players expected the scheme to work.
   ``They won't be able to withhold as much as they want off the
market or to maintain the high asking price,'' Ms. Kaul said. ``No
one will give them money unless they drop their prices.''
   Silver futures slumped on New York's Commodity Exchange after
independent professional traders tried and failed to rally the price
for March delivery up to $6.60 a troy ounce, said Bernard Savaiko,
an analyst with PaineWebber Inc. in New York.
   Gold was little changed despite the weakening of the dollar, a
bullish cue for precious metals.
   Gold settled unchanged to 40 cents higher with December at
$425.60 a troy ounce; silver was 9.3 cents lower across the board
with December at $6.30 a troy ounce.
   Near-month copper futures finished lower for the fourth time in
the last five sessions, but Savaiko said the selling was technically
motivated and supply-demand factors remained bullish.
   Copper settled 1.9 cents lower to 1.5 cents higher with December
at $1.28 a pound and the spot November contract at $1.35 a pound.
   Stock-index futures fell sharply on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange on fears that the Federal Reserve Board would respond to
signs of rising inflation by raising interest rates, analysts said.
   The contract for December delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
settled 4.45 points lower at 265.05.
   Grain futures settled mostly lower while soybeans finished mostly
higher on the Chicago Board of Trade in a quiet session that
appeared to mark the end of the recent selling wave, analysts said.
   Wheat settled 3 cents lower to 2 cents higher with December at
$4.10} a bushel; corn was unchanged to 2 cents lower with December
at $2.64\ a bushel; oats were 3\ cents to 5 cents lower with
December at $2.05\ a bushel; and soybeans were 1 cent lower to 4
cents higher with November at $7.44\ a bushel.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle settled .10 cent
lower to .20 cent higher with December at 73.25 cents a pound;
feeder cattle were .23 cent lower to .02 cent higher with November
at 81.95 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent lower to .25 cent
higher with December at 41.35 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .42 cent to .70 cent lower with February at 44.45 cents a pound.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, West Texas Intermediate
crude oil settled unchanged to 32 cents lower with December at
$13.67 a barrel; heating oil was .01 cent lower to .09 cent higher
with December at 44.47 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .46
cent lower to .30 cent higher with December at 46.50 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
