<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Plessey Bjt   11-16 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plessey, Bjt,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GEC, Siemens Launch $3 Billion Takeover Bid for Plessey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's General Electric Co. PLC and Siemens AG
of West Germany launched a $3 billion takeover bid Wednesday for
electronics rival Plessey Co. PLC. Plessey promptly rejected the
offer.
   The bidders said competition from America and Asia made the
merger vital for the European electronics industry.
   GEC, which is unrelated to the U.S.-based General Electric Co.,
and Siemens offered 225 pence, or $4.07, a share for all of
Plessey's stock.
   But Plessey said it ``emphatically'' rejected the offer and
strongly recommended that its shareholders take no action on the bid.
   Its shares jumped 54 pence, or 97 cents, a share to 230 pence, or
$4.16, on the London Stock Exchange soon after the announcement.
   The bidders said in a statement that they were forming a joint
company, GEC Siemens PLC, to make the offer to Plessey.
   In the statement, they cited the approach of the 1992 removal of
trade barriers within the 12-country European Economic Community.
   ``Unless EC companies work together to make the most of available
European resources, they increasingly risk dependence on U.S. and
Japanese technology to retain any real market presence, even in the
short term,'' the statement said.
   GEC made a hostile 1.2 billion-pound bid for Plessey in 1986, but
the British government blocked it, saying the combination would grab
too large a slice of the British defense electronics business. The
bid was worth about $2 billion at the time.
   Following the failure of that bid, GEC and Plessey agreed to a
friendly merger of their telecommunications businesses, setting up
GEC Plessey Telecommunications Holdings Ltd., also known as GPT.
   But Siemens and GEC said the escalating cost of research and
development, scarce technical and managerial resources and
``relentless competition'' from the Far East and North America
prompted them to make the new bid.
   They said that if the bid succeeded, Siemens would take a
40-percent stake in GPT, with GEC holding the balance, and would
work together on telecommunications research and development.
   GPT and Siemens will maintain their existing telecommunications
product lines, particularly GPT's System X telephone switching
system and Siemens' EWSD switching system. But GPT and Siemens hope
successor systems will be developed jointly.
   ``Collaboration will encompass new products for the EC market,
and in particular for the massive U.S. market, where both companies
(GPT and Siemens) have achieved only limited success to date,'' GEC
and Siemens said.
   GEC plans to take a 50-percent stake in Siemens' defense
electronics business and a 51-percent stake in Plessey's recently
acquired U.S. defense electronics interests. Plessey agreed in July
to buy the defense interests of Singer Co. for $310 million.
   To allay any government concerns about a monopoly, the statement
said, Plessey will continue to operate as a separate entity in
Europe but will be able to call on Siemens products and technology.
</TEXT>
