<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 1754EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Interco     11-16 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Interco,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Raleses Say They're Close to Abandoning $2.7 Billion Hostile Bid
for Interco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group waging a $2.7 billion hostile
takeover bid for Interco Inc. said it was close to scrapping the bid
late Wednesday because of the furniture-apparel company's stiff
resistance.
   Cardinal Acquisition Corp., a group controlled by Mitchell and
Steven Rales of Washington, D.C., said it was preparing to abandon a
$74-a-share cash tender offer as of midnight EST and return all
tendered shares, which amounted to nearly 90 percent of the
company's 35.56 million shares outstanding.
   Interco's stock price fell $1.87{ a share to $63.37{ in composite
New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Cardinal's announcement came two days after Interco, a St.
Louis-based maker and seller of products including Florsheim shoes,
London Fog raincoats and Ethan Allen furniture, rejected another
request for negotiations.
   Interco also indicated at that time that it planned to undertake
a defensive restructuring, which includes payment of a special
dividend and the sale of some of its major businesses, even if
Cardinal dropped its offer.
   Abandoning the bid would end the Rales' four-month fight to
acquire Interco, which has rebuffed their maneuvers since an initial
$64-a-share offer they made in July.
   Interco responded with a defensive restructuring plan that would
cost $2.8 billion, pay shareholders a special dividend, plunge the
company into debt and require the sale of some businesses to help
pay it off.
   The battle also extended into the courts of Delaware, where
Interco is incorporated, when the Rales sought to invalidate a
so-called ``poison pill'' company bylaw that would make a hostile
purchase prohibitively expensive.
   Although the Delaware Chancery Court prohibited Interco from
using the poison pill defense in a ruling earlier this month, the
company appealed to the state supreme court, which agreed to hear
the matter Nov. 30.
   The Raleses have indicated previously they would not buy any
Interco shares until the issue was resolved.
   Interco employs about 54,000 people nationwide and had sales of
$3.34 billion last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
