<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Polaroid-Shamrock     11-16 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polaroid-Shamrock,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polaroid, Shamrock Trial Nearing End</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Polaroid Corp. ended
his testimony Wednesday as the trial in which the instant
camera-maker is hoping to fend off a hostile takeover drew closer to
an end.
   Under cross examination, Chairman I. MacAllister Booth defended
Polaroid's employee stock ownership plan that would all but block a
takeover because it puts 14 percent of Polaroid's stock in the hands
of employees.
   Booth reiterated earlier testimony that the plan was put in place
to give workers ``a piece of the rock'' and increase the company's
financial performance.
   Shamrock Holdings Inc. filed suit in Delaware Chancery Court and
is asking Vice Chancellor Carolyn Berger to overturn the
10-million-share, $300 million stock plan.
   Shamrock is controlled by the Disney family and is based in
Burbank, Calif. On July 19, Shamrock made a friendly $40-a-share bid
that was rejected. It later made a hostile bid at $42 per share.
   Polaroid, which is based in Cambridge, Mass., but incorporated in
Delaware, has urged its shareholders to reject the hostile bid. The
takeover hinges on the outcome of the trial.
   Ms. Berger is expected to rule soon on whether there will be
further testimony.
</TEXT>
