<FILEID>AP-NR-11-16-88 2057EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Shipbuilding     11-16 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shipbuilding,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Morrison Knudsen Discussing Sale of Shipbuilding Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morrison Knudsen Corp. has begun
``substantive negotiations'' with a management-led group of
employees interested in buying its National Steel and Shipbuilding
Co. subsidiary.
   The San Diego-based subsidiary accounted for $19.9 million of
Morrison Knudsen's $55 million loss in operating income during the
first nine months of this year, Morrison Knudsen spokesman Vern
Nelson said Wednesday.
   During the same period, National Steel and Shipbuilding's revenue
of $133 million represented less than 10 percent of Morrison
Knudsen's $1.5 billion in revenue.
   ``We believe the sale of NASSCO would be in the best interests of
the employees, as well as those of the community of San Diego and
(Morrison Knudsen),'' William Agee, chairman, president and chief
executive officer of Morrison Knudsen, said in a statement.
   He said the transaction is subject to working out terms of a
definitive sales agreement, as well as the resolution of contract
issues between Morrison Knudsen and the Department of the Navy.
   ``It would save jobs and benefit San Diego, important objectives
for us,'' Agee said. ``To that end, we're doing everything possible
to reach a timely and fair resolution in our discussions both with
the NASSCO executive team and the Navy.''
   No details were released, but Agee said Morrison Knudsen probably
would retain a minority ownership position in NASSCO. Any such
transaction would result in a one-time charge against Morrison
Knudsen's earnings, he said.
   NASSCO posted operating income of $900,000 during the first
quarter of 1988, but lost $19.9 million in the second quarter and
another $900,000 during the third quarter, which ended Oct. 30.
   The Navy recently exercised an option to have NASSCO build a
second fast combat support ship. When that work is fully underway,
the company expects to be employing about 2,500 people.
   Morrison Knudsen is a major construction, engineering and
shipbuilding corporation with headquarters in Boise, Idaho.
</TEXT>
