<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Holly-Tyson     11-16 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holly-Tyson,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tyson, Holly Farms Execs Meet, No Resolution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top officials of Holly Farms Corp. and
rival poultry producer Tyson Foods Inc. have met to discuss Tyson's
proposed $941 million buyout offer but no decisions were reached, a
Tyson spokesman said Wednesday.
   Tyson, the nation's largest poultry producer, has been trying
since Oct. 18 to take over Holly Farms, but directors of the
Memphis-based company have spurned those advances.
   In its latest bid, Tyson offered $52 a share for Holly Farms'
18.1 million shares of common stock. Tyson has made the $941 million
offer directly to Holly Farms stockholders but still is seeking the
blessing of the company's board of directors.
   The rejections of Tyson's offers have been curt, and Holly Farms
president Lee Taylor reportedly has refused to return phone calls to
Tyson chairman Don Tyson of Springdale, Ark.
   But Bob Justice, a spokesman for Tyson, said the two executives
and their top assistants met Tuesday in Memphis.
   ``We're pleased with the meeting as far as Mr. Tyson is
concerned,'' Justice said.
   Ted Bailey, a spokesman for Holly Farms, confirmed that the
meeting took place but declined comment on what was discussed.
   ``The Tyson people were at our office yesterday,'' he said.
   Bailey also declined to say if other meetings are planned, but
Justice said Holly Farms' officers have agreed to present their
board of directors with Tyson's offer.
   ``We were assured that the information and the discussions
between the two companies would be provided to the board of
directors,'' Justice said.
   Bailey declined to say if a board meeting was scheduled.
   Tyson's offer expires Nov. 18.
   In trading Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange, Holly Farms
fell 75 cents a share to $52.75.
   Justice said Tyson will continue its takeover efforts whether the
Holly Farms board approves the deal or not.
   Holly Farms is a diversified foods company with about half of its
sales in chicken. The company had total sales of $1.6 billion last
year.
   Tyson had gross sales last year of $1.8 billion.
</TEXT>
