<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Multifoods     11-16 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Multifoods,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Multifoods Buys Stake From Former Suitor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Multifoods Corp. has paid $53.8
million to buy back the 12.1 percent of its stock held by a group
led by Bregman Partners of Toronto, Ontario, the food company
announced Wednesday.
   Multifoods has paid $30.75 a share for 1,751,000 shares of
Multifoods common stock previously owned by Bregman Partners and its
affiliates, which last year indicated it might acquire up to 24.9
percent of the company's stock.
   Multifoods stock closed Wednesday at $30.62{, down 37{ cents a
share in New York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   Multifoods could repurchase up to 500,000 additional shares of
its common stock under a plan approved by the board of directors,
the company said.
   Bregman Partners never made a tender offer to acquire Multifoods,
but it said more than a year ago in a filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission that it intended to buy more than 24.9 percent
of Multifoods' outstanding shares.
   According to its most recent SEC filing, Bregman had purchased
only 12.1 percent of the shares.
   ``To the best of our knowledge we have purchased all of their
holdings,'' said Linda Berg, a Multifoods spokeswoman. ``You never
knew what their motives were.''
   Bregman Partners, which includes the Belzberg banking family of
Vancouver, British Columbia, could not be reached for comment. The
investment group earlier had suggested that Multifoods restructure
its business but Multifoods Chairman Andre Gillette rejected the
idea as a ``misleading and thinly disguised self-serving effort.''
   In late July, the Canadian group proposed a restructuring in
which Multifoods would sell its U.S. grain merchandising, Mister
Donut chain and Canadian operations other than industrial and
consumer flour opeations to raise $120 million.
   The partnership also proposed that the company borrow $270
million and pay a special dividend of $28 in cash plus $6 in notes
to the holders of its 14.6 million shares.
   In rejecting the offer, Gillet proposed then to buy back the
stock held by the partnership for $32 a share, the closing price of
the stock on the previous day.
   Multifoods, which nearly doubled its earnings from continuing
operations in fiscal 1988, has divested itself of its regional
consumer food companies and flour mills in the United States in the
past three years. It also has acquired and consolidated companies
that have given it a prominent position in the production and
distribution of food for the hospitality industry and vending
machines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
